ot and killed a suspected \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  Tuesday night northwest of Sells on the Tohono O'odham Nation.\par \par \uc2 The shooting occurred at about 8 p.m. near Milepost 97 on Arizona 86, Tohono O'odham Police Chief Joseph Delgado said in an email.\par \par \uc2 The man from Rio Hondo, Guatemala, was 28, said Julia Guzman, the consul general of Guatemala in Phoenix. She withheld the man's name until his family is notified.\par \par \uc2 The man was part of a group of crossers. Most of the people fled in different directions when they encountered the agents. The man who was shot, however, became combative, grabbing one of the agents' collapsible clubs and attacking agents and an agency dog, she said.\par \par \uc2 A Border Patrol agent fired a single round from his handgun, striking the man in the chest, she said. Efforts to resuscitate him were unsuccessful, and he was pronounced dead at 8:45 p.m.\par \par \uc2 Guzman spoke early Wednesday morning with seven other Guatemalans who were apprehended by the Border Patrol at the scene of the shooting. They told her they didn't know the man who was shot and didn't see the shooting because they were running away, she said.\par \par \uc2 Tohono O'odham police are leading the investigation with assistance from the FBI.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find extensive coverage of immigration issues at azstarnet.com/border\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020111214e7c80002o\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSON\par {\*\bkmkstart toc1}{\*\bkmkend toc1}\b \uc2 Ganan democratas en Tucson; revocan a Pearce del Senado\b0\par\par\uc2 LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSoN; ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,062 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 November 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par 20\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 El democrata Jonathan Rothschild sera el nuevo alcalde despues de recabar 55 por ciento de los votos contra el republicano Rick Grinnell, quien logro 40 por ciento en las elecciones locales.\par \par \uc2 En la carrera por el Concejo del Distrito 1, la concejal Regina Romero derroto a su rival del Partido Verde, Beryl Baker.\par \par \uc2 En el Distrito 2, el concejal Paul Cunningham, quien fue nombrado el ano pasado para llenar un puesto vacante en la Mesa Directiva, regira un periodo completo al ganarle a la republicana Jennifer Rawson.\par \par \uc2 Pero el resultado mas sorprendente en la eleccion se dio en Mesa, Arizona, donde el presidente del Senado estatal, Russell Pearce, fue destituido por los votantes del Distrito Electoral 18.\par \par \uc2 Pearce, el controversial republicano legislador que encabezo muchas de las leyes antiinmigrantes estatales, incluso la SB 1070, sera sustituido por el republicano Jerry Lewis.\par \par \uc2 En Tucson, el triunfo de Rothschild no fue sorprendente debido a la ventaja que le lleva el electorado democrata al republicano. Adicionalmente, Rothschild recaudo mas dinero que Grinnell.\par \par \uc2 La primera tarea de Rothschild sera restaurar la confianza en el gobierno local, que ha disminuido por el malgasto de dinero de Rio Nuevo, serios problemas con el sistema de 911, negocios cuestionables respecto al desarrollo del centro y robos en el programa de estacionamiento.\par \par \uc2 Mediante un plan de 180 dias, Rothschild prometio iniciar discusiones con empresas y designar a alguien en su oficina que funja como enlace con los pequenos empresarios.\par \par \uc2 En el discurso que pronuncio en una alegre celebracion democrata, Rothschild dijo que esta listo para trabajar jornadas de 14 horas y que va a convertir la oficina del Alcalde en la "maquinaria" que movilizara su plan.\par \par \uc2 Rothschild senalo que los desafios que enfrenta la ciudad son graves, como el envejecimiento de la infraestructura, una pobreza extrema y un sistema educativo que necesita mejoramientos.\par \par \uc2 Tom Volgy, un antiguo alcalde democrata que apoya a Rothschild, dijo que mensajes por el estilo en su campana le ayudaron a cortejar a los votantes.\par \par \uc2 "Esta claro que se dirigio a lo que los tucsonenses realmente quieren -una fuerte direccion, un enfasis en la economia y un alcalde activista que abogara por opciones viables".\par \par \uc2 Grinnell dijo que habia anticipado una carrera mas aguerrida, pero felicito a sus voluntarios por el gran esfuerzo que realizaron.\par \par \uc2 "No hay perdedores en este proceso", comento en una entrevista. Grinnell dijo que de todas formas continuara involucrado en la politica local.\par \par \uc2 "Es ironico, porque continuare participando de una forma u otra - ya sea como alcalde o en la Mesa Directiva de Rio Nuevo. Seguire en esto".\par \par \uc2 En Mesa, y a lo largo del estado, los criticos de Pearce celebraron su revocacion.\par \par \uc2 La primera eleccion de este tipo contra un legislador estatal en Arizona fue promovida por los detractores de Pearce, liderados por el grupo Ciudadanos por una mejor Arizona.\par \par \uc2 Pearce intentaba retener su escano por la localidad de Mesa frente a Lewis, pero finalmente se impuso el segundo con un 53 por ciento de apoyo frente al 45 por ciento de su rival, segun los resultados divulgados por la prensa local el Miercoles 9 de Noviembre.\par \par \uc2 El Martes 8 por la noche Pearce acepto la derrota en una comparecencia en la que estuvo acompanado por el alguacil del Condado Maricopa, Joe Arpaio, conocido por sus redadas antiinmigrantes.\par \par \uc2 En Julio pasado, las autoridades electorales del Condado certificaron mas de 10 mil del total de firmas recolectadas, y el grupo solo necesitaba un minimo de siete mil 756 para que Pearce se sometiera a voto.\par \par \uc2 Criticos de Pearce argumentaron que la obsesion del Senador con la inmigracion ilegal le ha hecho olvidar las urgencias economicas y educativas del estado, cuya imagen se ha visto danada por la SB 1070.\par \par \uc2 La agencia EFE contribuyo a esta nota.\par \par \uc2 Democrat Jonathan Rothschild will be Tucson's new mayor after he won 55 percent of the vote to Republican Rick Grinnell's 40 percent in the city's election.\par \par \uc2 And in the races for City Council Ward One, council member Regina Romero defeated Green Party challenger Beryl Baker. In Ward Two, Councilman Paul Cunningham, appointed to fill a vacant seat on the council last year, won a full term, defeating Republican challenger Jennifer Rawson.\par \par \uc2 But the biggest election result ocurred in Mesa Arizona where state Senator Russell Pearce was removed from office by voters in Legislative District 18.\par \par \uc2 Pearce, the controversial legislator who was the force behind many of the state's anti-\uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  laws, including SB 1070, will be replaced by Republican Jerry Lewis.\par \par \uc2 In Tucson, Rothschild's win didn't come as a surprise to most political observers because of the Democratic voter advantage over Republicans. Additionally, Rothschild raised more money than Grinnell.\par \par \uc2 Rothschild's first task will be to help restore trust in city government, which has been sorely tested given wasteful Rio Nuevo spending, serious glitches in the 911 system, questionable development deals downtown and thefts in the parking program.\par \par \uc2 In a 180-day plan, Rothschild pledged to launch discussions with business interests and establish a small-business liaison in the mayor's office.\par \par \uc2 Speaking at a joyful Democratic celebration at the Lodge on the Desert midtown hotel, Rothschild said he's ready to begin 14-hour days, saying he'd make the mayor's office "an engine room" to accomplish his plan.\par \par \uc2 Rothschild said the challenges facing the city are stark, from aging infrastructure to deep poverty and an education system that needs improvement. "Tomorrow morning, the real work begins."\par \par \uc2 Tom Volgy, a Rothschild ally and former Democratic mayor, said that kind of talk on the campaign trail helped Rothschild woo voters.\par \par \uc2 "It's clear that Jonathan appealed clearly to what Tucsonans really want and need - a stronger sense of direction, a stronger economic focus, and an emphasis on an activist mayor who will pursue real viable options for us."\par \par \uc2 Grinnell said he had anticipated a closer race, but complimented his volunteers for a strong effort. "There are no losers in this process," he said in an interview.\par \par \uc2 Grinnell said he'll still continue to be engaged in Tucson politics anyway.\par \par \uc2 "The irony is, I'm still involved one way or the other - either as mayor or on the Rio Nuevo Board. So it's not like I'm going anywhere."\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020111118e7bb0003j\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc2}{\*\bkmkend toc2}\b \uc2 Charges dropped against man in federal gun probe of '06-07\b0\par\par\uc2 TIM STELLER   \par \uc2 TIM STELLER, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 383 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 October 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 A federal prosecutor dismissed charges Thursday against Ricardo Mendez Jr., one of nine people charged as a result of the cross- border gun-smuggling investigation called Operation Wide Receiver.\par \par \uc2 That 2006-2007 Tucson investigation has become a topic of interest at a congressional committee investigating the more recent, Phoenix-based Operation Fast and Furious.\par \par \uc2 The dismissal occurred just five days before Mendez's trial was scheduled to begin in Tucson's U.S. District Court on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Mendez was a minor player amid the broader investigation, in which a Tucson firearms dealer sold hundreds of guns to "straw buyers" who sent them to criminal groups in Mexico. Mendez bought just one gun but did so alongside one of the lead defendants, Carlos Armando Celaya, who bought 21 guns that day in March 2007.\par \par \uc2 As recently as Monday, Assistant U.S. Attorney Laura Gwinn and defense attorney John Kaufmann appeared in federal court as U.S. District Judge David Bury decided pretrial motions.\par \par \uc2 Gwinn, a Justice Department prosecutor from Washington, D.C., said in a document filed Thursday that she spoke with a co- defendant about Mendez after a recent plea deal was signed. That co- defendant - whom Kaufmann identified as Celaya - said Mendez was not part of the gun-trafficking conspiracy and had bought the gun for himself, Gwinn said in the filing.\par \par \uc2 Bury dismissed the case with prejudice, meaning it cannot be refiled.\par \par \uc2 Celaya pleaded guilty Oct. 12 to conspiring to illegally export firearms, making false statements and providing a firearm to an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 . In the plea agreement, he acknowledged being part of a group that bought 282 firearms for buyers in Mexico, including his cousin in Sonora.\par \par \uc2 The House Oversight and Government Reform Committee is investigating Operation Fast and Furious, in which about 2,000 firearms were sold to people intending to sell them to criminals in Mexico. The earlier Operation Wide Receiver resulted in 400 to 500 firearms going to Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Tim Steller at 807-8427 or at tsteller@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Follow the news and events at Pima County's courthouses in Kim Smith's blog, At the Courthouse, at go.azstarnet.com/courthouse\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020111110e7as0000b\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc3}{\*\bkmkend toc3}\b \uc2 Former migrant's incredible journey\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,465 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 October 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Road to citizenship points him toward social-justice work\par \par \uc2 The immigration judge's question was simple: "Why should I let you stay?"\par \par \uc2 Leo Guardado had arrived illegally in Los Angeles as a 9-year- old boy, fleeing with his mother from their war-torn village in El Salvador. But by 2001 he was a college freshman, tired of hiding his immigration status from classmates and professors. And he was painfully aware that without a green card, he wouldn't be able work legally no matter how many degrees he earned.\par \par \uc2 So he and his mother decided to emerge from the shadows and seek legal sanctuary.\par \par \uc2 "I volunteer, I'm involved in the school, I'm involved in community, I do service, I'm going to college," Guardado told the judge. "I don't have a criminal record. I don't plan on having one. I will pay taxes when I actually can work."\par \par \uc2 He told judge Henry Ipema that he had finished second in his class at a prestigious Catholic high school in Los Angeles and earned a full scholarship to St. Mary's College of California. He laid out his life plan if allowed to stay in the U.S.\par \par \uc2 "I'll be a model citizen in ways that many citizens aren't," Guardado said. "I've proven that already without being a citizen."\par \par \uc2 In a rare occurrence in the U.S. immigration system, the judge granted them political asylum, and legal residency.\par \par \uc2 "He could have easily said, 'Great story, I feel for you but you've broken the law, please go back to El Salvador,' " Guardado said. "My future would have been vastly different."\par \par \uc2 In the decade since that decisive day - Dec. 22, 2001 - Guardado has lived up to the promise he made the judge. And his journey from the lush mountains of El Salvador through California, Indiana, New York and Europe has now brought him to Tucson.\par \par \uc2 At 29, he is the social ministry director at Most Holy Trinity Catholic Church, 1300 N. Greasewood Road.\par \par \uc2 An articulate, thoughtful and compassionate young man who is open about sharing his story as a former undocumented immigrant, Guardado seems out of central casting as an emerging leader in the nation's hot spot for border and immigration issues.\par \par \uc2 When faith-based leaders were deciding whether to offer sanctuary to a Tucson man facing deportation earlier this month, the Rev. Bill Remmel of the Most Holy Trinity Catholic Church gave Guardado a seat at the table.\par \par \uc2 "I really trust his judgment," Remmel said. "He's got such a good head on his shoulders."\par \par \uc2 Yet Guardado may be gone just as Tucson gets to know him. He is seriously considering life as a Trappist monk at a California monastery where he spent 10 months in 2005-2006.\par \par \uc2 Salvadoran childhood\par \par \uc2 A life of solitude and stillness may seem a peculiar choice for a man who has built his career on helping others. To understand the draw, you must go back to his childhood in the tiny village of Canton Tobias in northwest El Salvador.\par \par \uc2 Tucked into a mountainous region of El Salvador known as Chalatenango, Guardado's village of about 100 people was a place of peaceful jungles and a bloody civil war.\par \par \uc2 He climbed trees and swam in rivers. He enjoyed a simple life without running water or electricity. But he is haunted by memories of bodies in the street.\par \par \uc2 When he was nearing his 10th birthday - the age at which the guerrillas and government army were drafting boys - he and his mother fled.\par \par \uc2 Of their 26-day trek to Los Angeles, Guardado says he remembers "vignettes, not the entire narrative." He recalls walking under the moonlight, cramming into a fake compartment in a semitrailer and crossing a river by raft in the dark.\par \par \uc2 Once they crossed the border, they no longer had to walk in the moonlight - but their life in the shadows was just beginning.\par \par \uc2 Guardado could say two things in English when he arrived in this country: sorry and thank you.\par \par \uc2 A fast learner and a diligent student, he was fluent in English within 1 1/2 years, said his mother, Maria Guardado. Just as he had done in El Salvador, he earned straight As in school.\par \par \uc2 His potential caught the eye of Louis Moret, a prominent figure in the Democratic Party in Los Angeles who employed Maria Guardado to clean his house and help take care of his children.\par \par \uc2 Moret helped get Guardado into Cathedral High, a private all- boys Catholic school. Guardado never told anyone there that he had no Social Security number, and he made excuses when invited to represent the school at a youth gathering in England. He formed a profound but angry relationship with God, who he felt had set him up for so much success that would only be followed by failure.\par \par \uc2 "That cut at a deep level," he said.\par \par \uc2 Facing long odds to attend college because he didn't qualify for federal aid or in-state tuition, he set out a plan: Apply to wealthy, private liberal-arts colleges that wouldn't care about his immigration status and would have scholarships to fund his education.\par \par \uc2 It worked.\par \par \uc2 He was offered a full ride to Swarthmore College in Pennsylvania and St. Mary's College of California. The deciding factor: St. Mary's had a chapel open 24 hours a day.\par \par \uc2 "There's something beautiful to me about going into a church at 2 in the morning, and just being for a few minutes," he said.\par \par \uc2 Compassion runs deep\par \par \uc2 Compassion is deeply rooted in Guardado.\par \par \uc2 As a boy in El Salvador, he asked his mother for money, then walked over and gave it to a man without a leg.\par \par \uc2 In Los Angeles, he put pieces of tortilla in his backpack and fed them to stray dogs in the neighborhood.\par \par \uc2 "I don't think that desire to keep helping will ever die," his mother said in Spanish.\par \par \uc2 Guardado says he's drawn to social-justice work and ministry because he knows what it's like to need help from strangers - and get it.\par \par \uc2 "When you are a recipient of generosity on some level it creates a kinship moment with individuals who also might need help in your future," Guardado said. "That's not the kind of thing you forget."\par \par \uc2 He earned a bachelor's degree in religious studies from St. Mary's and a master's in theology from Notre Dame. In between, he spent a year in New York City, working with inner-city kids through the Lasallian Volunteer Program.\par \par \uc2 In 2008, he took a job in campus ministry at St. Mary's. But he became disillusioned when the college laid off janitors and other staff workers during the recession.\par \par \uc2 He knows a higher-paying field would help his mother, who is 60 years old and still cleans houses. But, he says of a corporate job, internally "it's not going to feed me."\par \par \uc2 Seeking inner peace\par \par \uc2 While he was still at St. Mary's, Guardado led student trips to the border. That's how he met the Rev. Remmel, who saw in Guardado intelligence, a keen grasp of theology - and something more.\par \par \uc2 "There's a tangible quality I can't put a name on," Remmel said. "Anyone I know that's met him seems to be able to immediately relate to him."\par \par \uc2 He has all the traits of an outstanding leader, said the Rev. John Fife, retired pastor at Southside Presbyterian Church and co- founder of the Sanctuary Movement of the 1980s. "Leo's going to make a substantial difference in the world before he's done."\par \par \uc2 Just months from his 30th birthday, Guardado now faces a decision about going to the monastery. Part of his desire is an unexplainable draw to the place, the people and the mystery of God, he says. The other attraction is to the stillness and rhythm of the life.\par \par \uc2 "I grew up climbing trees and swimming in rivers. I grew up playing on my own in the wilderness," he said. "I was then transplanted, to use the imagery, to a cement jungle in Los Angeles."\par \par \uc2 At the monastery, he says, "You till the land, you work the land. I think as I grow older, psychologically, it takes me back to my roots in El Salvador."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 If you go\par \par \uc2 * What: Leo Guardado, director of social ministry at Most Holy Trinity Catholic Church, will deliver a sermon about his journey from \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  to U.S. citizen and how the migrant experience relates to Scripture.\par \par \uc2 * Where: Southside Presbyterian Church, 317 W. 23rd St.\par \par \uc2 * When: 9:30 a.m. Sunday\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020111109e7am00009\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc4}{\*\bkmkend toc4}\b \uc2 US deportations set record even as those from AZ fall\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 790 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 October 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 The federal government deported nearly 400,000 people nationwide in the recently completed fiscal year - marking the 10th straight record year.\par \par \uc2 But bucking the national trend, deportations in Arizona dropped for the first time in five years - from 92,600 in 2010 to just less than 52,000 in fiscal 2011, statistics released Tuesday by U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement show. The fiscal year ended on Sept. 30.\par \par \uc2 For the first time in at least four years, Arizona did not lead the nation in deportations, said Immigration and Customs Enforcement spokesman Vincent Picard. It's unknown why there was a decrease, he said.\par \par \uc2 More than half of this year's deportees nationwide - nearly 217,000 - had felony or misdemeanor convictions, setting a 10-year high for the percentage of "criminal" illegal immigrants among total deportations, figures show.\par \par \uc2 The 396,906 deportations nationwide in fiscal 2011 represent a small increase from the 392,862 formally returned in fiscal 2010, the stats show. Deportations have ratcheted up under the Obama administration, with more than 389,000 deportations each of the past three years.\par \par \uc2 The 2011 total deportations are more than three times the total deportations made in fiscal 2001, government figures show.\par \par \uc2 The increase shows the agency is making progress in "smart and effective" immigration enforcement, Immigration and Customs Enforcement Director John Morton said.\par \par \uc2 "This comes down to focusing our resources as best we can on our priorities," Morton said. "We continue to hope for comprehensive immigration reform at a national level, working with the Congress, but in the meantime we work with the resources we have, under the laws we have."\par \par \uc2 The Obama administration has taken criticism from both sides of the immigration debate for rising deportation levels.\par \par \uc2 Republican border hawks and critics of the administration's immigration enforcement strategy call the deportation numbers inflated because they include people who voluntarily leave with no penalties and may be able to cross back into the country illegally.\par \par \uc2 Immigrant rights groups contend the government is unfairly targeting illegal immigrants who are not a menace to society, separating families and creating fear in immigrant communities.\par \par \uc2 "It's very worrisome because they are not just numbers, but real people and real families being torn apart," said the Rev. Alison Harrington of Tucson's Southside Presbyterian Church.\par \par \uc2 Lumping in deportees who have committed nonviolent crimes with violent crimes in the "criminal" \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  count is misleading, Harrington said. Some people are deported because of driving without a license or having reentered the United States after deportation, which can be a felony, she said.\par \par \uc2 Immigration and Customs Enforcement officials could not provide a comprehensive list of the crimes committed by deportees included in the criminal category. They also could not say how many of those crimes related to reentering the U.S. after being deported.\par \par \uc2 They only provided fiscal 2011 totals for these four categories:\par \par \uc2 * 1,119 convicted of homicide.\par \par \uc2 * 5,848 convicted of sexual offenses.\par \par \uc2 * 55,653 convicted of drug-related crimes.\par \par \uc2 * 35,927 convicted of driving under the influence.\par \par \uc2 That leaves 118,151 others in the criminal category with unknown crimes.\par \par \uc2 Two-thirds of the "noncriminal" illegal immigrants deported were recent illegal border crossers or repeat immigration violators, the agency said.\par \par \uc2 "The administration and ICE shouldn't be so proud of themselves," said Jennifer Allen, the director of Tucson-based Border Action Network. "Still nearly half of the people that have been taken out of this country have done nothing more than have immigration violations."\par \par \uc2 The total number of criminal illegal immigrants deported in fiscal 2011 was more than double the fiscal 2007 total and more than three times the the fiscal 2001 total.\par \par \uc2 The last time criminal illegal immigrants made up such a large portion was in fiscal 2002 when they accounted for 58 percent of the nearly 123,000 deportations. By comparison, only 31 to 35 percent of deportees were "criminals" in fiscal 2007-2009.\par \par \uc2 The percentage of criminal illegal immigrants in Arizona accounted for half of the total deportations.\par \par \uc2 More than 90 percent of fiscal 2011's deportations fell under Immigration and Customs Enforcement's priority groups: those who have broken criminal laws; recent border crossers; repeat immigration law violators; and fugitives from immigration court.\par \par \uc2 The breakdown of the countries of origin of the deportees was not available Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com. The Associated Press contributed to this story.\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Reporter Brady McCombs will answer your questions about illegal immigration and border security in a live online chat Thursday at noon. Go to azstarnet.com/borderchat to sign up for an email reminder.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020111104e7aj00025\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc5}{\*\bkmkend toc5}\b \uc2 Council to rewrite rules on remarks from the audience\b0\par\par\uc2 ROB O'DELL   \par \uc2 ROB O'DELL, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 749 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 September 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 The City Council agreed Tuesday to rewrite the rules for the weekly public call to the audience despite contending there's nothing wrong with their current policies that attempt to restrict what people can say.\par \par \uc2 Mayor Bob Walkup announced at the meeting a week ago that he was imposing new restrictions on what speakers can say at meetings, allowing him to prohibit criticism of the council and the city staff in the name of civility.\par \par \uc2 One speaker, anti-\uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  activist Roy Warden, was cut off from speaking and ejected from the meeting after making a reference to interim City Manager Richard Miranda.\par \par \uc2 This week, Councilman Steve Kozachik asked the council to rewrite the rules after the "unprecedented move" of shutting down speech last week.\par \par \uc2 He said the wording of the city's rule, which prohibits "personal, impertinent or slanderous remarks" or "boisterous" behavior, is too broad. Two First Amendment lawyers interviewed by the Arizona Daily Star last week had similar opinions.\par \par \uc2 Kozachik wanted new rules that mandate a speaker be warned before being cut off, and wanted to change the language to be less broad. "Speech rights come with a cost," he said.\par \par \uc2 He wanted to change the language so that speakers who make "statements which disrupt, disturb or otherwise impede the orderly conduct of the council meeting, including comments that are repetitive in nature, or whose speech reflects a clear and present danger, is obscene, libelous, slanderous or poses an imminent true threat" may be removed from the meeting.\par \par \uc2 City Attorney Mike Rankin said he would take Kozachik's language into consideration when he drafted the new rules, along with the rules and best practices from other cities and towns in Arizona.\par \par \uc2 He defended the city's rules, saying they were consistent with the rules of other Arizona cities and that they have been in place since 1982.\par \par \uc2 "What we can't do and won't do and haven't done is restrict speech based on viewpoint," Rankin said, adding that all the council has done has properly restricted the time, place and manner of speech. "What we have currently is well within the fold."\par \par \uc2 Councilwoman Karin Uhlich said she was "reticent to impose restrictions" on speech, but she said the council shouldn't have to put up with threats of violence or disruption. She said civility is a "core value" of Tucson, and that other attendees at the call to the audience shouldn't have to be "subjected to behavior or verbiage that is out of bounds."\par \par \uc2 Although she is a supporter of the First Amendment, Councilwoman Regina Romero said the council needs to provide a space for citizens where speakers follow rules of propriety and decorum. She said there are rules for behavior in front of children, in schools and even while sitting in traffic, so there are also rules for behavior in council meetings.\par \par \uc2 "We need to be able to provide a place that people feel safe," she said.\par \par \uc2 Walkup said he wants to start giving people warnings before cutting them off, give clearer rules for behaviors, and spell out on the speaker request forms more clearly what behavior is or isn't allowed.\par \par \uc2 The rules need some review and adjustment, Walkup said.\par \par \uc2 Warden, who touched off the controversy when he was cut off last week, spoke at Tuesday's call to the audience and continued his speech from the week before where he talked about Miranda and a lawsuit that he was involved in that the city lost.\par \par \uc2 Walkup let him speak, but after he finished, Walkup told him not to come next week and say the same thing because the city rules do not allow repetitive speech week to week. He warned Warden that he would be cut off if he said the same thing next week.\par \par \uc2 The city's rules do not prevent repetitive speech, however, and after first insisting they did, Walkup later relented after speaking with Rankin.\par \par \uc2 Rankin said Warden would be allowed to come back and make the same comments, at least until the city finalizes its rule changes.\par \par \uc2 Walkup insisted his intervention last week raised the civility of the call to the audience. "The demeanor was decidedly better," he said.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Rob O'Dell at 573-4346 or rodell@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Read more about local, state and national political news at azstarnet.com/politics\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020111012e79l0003r\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc6}{\*\bkmkend toc6}\b \uc2 Mayor's rules might violate free speech\b0\par\par\uc2 ROB O'DELL   \par \uc2 ROB O'DELL, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,104 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 September 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par C1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Limits on comments to council may be too vague, lawyers say\par \par \uc2 Mayor Bob Walkup announced last week he is imposing new restrictions on what speakers can say at Tucson City Council meetings - restrictions that allow him to shut down criticism of the council and city staff - in the name of civility.\par \par \uc2 Walkup announced the rules at the start of Tuesday's public call to the audience, and ejected one speaker after he made a reference to interim City Manager Richard Miranda.\par \par \uc2 Anti-\uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  activist Roy Warden had, at past meetings, unleashed a number of personal attacks on city officials, particularly Miranda. But on Tuesday he just said Miranda's name when the mayor cut him off. When Warden continued speaking, Walkup ordered police to remove him from the meeting.\par \par \uc2 Walkup said Warden violated city rules by saying Miranda's name, and he had the right to cut him off before the personal attacks started.\par \par \uc2 "That's what he did last week and that's what he did the week before," Walkup said. "That's where he was headed and I didn't even want him to start that attack."\par \par \uc2 But two First Amendment lawyers said once the council lets citizens speak at its meetings the city has a very limited ability to regulate what they say. They said the wording of the city's rules prohibiting "personal, impertinent or slanderous remarks" or "boisterous" behavior is too vague and too broad to restrict speech.\par \par \uc2 Civility has been a Walkup initiative in the wake of the Jan. 8 shootings, in which six people were killed and 13 where wounded, including U.S. Rep. Gabrielle Giffords. He sponsored a Civility Accord signed by nearly 250 mayors at January's U.S. Conference of Mayors, pledging to support more respectful discourse.\par \par \uc2 But until Tuesday Walkup had not made those voluntary principles mandatory for speakers addressing the council.\par \par \uc2 After the mayor read the "new" rules Tuesday, City Attorney Mike Rankin said anyone violating the rules could be ejected from the meeting.\par \par \uc2 Warden, who made his name burning Mexican flags at immigration rallies, objected to the new rules and then pointed at Miranda - who just took over as the city's interim top executive - and started to speak about his involvement in a lawsuit the city lost.\par \par \uc2 But before Warden could continue, Walkup told him his time to speak was over and called in the police when he refused to stop.\par \par \uc2 As Warden was being taken out he questioned whether he was being arrested - he wasn't. He called Miranda an unprintable name as he was being taken away.\par \par \uc2 Warden later said in an email to the Star that he intends to sue over being removed.\par \par \uc2 Defense Attorney Michael Bloom, who has tried several First Amendment cases, said he does not support Warden and finds Warden's "opinions and remarks are frequently disgusting." Still, Bloom said he has "serious concerns about people being silenced and removed from meetings based solely upon the content of their statements."\par \par \uc2 "I don't think that's appropriate and I also don't think it's legal," he said.\par \par \uc2 Bloom, who watched the video of Warden being ejected, noted that under the council's rules, "citizens can be silenced and removed if they make remarks that are 'personal.' "\par \par \uc2 "The Constitution demands that people can only be removed from public meetings for violating clear, objective standards," Bloom said. The council's current standards "are too vague and subjective, and allow people to be removed just because their remarks are unpopular."\par \par \uc2 Dan Barr, attorney for the First Amendment Coalition or Arizona, who also watched the video, said the city's rules "have problems under the First Amendment."\par \par \uc2 Cities don't have to have a call to the audience at their meetings, Barr said, but if they do they can't regulate the content of people's speech. He said the city's rules are "over-broad and vague," calling them more aspirational guidelines than justification for removing speakers from a meeting.\par \par \uc2 The city can limit how long people can speak, and prevent disruptive or unruly speech - such as rampant cursing, disruptions during the meetings, or threats, he said, but not the content of comments.\par \par \uc2 "If you're going to allow a call to the public you can't limit them based on something you disagree with," Barr said. "Is it so vague that civility means agreeing with the City Council?"\par \par \uc2 Rankin said the city rules have been in place for years and are the same as those of many Arizona cities and towns.\par \par \uc2 He said it is up to the mayor to decide what speech doesn't meet the rules, although he said he would step in if the mayor got "too aggressive."\par \par \uc2 Although Warden had not made any personal attacks Tuesday before the mayor cut him off, Rankin said Warden's previous comments were part of the "context" that justified removing him. "It was clear where he was going," Rankin said.\par \par \uc2 This is the second recent incident in which speaker comments at a government hearing have raised questions.\par \par \uc2 Last month a speaker at a Tucson Unified School District meeting had to be told to leave his knife in his vehicle before entering. Once inside, he made a number of inflammatory comments about Hispanics, bloodshed and war that many perceived as threats, and verbally attacked a board member's father.\par \par \uc2 Then-chairman Mark Stegeman was criticized for letting the man continue to speak after warning him to tone it down.\par \par \uc2 Although Warden's past comments have been offensive to many, they didn't include specific threats.\par \par \uc2 Councilman Steve Kozachik initially said he was OK with the mayor's action because "people in the room have a right to a higher level of discourse" than listening to what he called Warden's offensive and racist attacks.\par \par \uc2 But Kozachik later said he wants a study session discussion of the issue because he is concerned about potentially stepping on free- speech rights, although he pointed out he's no supporter of Warden's.\par \par \uc2 Councilwoman Karin Uhlich said bullying or threatening comments can create an environment in which other people don't feel safe.\par \par \uc2 "In this instance, and more broadly in Tucson, there is a concern about dialogue that devolves into threats and personal attacks," she said.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Rob O'Dell at 573-4346 or rodell@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Go to azstarnet.com/news/local/govt-and-politics to read more about local and state government and political news.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020111012e79i00024\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc7}{\*\bkmkend toc7}\b \uc2 Immigrant arrests nearing 40-year low\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,763 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 September 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Steep drop linked to many factors, including border buildup, US recession, capture policies\par \par \uc2 Arrests of illegal immigrants trying to cross the U.S.-Mexico border have fallen to levels not seen since the early 1970s.\par \par \uc2 With one month left in fiscal year 2011, the Border Patrol has apprehended nearly 305,000 illegal border crossers across the Southwest border. That puts the final year total on pace to be the lowest since 1972, when 321,000 apprehensions were made.\par \par \uc2 By comparison, the agency made 852,500 to 1.6 million apprehensions each year from 1983 to 2007 along the Southwest border before the sharp downturn in the last four years.\par \par \uc2 The precipitous decline is the latest measure to suggest illegal immigration, especially from Mexico, has fallen substantially.\par \par \uc2 The number of people leaving Mexico dropped by 60 percent from 2006 to 2010, according to a July report from the Pew Hispanic Center based on analysis of Mexican government data. The estimated number of illegal immigrants living in the United States has dropped to 11.2 million since reaching a peak of 12 million in 2007, found a February report from the Pew Hispanic Center.\par \par \uc2 Many immigration analysts say the U.S. recession - the worst in a quarter century - is the most likely cause of the slowdown. With fewer jobs available, it's probable would-be crossers are being warned by family and friends already here that the trip north is not worth the money or the peril, said Rey Koslowski, associate professor of political science, public policy and informatics at the University at Albany-SUNY in New York.\par \par \uc2 Federal border officials acknowledge the economy is a factor. However, they note the decline demonstrates that the two-decade- long buildup of agents, barriers, roads and technology across the border - along with the gradual reduction of the old 'catch and release' policy - is working.\par \par \uc2 Apprehensions began decreasing in 2007 before the economic recession began in March 2008, Alan Bersin, U.S. Customs and Border Protection commissioner, points out.\par \par \uc2 The "enforcement posture is greater than we've ever had," Bersin said this week while visiting Tucson. "The results are beginning to show."\par \par \uc2 In its recent report about fewer Mexicans leaving their homeland, the Pew Hispanic Center said factors in both the U.S. and Mexico are likely the cause. The report cited declining job opportunities and increased border enforcement in the U.S., and recent conomic growth in Mexico that may have reduced the "push" factors.\par \par \uc2 In the Tucson Sector - the busiest for illegal border crossings since 1998 - apprehensions are on pace to be as low as 1994, when 139,473 were made. The sector remains the busiest of the nine on the Southwest border, but only accounts for 38 percent of all Southwest border apprehensions this fiscal year, down from 44 percent to 47 percent from 2007 to 2009.\par \par \uc2 Bersin's goal is to see apprehensions in the Tucson Sector below 100,000, which hasn't happened since 1993.\par \par \uc2 He won't go as far as to predict when that will happen, but said it's now a matter of when - not if - arrests will drop that low.\par \par \uc2 "The fat lady hasn't sung in Arizona yet," Bersin said, "but I can hear her tuning up."\par \par \uc2 Imperfect Measurement\par \par \uc2 Using the Border Patrol's apprehensions statistics to gauge illegal immigration rates has been likened to judging a baseball player by his hits without knowing how many times he's been at bat.\par \par \uc2 Because the figures only reflect arrests and not how many people made it into the United States successfully, Koslowski cautions not to put too much stock in the border-arrest figures.\par \par \uc2 "In terms of apprehensions reflecting in any way flows of illegal migrants, it all depends on how many are getting past per apprehension," said Koslowksi, who is also a non-resident fellow at the Migration Policy Institute.\par \par \uc2 This "get-away" figure has historically been vague.\par \par \uc2 Bersin said the estimate he used as U.S. attorney in San Diego in the mid-1990s - that two people get past agents for every one caught - is outdated.\par \par \uc2 With an array of technology, aerial surveillance and more agents than ever, he said, the agency detects far more illegal entries and catches a greater percentage of them.\par \par \uc2 In most parts of the U.S.-Mexico border, including the Yuma, San Diego and El Paso sectors, agents are catching more than 90 percent of illegal crossers, he said.\par \par \uc2 In the Tucson Sector, agents are catching at least 70 percent of them, he said.\par \par \uc2 A rise in what the agency calls the "effectiveness ratio" makes the apprehensions figures more indicative of the \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  traffic than in past decades, Bersin said.\par \par \uc2 But the other drawback of using apprehensions as a gauge is that they count the arrest rather than track the person. For example, a person caught three times in one year is tallied as three apprehensions.\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol tracks how many times each \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  is caught, but that information is not made public.\par \par \uc2 "You have to be very careful about extrapolating in any way the flow of illegal migrants into the country," said Koslowski, noting the arrest data the agency keeps secret.\par \par \uc2 While apprehension rates are an imperfect measure of illegal immigration flow, the slowdown is likely real, said Steve Camarota, director of research for the Center for Immigration Studies, a Washington-based organization that advocates for slowing immigration.\par \par \uc2 The decline began as far back as the summer of 2008, Camarota said, based on his analysis of the U.S. Census Population Survey data.\par \par \uc2 "Fewer folks are coming, and more are leaving," Camarota said. "This means that what was once thought to be inexorable is not."\par \par \uc2 It's important to remember, though, that a slowdown of border crossings may not mean all flow of illegal immigrants has declined proportionately, he said. In 2006, the Pew Hispanic Center estimated that as many as 45 percent of the then-12 million illegal immigrants in the United States overstayed non-immigrant visas after entering through legal ports of entry.\par \par \uc2 More consequences\par \par \uc2 As recently as the mid-2000s, the majority of illegal border crossers were dropped off at the nearest border city, often within hours of their arrest.\par \par \uc2 About four years ago, the Border Patrol ratcheted up its efforts to end this 'catch and return' policy by implementing and expanding a set of programs that levied consequences against more and more illegal border crossers.\par \par \uc2 Some illegal immigrants face a criminal charge of illegal entry in federal court, which could result in jail time. Other arrestees get deported hundreds of miles away from where they were caught in an effort to disrupt the smuggling route. During the summer months, many illegal immigrants are flown home to Mexico City.\par \par \uc2 With the exception of some juveniles and some humanitarian cases, every person caught crossing illegally into Arizona faces some type of consequence today, Bersin said.\par \par \uc2 "We say on the voluntary returns, 'no mas,'" Bersin said. "We are out of the voluntary return business."\par \par \uc2 With fewer arrests, federal officials have been able to prosecute a larger percentage of apprehended illegal immigrants each year since 2006, information from the Transactional Records Access Clearinghouse at Syracuse University shows.\par \par \uc2 Through the first half of fiscal 2011, the Border Patrol had referred 46,125 illegal border crossers for prosecution, which represents 19 percent of total apprehensions made through that time. That was up from 16 percent in fiscal 2010 and 2 percent in fiscal 2006.\par \par \uc2 Bersin considers what he calls the 'consequence delivery system' the fourth pillar of the current border security strategy, along with agents, border barriers and roads and technology.\par \par \uc2 The threat of incarceration or being sent to border states far from where they crossed into the U.S. is absolutely a deterrent for would-be crossers, said Koslowski, the University at Albany professor.\par \par \uc2 "With the tougher border controls, the prices goes up," Koslowski said. "As the cost goes up, fewer will attempt to do it."\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol wants all would-be crossers to know about the increased consequences. Bersin said the agency is hammering home that point through media in the five Mexican states that are home to the most illegal immigrants who come through the Tucson Sector: Puebla, Guerrero, Oaxaca, Sonora and Mexico State.\par \par \uc2 "It is a no longer a game of cat and mouse," Bersin said. "You get caught, you will be punished and a sanction will be levied against you."\par \par \uc2 The campaign also includes a warning about the risks of crossing the border.\par \par \uc2 "We're telling people that it's dangerous to come across this border," Bersin said.\par \par \uc2 "The coyotes (smugglers) are now controlled by organized crime, so even if you don't die in the desert, you will run the risk of being exploited."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Read more about border-related issues in Brady McCombs' blog, Border Boletin, at go.azstarnet.com/borderboletin\par \par \uc2 No decline in border deaths\par \par \uc2 The number of illegal border crossers found dead each year in Arizona's desert has not decreased along with the apprehensions.\par \par \uc2 The disparity suggests that illegal immigrants trying to cross Arizona's desert face a deadlier trek than ever.\par \par \uc2 The rate of death - the number of bodies found per 100,000 Border Patrol apprehensions - has been on the rise for the last decade. Even with a decrease in deaths in 2011, following a record-setting 2010, the rate has increased again.\par \par \uc2 Through the first 11 months of fiscal year 2011, there were 144 known deaths per 100,000 apprehensions in the area covered in the U.S. Border Patrol's Tucson Sector, the Arizona Daily Star's border death database indicates.\par \par \uc2 That's up from 119 known deaths per 100,000 apprehensions in 2010; 39 known deaths per 100,000 apprehensions in 2004; and three per 100,000 apprehensions in 1998.\par \par \uc2 By the numbers: Border buildup\par \par \uc2 Agents\par \par \uc2 18,415\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol agents on the U.S.-Mexico border today.\par \par \uc2 3,555\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol agents on the U.S.-Mexico border in 1992.\par \par \uc2 Barriers\par \par \uc2 649\par \par \uc2 miles of border fences and vehicle barriers on the U.S.-Mexico border today.\par \par \uc2 143\par \par \uc2 miles of border fences and vehicle barriers on the U.S.-Mexico border in 2006.\par \par \uc2 Budget\par \par \uc2 $11.4 billion\par \par \uc2 budget for Customs and Border Protection, the Department of Homeland Security agency responsible for border security, in fiscal year 2010\par \par \uc2 $6 billion\par \par \uc2 budget for Customs and Border Protection fiscal year 2004\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110922e7940005r\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc8}{\*\bkmkend toc8}\b \uc2 Eurofresh admits 17 employees were illegal\b0\par\par\uc2 TONY DAVIS   \par \uc2 TONY DAVIS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,010 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 August 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 But ex-HR boss, in '07 guilty plea, said more than 1,000 were hired\par \par \uc2 Willcox-based tomato-grower \uc2 Eurofresh Inc\uc2 . pleaded guilty Friday to knowingly hiring and continuing to employ "at least 17" illegal immigrants in supervisory-level positions.\par \par \uc2 The company also agreed to pay $600,000 in forfeitures to the federal government over the next five years, and to be on probation until the money is paid.\par \par \uc2 The plea agreement was reached between Eurofresh and the U.S. Attorney's Office after an investigation dating to the past decade into the company's hiring practices. The investigation was conducted by the Department of Homeland Security, Immigration and Customs Enforcement and federal prosecutors.\par \par \uc2 There are contradictory statements about the case, however, between Eurofresh, its plea agreement and its former human- resources director. Those contradictions pertain to how many employees were illegally hired, precisely when that hiring occurred, and whether top Eurofresh officials knew of the illegal hiring at that time, or whether it was done by their then-human-resources director, Kenneth Ward, without their knowledge.\par \par \uc2 Ward pleaded guilty to similar federal charges in 2007 and is awaiting sentencing. In his guilty plea, he alleged that four top company officials, whom he didn't name, knew of the illegal hiring and that the number of employees illegally hired was more than 1,000.\par \par \uc2 But Eurofresh's CEO, \uc2 Johan van den Berg\uc2 , denied all those allegations in response to questions Friday from the Star. Van den Berg said Ward was fired more than four years ago after the company learned he had been bringing in \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  employees without higher officials' knowledge.\par \par \uc2 The new plea agreement says Eurofresh admitted that from about August 2000 until December 2006, the company, through its human- resources director, "engaged in a pattern and practice of hiring or employing unauthorized workers" from Mexico because of labor shortages at the Eurofresh farms. Such shortages are a common problem for commercial farmers in the United States.\par \par \uc2 "This judgment is a message to other employers who engage in illegal practices that there is a real cost to their actions," said U.S. Attorney Dennis K. Burke in a news release Friday.\par \par \uc2 Friday's plea agreement does not say directly whether the company's top management knew of the 