ures represents. The new plea agreement said that payment is to compensate for the money Eurofresh earned from the hiring of 17 illegal immigrants from Mexico over the last decade for supervisory jobs. Van den Berg said later, however, that the company does not agree that the $600,000 is an amount directly related to the violations. Rather, it is a negotiated amount between Eurofresh and the Justice Department, he said.\par \par \uc2 In his comments Friday, van den Berg said all 17 of the illegally hired workers obtained proper work visas and kept working for Eurofresh after the infractions were reported. Nine of those employees still work for Eurofresh while the rest went on to work for other employers, he said.\par \par \uc2 Since the illegal hiring was discovered, Eurofresh has implemented tight systems and regular audits to prevent illegal immigrants from obtaining jobs there, van den Berg told the Star. In addition, the company has for more than three years used the Federal E-Verify system, an electronic system that almost 250,000 companies rely on to ensure that new employees aren't in the U.S. illegally, he said.\par \par \uc2 "The Eurofresh management team is diligent about conducting business with the utmost attention to ethical and legal practices," van den Berg said. "Eurofresh management and leadership teams regret that a former employee conducted these wrongful hiring practices, as we believe it is our duty to demonstrate leadership by example. We will continue to operate with the highest standards in our industry."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Tony Davis at tdavis@azstarnet.com or 806-7746.\par \par \uc2 DID YOU KNOW?\par \par \uc2 Eurofresh calls itself this country's leading year-round producer and marketer of greenhouse tomatoes, and says it employs more than 1,100 people and operates on 318 acres in Willcox and Snowflake.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110921e78r00034\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc9}{\*\bkmkend toc9}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 517 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 July 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par B8\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Driver, 84, errs; car rams store, hurting 1\par \par \uc2 A shopper was injured Saturday afternoon when a car crashed into a Green Valley \uc2 Safeway\uc2  store, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 The person who was struck was hospitalized. Two other people were hit with debris after the car plowed into the supermarket at 260 W. Continental Road.\par \par \uc2 The 84-year-old driver was parking her car when she put her foot on the accelerator instead of the brake, said Deputy Dawn Barkman, a Pima County Sheriff's Department spokeswoman. She was not injured, Barkman said.\par \par \uc2 No tickets were issued as of Saturday afternoon, she said.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 Man killed by car ID'd as city resident, 71\par \par \uc2 A pedestrian struck and killed by a car Friday night has been identified as Joseph E. Montano, 71, of Tucson.\par \par \uc2 When he was hit on West Ajo Way just west of South Holiday Isle, Montano was not in a crosswalk, Tucson police said.\par \par \uc2 Alex Dalenberg\par \par \uc2 Two local children saved from drowning\par \par \uc2 Two young children nearly drowned Saturday in family swimming pools, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 The first incident occurred when a 2-year-old girl fell into a pool while roughhousing with siblings.\par \par \uc2 The Drexel Heights Fire District responded to the home in the 3900 block of South Palant Drive, near West Bopp and South San Joaquin roads, said Tracy Koslowski of the Drexel Heights Fire District.\par \par \uc2 When firefighters arrived, the girl was conscious after her parents performed CPR on her, Koslowski said.\par \par \uc2 The second incident took place at a home in the 8100 block of East Quartz Ridge Drive, said Capt. Trish Tracy of the Tucson Fire Department.\par \par \uc2 A father was watching his 3-year-old son in the pool, and after he turned his head for about 10 seconds, the boy was at the bottom of the pool, Tracy said said.\par \par \uc2 He was pulled out and vomited water about 30 seconds later.\par \par \uc2 Both children were taken to a hospital for observation.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 Alleged smuggler faces charges in two deaths\par \par \uc2 A Mexican man is facing federal charges after authorities said he left two illegal immigrants to die in the desert.\par \par \uc2 Marcos Soto-Mendoza, 41, was arrested Thursday on charges of human smuggling resulting in death after U.S. Border Patrol agents found two bodies in the desert on the Tohono O'odham Nation near Sells.\par \par \uc2 Soto-Mendoza was reportedly leading five illegal immigrants through the desert when he abandoned two of them, who succumbed to dehydration.\par \par \uc2 After someone found the group and called the Border Patrol, agents took Soto-Mendoza into custody and rescued the remaining immigrants, all of whom needed medical assistance.\par \par \uc2 It was the second arrest in a week related to human smuggling resulting in death. Border Patrol agents took Gaspar Osorio- Carbajal into custody June 23 after authorities said an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  in his group was left to die in the desert heat.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the city of Tucson, updated every morning with the previous day's data, at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110713e7730007o\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc10}{\*\bkmkend toc10}\b \uc2 Many in S. Ariz. fire zone blame border crossers\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,673 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 June 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 The two largest wildfires burning in Southern Arizona originated in rugged, mountainous corridors frequently used by cross-border people and drug smugglers.\par \par \uc2 And the U.S. Forest Service has determined that both fires were human-caused.\par \par \uc2 So even though the investigations remain open, speculation is ablaze that illegal immigrants or smugglers are responsible for the Horseshoe 2 Fire northeast of Douglas and the Murphy Complex Fire northwest of Nogales.\par \par \uc2 "It's definitely not caused by somebody on a picnic whose wiener overcooked," resident Brad Titcomb said about the Murphy Fire, which came within a mile of his house in the Aliso Springs neighborhood west of Tubac. "This is illegal traffic one way or another."\par \par \uc2 At a press conference last week, Coronado National Forest supervisor Jim Upchurch said causes of fires include ricocheting bullets, campfires, welding equipment and possibly ignition by smugglers or illegal immigrants. But when asked specifically about the Horseshoe 2 and Murphy Complex fires, Forest Service officials say only that they are human-caused and under investigation.\par \par \uc2 The Horseshoe 2 Fire has burned 128,652 acres in the Chiricahua Mountains - including three homes and six buildings. The Murphy Complex Fire has burned 68,033 acres in the Tumacacori and Atascosa mountains - including the historic Atascosa Lookout.\par \par \uc2 Both rank among the top 10 largest wildfires in Arizona since 1990, shows information from the Southwest Coordination Center, which manages firefighting activities in the Southwest.\par \par \uc2 Don't expect definitive answers on who set the blazes - many human-caused fire cases are never solved.\par \par \uc2 Finding the culprit is daunting for fire investigators, said Pat Schneider, an assistant U.S. attorney in Arizona for the past 20 years who has experience on cases stemming from wildfires including the well-known Rodeo-Chediski Fire of 2002.\par \par \uc2 More than 70 percent of Arizona is federal land and the number of law enforcement officers is limited, he said. And wildfires believed to be caused by people are frequent - 142 fires of more than 100 acres in Arizona from 2003 to 2010, show data from the Southwest Coordination Center.\par \par \uc2 "Many times, the cases we are able to make and prosecute are when the suspect is caught in the act or soon thereafter, or because someone from the public helps as our eyes and ears," Schneider said. "The problem with fire, depending on how it burns, is that many times fire destroys a lot of evidence that was there."\par \par \uc2 The U.S. Attorney's Office in Arizona has handled just a few wildfire cases each of the past two years, he said. He didn't recall any prosecution of illegal immigrants in connection with wildfires.\par \par \uc2 Pinpointing a cause\par \par \uc2 Annual fire reports from government agencies focus solely on how many fires were caused by people versus lightning, said Carrie Templin, spokeswoman with the Bureau of Land Management.\par \par \uc2 The Horseshoe Fire, which started on May 31, 2010, and burned 3,400 acres in the Chiricahua Mountains northeast of Douglas, remains under investigation, said Coronado Forest spokeswoman Heidi Schewel.\par \par \uc2 Like the Horseshoe 2 Fire, there was no lightning in the area, so both are classified as human-caused.\par \par \uc2 With fires presumed to be started by people, the focus is on finding a specific cause - not on determining where the people were from, said Mary Zabinski, fire information officer at the Southwest Coordination Center.\par \par \uc2 Cause of fires in Southeastern Arizona include sparks from electrical equipment and tailpipes, matches and cigarettes and sometimes strange occurrences, such as a bear getting electrocuted on a power pole and falling to the ground on fire, Zabinski said.\par \par \uc2 But the most common cause of fires, in Arizona and nationwide, is abandoned campfires, Zabinski said. Officials often see a rash of them on holiday weekends.\par \par \uc2 The Murphy Complex Fire was started on May 30 - Memorial Day. That was not lost on Jim Cumming, who lives in a house west of Rio Rico built by his family in 1946.\par \par \uc2 "If you are betting odds, it was probably caused by illegal immigrants," Cumming said about the Murphy Complex Fire. "But being that it was caused on Memorial Day, it could have been caused by a camper. It's anybody's guess who started it."\par \par \uc2 Hot spot for crossers\par \par \uc2 The Murphy Complex Fire is burning west of Nogales, stretching from south of the international border to about 18 miles northwest of Tubac. It is the combination of two blazes that met up: the Pajarita and Murphy fires.\par \par \uc2 The flames are raging right in the heart of a smuggling corridor commonly used by drug runners and rip crews.\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol agent Brian Terry was fatally shot in the same area during a shootout between agents and suspected border bandits on Dec. 14, 2010. The corridor has been a hot spot for confrontations between smugglers and criminals dating back to 2007.\par \par \uc2 Hikers, hunters and outdoor enthusiasts sometime go up there, but the area is primarily used by drug smugglers and illegal immigrants, said Lt. Raoul Rodriguez of the Santa Cruz County Sheriff's Office. That's why he believes it's fair to speculate they started this most recent fire.\par \par \uc2 Cumming doesn't believe the fire was started intentionally, whether by illegal immigrants or U.S. citizens.\par \par \uc2 "It was definitely human-caused," Cumming said, "but by human error."\par \par \uc2 Smugglers don't generally set fires purposely as diversions, said Border Patrol Tucson Sector spokesman Mario Escalante.\par \par \uc2 But they regularly make fires to cook, or to keep warm during the colder months, said Brandon Judd, president of Local 2544 of the National Border Patrol Council, the union representing agents in Arizona. In the areas where the Murphy Complex Fire and Horseshoe 2 Fire started, the only people agents encounter are illegal immigrants or drug smugglers, he said.\par \par \uc2 "We definitely believe that the majority of these fires are started by illegal aliens," Judd said.\par \par \uc2 At the height of the Murphy Complex Fire, firefighters laid a fire retardant 100 yards from area resident Titcomb's ranch-style house he's owned for 15 years in Aliso Springs.\par \par \uc2 "This really hit home, I thought we were going to lose the house," said Titcomb, a native of Nogales, Ariz. "For what, so some guy can smuggle pot or meth?"\par \par \uc2 Titcomb is frustrated that officials only report such fires as human-caused and ignore the reality that some are likely started by smugglers and illegal immigrants. The political sensitivity of border issues scares politicians from talking about the truth, he said.\par \par \uc2 One theory percolating in the Tubac/Rio Rico area is that the Murphy Fire was started by two illegal immigrants in distress.\par \par \uc2 But Titcomb finds that theory hard to believe because all somebody would have to do to get help is walk down from the mountains to the numerous houses nearby. And since it was set in late May, it also seems unlikely it was to keep a group warm.\par \par \uc2 He believes it's more likely that drug smugglers set a fire in the area to burn Border Patrol sensors, a theory he heard from several firefighters. Most of the Border Patrol agents he sees in the area say they are responding to sensors, he said.\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol officials declined to discuss the cause of the Murphy Fire, citing the ongoing Forest Service investigation. Judd, of the union, said he hasn't heard of smugglers burning sensors, but said it might be a new tactic.\par \par \uc2 "It could be effective, sure," Judd said.\par \par \uc2 Focus on loss, not culprit\par \par \uc2 The Horseshoe 2 Fire started May 8, about 35 miles north of the U.S.-Mexico border in the Chiricahua Mountains of Southeastern Arizona.\par \par \uc2 The mountain range and the valleys surrounding it are commonly used by those smuggling drugs and people. Cochise County rancher Robert Krentz was killed in March 2010 on his property south of the fire. The case is still unsolved but authorities believe he was shot by a cross-border smuggler.\par \par \uc2 The Burro Springs area where the fire started is a popular staging area for smugglers, brimming with backpacks and trash left behind, said Ed Ashurst, who manages the 10X Ranch in the valley east of the Chiricahuas. There are propane tanks used to cook up there, he said. It's rugged, mountainous terrain only accessible by foot or horseback.\par \par \uc2 "It's frequented by nobody except illegal aliens," Ashurst said. "Virtually everyone down here believes an illegal alien started it (the fire). Who else started it?"\par \par \uc2 He said he believes the first Horseshoe Fire in 2010 was also started by illegal immigrants but he doesn't expect Forest Service officials to admit that. The Obama administration doesn't want to say it was an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  because that would bring into question its claims that the border is more secure than ever, Ashurst said.\par \par \uc2 Ashurst and others have heard that Border Patrol agents tracked four illegal border crossers to the start of the Horseshoe 2 Fire, and that the first Forest Service firefighters spotted the same tracks, he said.\par \par \uc2 His fellow ranchers west of Nogales have told him the Murphy Fire was also caused by illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 But few believe the cases will be solved, which is why area resident Cumming thinks it's a waste of energy to focus on who started the fire. The focus should be on what to do about the tremendous loss of mature trees and habitat for thousands of animals, he said.\par \par \uc2 "This fire has been real devastating," Cumming said. "To sit back and place blame about who caused it is moot."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet. com. Star reporters Tom Beal and Doug Kreutz contributed to this story.\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: For the latest news, photos and video on Arizona wildfires go to azstarnet.com/wildfire\par \par \uc2 By the numbers\par \par \uc2 Officials say these two AZ fires are human-caused and under investigation.\par \par \uc2 128,652\par \par \uc2 acres burned in Horseshoe 2 Fire; 40 percent contained\par \par \uc2 68,033\par \par \uc2 acres burned in Murphy Complex Fire; 75 percent contained\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110706e76c00005\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc11}{\*\bkmkend toc11}\b \uc2 Border seen as unlikely terrorist crossing point\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS; TIM STELLER   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS AND TIM STELLER, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,939 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 June 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 They're more apt to use other routes or be here already, but that doesn't stop fear\par \par \uc2 A turning political tide has renewed fears that raged after the Sept. 11, 2001, terrorist attacks - that terrorists will sneak into the country across the U.S.-Mexico border.\par \par \uc2 Nobody disputes that's possible, but analysts and government officials say terrorists plotting to kill Americans are more likely to use other routes into the country, if they're not here already.\par \par \uc2 It's much more common for people convicted in the U.S. of crimes connected to international terrorism to have been U.S. citizens or legal residents, or come into the country on visas.\par \par \uc2 "There is no serious evidence that the U.S.-Mexico border is a significant threat from terrorism," said Edward Alden, a senior fellow at the Council on Foreign Relations, a nonpartisan think tank based in New York.\par \par \uc2 Claims of terrorist threats on the Southwest border distract legislators and policymakers from addressing long-term solutions to drug smuggling and illegal immigration, said Tom Barry, senior analyst at the Center for International Policy in Washington.\par \par \uc2 "It's politically motivated," Barry said, "playing on that sense of fear that certain people are susceptible to."\par \par \uc2 But proponents of tougher border enforcement say protecting Americans against terrorism motivates them, not politics.\par \par \uc2 "There's an enormous risk," said Michael Braun, who retired as chief of operations for the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration in 2008. Members of Hezbollah, for example, "are absolute masters at identifying existing smuggling infrastructures on many borders around the world where they operate."\par \par \uc2 The State Department's 2009 "Country Reports on Terrorism" found that "no known international terrorist organizations had an operational presence in Mexico and no terrorist incidents targeting U.S. interests and personnel occurred on or originated from Mexican territory."\par \par \uc2 The State Department said that there was no evidence of ties between Mexican organized crime and international terrorist groups. But it warns: "The violence attributed to organized-crime groups on the border, however, continued to strain Mexico's law-enforcement capacities, creating potential vulnerabilities that terrorists seeking access to the United States could exploit."\par \par \uc2 Pinal County Sheriff Paul Babeu emphasized the risk of terrorists crossing the Mexican border into the U.S. in a May 26 open letter to President Obama.\par \par \uc2 "If the majority of regular illegal immigrants can sneak into America, what does this say about the ability of terrorist sleeper cells?" Babeu wrote. "The porous U.S.-Mexican border is the gravest national-security threat facing America."\par \par \uc2 Hiding in a car trunk\par \par \uc2 In his letter to the president, Babeu said thousands of illegal immigrants hailing from "special-interest countries" make the U.S.- Mexico border a national-security threat.\par \par \uc2 "In some cases, we have confirmed their troubling ties to terrorism," Babeu wrote. "Yet for those we apprehend, how many today live amongst us?"\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol apprehended an average of 339 people from "special-interest countries" - those that warrant special handling based on terrorism risk factors - at the U.S.-Mexico border each year over the past six years, Homeland Security data show. That's less than 1 percent each year of the total apprehensions along the U.S.-Mexico border, Homeland Security figures show.\par \par \uc2 None of the 2,039 people arrested at the U.S.-Mexico border in that span presented a credible terrorist threat, Homeland Security officials say.\par \par \uc2 Homeland Security monitors, analyzes and gathers intelligence about potential threats but at this time "does not have any credible information on terrorist groups operating along the Southwest border," said department spokesman Matt Chandler.\par \par \uc2 Among the 36 people convicted by the U.S. Justice Department of charges relating to international terrorism last year, none came into the United States from Mexico. Half were U.S. citizens, most of them naturalized from countries such as Sudan or Somalia. Seven were extradited from other countries, while three were captured abroad by American forces. The others came to the United States on visas, or, in one case, were arrested while trying to come into the United States legally at a port of entry on the Canadian border.\par \par \uc2 However, over the last decade there have been a handful of cases in which suspected terrorists or Muslim extremists crossed the Mexican border illegally. None led to attempted terrorist attacks in the United States.\par \par \uc2 In 2001, for example, Mahmoud Youssef Kourani rode into the United States in the trunk of a car coming from Tijuana. He went on to live in Dearborn, Mich., but was arrested in 2003, and in 2005 was convicted of conspiring to send money to Hezbollah in Lebanon.\par \par \uc2 In January of this year, an extremist imam from Tunisia, Said Jaziri, was arrested while riding in the trunk of a car on a highway east of San Diego. Jaziri, who was expelled from Canada in 2007, hiked across the Mexican border with another \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , and both were picked up by an American driver.\par \par \uc2 But a firefighter saw them pile into the trunk and reported them to Border Patrol agents, who pulled the car over and found the men. Jaziri was charged with a misdemeanor immigration violation.\par \par \uc2 not A traditional route\par \par \uc2 Over the last two decades, almost all of the known international terrorists arrested in the United States have come on legal visas or were allowed to come in without a visa, said Alden, of the Council on Foreign Relations.\par \par \uc2 "These are people that come on airplanes," said Alden, author of "The Closing of the American Border," which explains how the U.S. revised visa and border policies in the wake of the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks.\par \par \uc2 The 19 people involved in the Sept. 11 attacks entered the country on legal visas.\par \par \uc2 And over the last four to five years, the terrorist plots have increasingly involved people already in the United States - citizens and legal residents, he said.\par \par \uc2 "The notion of the (Southwest) border as the line that protects us from terrorism has really gone out of the window in the last several years," Alden said.\par \par \uc2 Not only is the U.S. side of the border heavily guarded, but the Mexican government makes an extraordinary effort to prevent terrorists from coming through its country. For instance, Mexico shares real-time information with the U.S. about airline passengers arriving in Mexico to make sure they don't include potential terrorists, Alden said.\par \par \uc2 The Mexican drug-smuggling organizations have no interest in allowing smuggling routes to be used by terrorist organizations either, he said.\par \par \uc2 "If it is discovered that a terrorist that carried out an attack in the United States came across the Mexican border, then the response would be further fortification of that border that shuts down smuggling routes and cuts into the profits," he said.\par \par \uc2 Being associated with terrorist groups would be very bad for business for drug-smuggling organizations, said Sylvia Longmire, a drug-war analyst and author. Proof of a terrorist coming through Mexico would have dire consequences for the Mexican government, too, she said.\par \par \uc2 But that point of view ignores the fact that terrorist groups and Latin American drug smugglers sometimes do business with each other and therefore have connections, said Braun, the former DEA operations chief, who now runs a security-consulting firm, Spectre Group International.\par \par \uc2 "Hezbollah is now heavily involved in the global cocaine trade," Braun said. "Most of the cocaine they're involved in distributing is heading toward Europe, but they're affiliating with the same cartels sending drugs to the United States."\par \par \uc2 That isn't to say the groups share an ideology, but simply that they have the connections needed to exploit smuggling routes into the United States. Also, people from the Middle East tend to have dark hair, dark eyes and olive skin, like most Latin Americans, so they can easily blend in, he said.\par \par \uc2 "On a moonless night at two in the morning, there's not a lot of due diligence going on when the coyotes and gatekeepers are moving human traffic across that border," Braun said.\par \par \uc2 Canada is a more likely crossing point because that country allows in more people as refugees and asylum seekers, said \uc2 Henry Willis\uc2 , a senior policy researcher on homeland security at the \uc2 Rand Corp\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "To regard the Southwestern border as the 'frontline against terrorism,' as the Border Patrol does, is folly," wrote Barry, of the Center for International Policy, in a recent report.\par \par \uc2 People have talked about terrorists crossing the U.S.-Mexico border, but Anthony Coulson, who retired as head of the Drug Enforcement Administration's Tucson office last year, has seen hardly any evidence.\par \par \uc2 "Through the years I can probably count on my fingers on one hand the number of times that there was some type of terrorist activity associated with the border," Coulson said. "It just doesn't happen."\par \par \uc2 But that's not to say it couldn't.\par \par \uc2 "Border security at the southern U.S. border is a critical national-security issue," said Willis of the \uc2 Rand Corp\uc2 ., "but for many reasons, not solely because of terrorism."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Tim Steller at 807-8427 or at tsteller@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Bill would label drug smugglers terrorists\par \par \uc2 Rep. Michael McCaul, R-Texas, wants Mexican drug-smuggling organizations designated as terrorists.\par \par \uc2 A bill he has proposed would help authorities go after cartels and those who assist them, he said during a May 11 hearing of the House Committee on Homeland Security.\par \par \uc2 "Federal law defines terrorism as activity that is intended to intimidate a civilian population or to influence the policy of a government by intimidation or to affect the conduct of a government by assassination or kidnapping," McCaul said during the hearing. "In my judgment, the drug cartels fall squarely within this definition."\par \par \uc2 One factor behind the push is the violent turf battles in Mexico between drug-smuggling organizations, which killed more than 34,500 people from December 2006 to December 2010, says the Trans Border Institute at the University of San Diego.\par \par \uc2 The highly publicized death of U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement agent Jaime Zapata in Mexico in February escalated concerns even more. Zapata was killed when gunmen attacked a vehicle he was in with another agent in the Mexican state of San Luis Potosi.\par \par \uc2 Classifying Mexican organized-crime groups as terrorist organization would be ill-advised because they are "clearly illicit business enterprises that lack any political motivation other than profit," said David Shirk, director of the Trans-Border Institute.\par \par \uc2 Given the chaotic and unpredictable violent conflict in Mexico, the cartels are a real and present danger to the United States, Shirk testified in late March before a House Committee on Homeland Security. But designating them as terrorists could present a serious problem to U.S. foreign policy.\par \par \uc2 "The concept of terrorism will be so expansive we could apply the same label to virtually any group of illicit actors that coerce through scare tactics and intimidation: human traffickers, kidnappers, U.S. gangs, and maybe even FIFA," Shirk wrote in an email. FIFA, world soccer's governing body, is embroiled in a bribery and corruption scandal.\par \par \uc2 But McCaul says the cartels are a growing national-security threat to both the U.S. and Mexico. His bill, which has been referred to committee, would give cartels reason to be afraid, he said.\par \par \uc2 "In my view, Mexico is losing this war and so are we," he said on May 11. "The cartels do not fear U.S. law enforcement."\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110629e7650001m\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc12}{\*\bkmkend toc12}\b \uc2 Obama mocks GOP in push for immigration overhaul\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,220 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 May 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Touting gains on border security and mocking Republicans' insatiable appetite for border enforcement, President Obama said Tuesday it's time for immigration reform.\par \par \uc2 The administration has gone "above and beyond" what Republicans asked for on border security when the last round of serious immigration reform debate stalled in 2007, Obama said in El Paso on his first trip to the U.S.-Mexico border since becoming president.\par \par \uc2 "All the stuff they've asked for, we've done," Obama said. "But, I suspect there's going to be those who try to move the goal posts on us one more time."\par \par \uc2 They'll now call for even more Border Patrol agents and a higher fence, he said.\par \par \uc2 "Maybe they'll say we need a moat? Maybe they'll want alligators in the moat?" Obama said. "They'll never be satisfied. And I understand that; that's politics. But the truth is that the measures we've put in place are getting results."\par \par \uc2 The administration has continued the work started during the second Bush administration, adding more Border Patrol agents and intelligence analysts, building more border fencing, adding unmanned aerial systems and forging partnerships with Mexico. Obama cited a decrease in Border Patrol apprehensions of illegal border crossers, an increase in contraband seizures and low violent-crime rates in U.S. border cities as evidence their efforts are working.\par \par \uc2 The next step to increase border security is reforming the "broken" legal immigration system, so fewer people are forced to cross the border illegally, leaving the Border Patrol to focus on criminals, Obama said.\par \par \uc2 But Republicans disagree with his assessment, citing incidents such as the killings of Border Patrol agent Brian Terry in December and rancher Robert Krentz in March 2010, both in Arizona.\par \par \uc2 "President Obama speaks about our broken immigration system; but what about our broken borders?" asked Arizona Republican Sens. John McCain and Jon Kyl in a joint statement. "We hear from our constituents on a daily basis, and, while some progress has been made in some areas, they do not believe the border is secure."\par \par \uc2 And some questioned whether the president's speech was a sincere attempt to drive reform or a strategy to recapture Latino voters in 2012.\par \par \uc2 "These are some of same good words we heard from President Obama as a candidate the last round," said Jennifer Allen, executive director of Tucson-based Border Action Network. "The challenge for the president is turning these words into meaningful action, so this doesn't just come across like this was to get the Latino vote."\par \par \uc2 Obama's Tuesday speech was his latest effort to push for reform. He's had several meetings this past month with business, labor, law enforcement and faith leaders. He also met with Latino entertainment and media stars.\par \par \uc2 He vowed to continue leading the charge but asked the public to help push Congress to take up the issue.\par \par \uc2 "I am asking you to add your voices to this," Obama said. "We need Washington to know that there is a movement for reform gathering strength from coast to coast. That's how we'll get this done."\par \par \uc2 While the president may be sincere in his intentions to push for reform, it's highly unlikely any reform will get through Congress with the Republicans controlling the House, said Steve Camarota, director of research for the Center for Immigration Studies, a Washington-based organization that advocates for slowing immigration.\par \par \uc2 Obama has pledged to push for immigration reform since he took office but with no results. There are an estimated 11.2 million illegal immigrants living in the United States, according to the latest Pew Hispanic Center study. Some crossed the border illegally and others overstayed visas.\par \par \uc2 "The overwhelming majority of these folks are just trying to earn a living and provide for their families," Obama said. "But they've broken the rules and have cut in front of the line. And the truth is, the presence of so many illegal immigrants makes a mockery of all those who are trying to immigrate legally."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com.\par \par \uc2 Immigration reform highlights\par \par \uc2 * Continue enforcing the law and securing the border.\par \par \uc2 * Punish businesses that hire and exploit \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  workers.\par \par \uc2 * Establish a path to residency for illegal immigrants that requires them to pay a fine, learn English, pay taxes, undergo background checks and go through a lengthy process before they can get in line for legal status.\par \par \uc2 * Revamp the outdated legal-immigration system to make it easier for the "best and brightest" to not only study here, but to start businesses and create jobs.\par \par \uc2 * Provide farms a legal way to hire the workers they need, and provide a path for those workers to get legal status.\par \par \uc2 * Adjust laws so families following the rules are reunited more quickly.\par \par \uc2 * Pass the Dream Act, which would allow people brought here illegally as children to go to college and join the military.\par \par \uc2 The reaction\par \par \uc2 Arizona Sens. John McCain and Jon Kyl\par \par \uc2 "During the president's first visit to our nation's southern border, we hope he will finally see firsthand the continued security challenges facing all of those who live along our southwest border," McCain and Kyl said in a joint statement.\par \par \uc2 McCain and Kyl urged Obama to pass the Republican duo's border security-enforcement bill before calling for immigration reform. And they questioned why Obama chose to give his speech in El Paso instead of Arizona, which has been the busiest stretch of border for a decade.\par \par \uc2 "As he is well aware, the Tucson Sector remains the most trafficked sector, with close to a quarter million apprehensions just last year. By comparison, the El Paso Sector where President Obama is speaking hasn't had over 200,000 apprehensions since 1993. It is no wonder the president chose El Paso and not Tucson as a backdrop to talk about immigration reform."\par \par \uc2 Gov. Jan Brewer\par \par \uc2 "After two years of waiting, I am glad the White House has chosen to focus on immigration. But I remain skeptical. It would be a shame if this effort is more about locking down votes in 2012 than securing our nation's border today."\par \par \uc2 "The president should have come to the Arizona border, where I have invited him repeatedly," Brewer said. "He should have spoken to our ranchers, who live with drug-runners and human-smugglers crossing their lands. He should have met with our law enforcement officers, who are frequently outgunned by the heavily-armed cartels."\par \par \uc2 "If the president felt confident in declaring the border secure, he should have come to tell the people of Arizona face-to-face."\par \par \uc2 U.S. Rep. Raul Grijalva\par \par \uc2 The president laid out the framework well for what immigration reform needs to include and reminded people why it's an issue that needs attention now, and not in 10, 20 or 50 years, Grijalva said. Grijalva said he wishes Obama would have made this speech earlier in his presidency but said it was still a necessary affirmation of his position. Obama was correct that Republicans continue to "move the goal posts" and demand more enforcement. "The president said it really well," Grijalva said. "There is no satisfaction point. It's insatiable."\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110521e75b00054\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc13}{\*\bkmkend toc13}\b \uc2 Harvard prof to speak about children of immigrants\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 218 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 April 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A8\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 The more than 4 million U.S. citizen children being raised by \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  parents are falling behind in cognitive and language skills by the time they are 3 years old, says a Harvard education professor who will be speaking today at the University of Arizona.\par \par \uc2 Hirokazu Yoshikawa's book "Immigrants Raising Citizens: Undocumented Parents and Their Young Children" is based on a three- year study of 380 babies born to Mexican, Dominican, Chinese and African-American parents in New York. Some parents were here legally and others illegally.\par \par \uc2 The book concludes that the stress of poor work conditions, isolated social networks and the threat of being deported harms the development of the small children of illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 The talk is at 2 p.m. today, with a reception afterward, and will be at the University of Arizona campus, McClelland Park, 650 N. Park Ave., Room 105.\par \par \uc2 If you go\par \par \uc2 Harvard professor of education Hirokazu Yoshikawa talks about his book "Immigrants Raising Citizens: Undocumented Parents and Their Young Children."\par \par \uc2 * When: 2-3:30 p.m. today, with reception to follow.\par \par \uc2 * Where: University of Arizona campus, McClelland Park, 650 N Park Ave., Room 105.\par \par \uc2 * Note: RSVPs would be appreciated by emailing ericaruegg@email.arizona.edu\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110517e74t0000i\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc14}{\*\bkmkend toc14}\b \uc2 Feds: 3 execs of Chuy's hired crossers illegally\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 817 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 April 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Father-son owners, accountant paid them in cash, indictment says\par \par \uc2 Federal agents arrested the father-son owners of 15 Chuy's Mesquite Broiler restaurants in Arizona and California on Wednesday on allegations they were knowingly hiring illegal immigrants and paying them under the table.\par \par \uc2 Mark Evenson, 58, of Paradise Valley, and his son, Christopher Evenson, 39, of Oro Valley, were arrested along with the company's accountant, Diane Strehlow, 47, of Tempe.\par \par \uc2 They face a variety of criminal charges including unlawful hiring and harboring of illegal immigrants, conspiracy to defraud the Internal Revenue Service and tax evasion, said Vincent Picard, Immigration and Customs Enforcement spokesman.\par \par \uc2 Agents from Immigration and Customs Enforcement and the Internal Revenue Service served search warrants at four Chuy's in Tucson, seven in Phoenix and four in California, said Rick Crocker, ICE deputy special agent in charge in Tucson. Search warrants were also presented at two houses in Tucson and three houses in Phoenix.\par \par \uc2 The arrests are the culmination of a two-year investigation that began with an anonymous tip that Chuy's was hiring illegal immigrants, Crocker said. The Evensons hired illegal immigrants to work in the kitchens of 15 Chuy's restaurants in Arizona and California, paying them off the books to avoid paying taxes, he said.\par \par \uc2 Agents also arrested 40 illegal immigrants they encountered Wednesday at Chuy's locations in Arizona and California, including 18 in Tucson, Picard said. They are facing administrative immigration charges. But they weren't the focus of the investigation, Crocker said.\par \par \uc2 "Our goal is not just to round up illegal aliens," Crocker said. "What we want to do is target the employers. We are trying to send a message that we are not going to tolerate this."\par \par \uc2 If convicted, Mark Evenson could face up to 86 years in prison and a $5.3 million fine. His son could face up to 81 years in prison and a $5 million fine. The accountant, Strehlow, could face up to 40 years and a $2 million fine. The three will be arraigned today in federal court in Tucson.\par \par \uc2 The company paid the \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  workers by check and did not report their earnings in the quarterly federal tax returns, the indictment shows. The company has failed to pay at least $400,000 in Federal Insurance Contribution Act (Social Security and Medicare) taxes since January 2008, the indictment shows.\par \par \uc2 "That provides an unfair commercial advantage for Chuy's," Crocker said.\par \par \uc2 The Evensons hired legal workers to be servers and perform other front-of-the-restaurant jobs and paid them through regular payroll practices. The illegal workers were hired for the kitchen, the indictment says.\par \par \uc2 Crocker said investigators are confident they've gathered sufficient evidence to prove in court that the Evensons "knowingly" hired the \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  workers. That's a requirement of federal law for an employer to be found guilty.\par \par \uc2 In November 2010, Mark Evenson instructed an employee preparing payroll that the restaurant did "cash" for the back help, the indictment says. "If those Social Security numbers get in the state, they'll come pick them up," Mark Evenson said.\par \par \uc2 After receiving a complaint about illegal workers at a Lake Havasu City Chuy's in September 2010, Mark Evenson told an employee, "If we throw some American people in there, maybe that'll just shut (them) up," the indictment says. He told the employee, who he believed was an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , "I just need to get you off the oh, show floor. I need to hide you in the kitchen."\par \par \uc2 When an employee told Christopher Evenson in August 2010 that a person he wanted to hire who was working at another restaurant had "no papers," Christopher Evenson told the employee that the other restaurant did "the same thing," the indictment says.\par \par \uc2 Dating to 2008, the Evensons hired about 360 illegal immigrants to work at the 11 Chuy's in Arizona, the indictment alleges. The younger Evenson, Christopher, was primarily responsible for the Chuy's locations in Tucson, the indictment says..\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 The restaurants\par \par \uc2 The Chuy's locations in Tucson run by the Evensons are located at:\par \par \uc2 * 3100 E. Speedway.\par \par \uc2 * 7585 S. Houghton Rd.\par \par \uc2 * 4499 W. Ina Rd.\par \par \uc2 * 6310 Tanque Verde Rd.\par \par \uc2 Different Owner\par \par \uc2 The Chuy's on East 22nd Street at South Kolb Road has a separate franchise owner and was not involved in the investigation, said owner J. Brian Latta.\par \par \uc2 Latta came to Arizona from California with Mark Evenson to start the chain but the business associates parted ways in 2003. "I hope it doesn't hurt my business," Latta said.\par \par \uc2 Did You Know\par \par \uc2 In May 2010, Chris and Mark Evenson agreed to pay $40,000 to settle a federal copyright lawsuit stemming from songs being played without permission.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110507e74l00074\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc15}{\*\bkmkend toc15}\b \uc2 Anti-immigration candidate dies\b0\par\par\uc2 ANDREA KELLY   \par \uc2 ANDREA KELLY, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 855 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 April 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 JOE SWEENEY: 1944-2011\par \par \uc2 Joe Sweeney, best known for repeatedly running for offices he did not win and railing against illegal immigration at public forums, died Saturday in Tucson.\par \par \uc2 The 66-year old political fixture battled cancer in the 1970s, and doctors said another form of cancer contributed to his death, said Barbara Nelson, Sweeney's sister.\par \par \uc2 A small, thin man, Sweeney drummed up a lot of political noise, frequently speaking at public meetings, telling the Tucson City Council or the Pima County Board of Supervisors they needed to control illegal immigration.\par \par \uc2 He would ask federal and local public officials to crack down on illegal border crossings and bemoan what he said was the Mexican government's role in sending illegal immigrants into the United States.\par \par \uc2 Sweeney ran for a seat in Congress every election cycle, starting in 1984, appearing on the ballot of the Democratic, Republican and New Alliance parties at various times, sometimes winning a party primary but never winning a general election in 14 tries.\par \par \uc2 His last few campaigns were as a Republican in Democrat- dominated Congressional District 7, facing liberal U.S. Rep. Raul Grijalva.\par \par \uc2 Because of his controversial positions, Pima County Republican officials considered distancing the party from his congressional campaign in 2004, calling him a "racist." He also came under criticism for frequent anti-homosexual comments. The county GOP ultimately decided not to get involved one way or another.\par \par \uc2 Family members were still sorting through the details of Sweeney's life and unexpected death as they fielded calls from the community Monday. Sweeney's nephew, Philip Cojanis, said the family is still jarred by the news, but is putting together plans and more information about him for the public.\par \par \uc2 "He was a good man, and from what we're even just finding out, he helped so many people in so many ways. We're just overwhelmed by how many people are finding out what's happened," Cojanis said. "He had a much bigger heart than many other people would know."\par \par \uc2 His sister said he was reliable and liked to handle things on his own. True to his nature, he didn't let family members know he was ill, Nelson said.\par \par \uc2 A middle child, Sweeney was born Aug. 4, 1944, in Nebraska. The family moved to Tucson in the 1950s, where Sweeney lived the rest of his life.\par \par \uc2 Sweeney ran his political campaigns on a shoestring budget and a platform of stopping illegal immigration, and rarely missed a chance to speak about it at the open portions of weekly government meetings.\par \par \uc2 Russ Dove, who appeared on Sweeney's public-access television show for three or four years, said Monday that he respected Sweeney for his high intelligence and ability to shrug off sometimes harsh popular opinion.\par \par \uc2 "He did what he did because he believed it was the right thing to do and he was obligated to do the right thing," Dove said.\par \par \uc2 "He truly believed in some form of superior race or some form of select group of people the scriptures applied to. I always argued that they apply to everyone.\par \par \uc2 "Joe Sweeney had the heart of Abraham Lincoln; he just didn't stop," Dove said, noting that Sweeney also traveled to Washington, D.C., to advocate for Peace Corps funding and was a strong supporter of the program.\par \par \uc2 "I wish that more people would take that interest in their community and put that forward to making the world a better place as Joe Sweeney did," Dove said. "I think he could have been more effective if he had taken Jesus at his face value and just loved, instead of loving his own. I think that was his greatest fault."\par \par \uc2 Local politician and government gadfly John Kromko didn't often find himself on the same side of many issues with Sweeney. But Kromko said he respected Sweeney for speaking his mind.\par \par \uc2 Kromko, a former state legislator and frequent political candidate, said he met Sweeney when he ran a print shop and Sweeney got materials printed for his law school.\par \par \uc2 "The underlying thing old Joe always believed was that the law was the key thing, that if people learned the law they could work for justice and their rights," Kromko said.\par \par \uc2 Sweeney started the Alexander Hamilton Evening Law School in the late 1970s.\par \par \uc2 Armed with his University of Arizona bachelor's degree in agriculture, he didn't charge tuition to the unaccredited school, but accepted donations. Those who completed the program received a certificate of recognition.\par \par \uc2 Kromko said it's rare to find someone who stuck so surely to his beliefs. Sweeney lost a job decades ago, and later found out his former employer had hired an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  for much lower wages, Kromko said. It may have been a tipping point, he said.\par \par \uc2 "Even if you didn't agree with him on illegal aliens, you could see he was sincere about it," Kromko said. "So many political types are not sincere in what they say."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Andrea Kelly at akelly@azstarnet.com or 807- 7790.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110420e7450000h\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc16}{\*\bkmkend toc16}\b \uc2 Slaying of border rancher still a mystery 1 year later\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 2,262 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 March 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 MURDER OF ROBERT KRENTZ\par \par \uc2 Authorities have identified 'person of interest' but haven't found him even with Mexico's help\par \par \uc2 DOUGLAS - The murder of a prominent Cochise County rancher that triggered a nationwide outcry about border security remains unsolved a year later.\par \par \uc2 Investigators have identified a man who fits the description of the possible killer - a tall, cross-border smuggler with a violent criminal record. But they don't know for sure if he's in the U.S. or Mexico - or if he's dead or alive.\par \par \uc2 And even if they find him, it won't mean the crime is solved. Authorities haven't found the gun used to kill Robert Krentz on his ranch last March 27, and they have no witnesses, show investigation documents the Daily Star obtained through public records requests.\par \par \uc2 Alejandro Chavez-Vasquez is not an official suspect in Krentz's murder but is a "person of interest" in a series of Portal burglaries in early 2010, say Cochise County sheriff's officials.\par \par \uc2 Investigators believe there is a link between two of those burglaries and the murder, documents show. A search warrant affidavit filed in Cochise County Court on March 31, 2010, by Immigration and Customs Enforcement shows investigators believe the burglar who stole a Glock 26 handgun and two cellphones from a vehicle near the town of Portal the day before is the person who killed Krentz.\par \par \uc2 The federal agency has been assisting the Cochise County Sheriff's Office with the case.\par \par \uc2 Krentz was murdered with the same caliber firearm that was reported stolen from the car, the affidavit said. The burglary occurred in the Herb Martyr campground in the Chiricahua Mountains about seven miles southwest of Portal, a Cochise County Sheriff's Office report shows.\par \par \uc2 Investigators have homed in on Chavez-Vasquez because of his height - 6 feet 3 inches - and criminal background. The shoe prints tracked from the crime scene about 20 miles south to the border were size 11, said Warner Glenn, a mountain lion hunter who helped track the prints. Based on the shoe size and 31-to-32 inch stride, Glenn and investigators estimate the killer is at least 6 feet tall.\par \par \uc2 Footprints of the same size and pattern were found at the campground vehicle burglary and at an area home that was likely burglarized during the day of March 27, shows a Cochise County sheriff's report.\par \par \uc2 Chavez-Vasquez, likely in his late 30s, has convictions in four states for crimes including sexual assault, vehicle theft and possession of narcotics. He also pleaded guilty in 2004 to illegal re-entry after deportation.\par \par \uc2 In April, the Cochise County Sheriff's Office distributed a photo of Chavez-Vasquez to media outlets, area ranchers and Mexican authorities. Agua Prieta Police Chief Alfonso Novoa Novoa said Border Patrol officials told him Chavez-Vasquez could be a suspect in the killing.\par \par \uc2 Agua Prieta police distributed 500 pictures around the border city south of Douglas, but nobody claimed to know anything about Chavez-Vasquez. They also ran his name through municipal, state and federal databases throughout Mexico but found nothing - no property, no voter card, no driver's license, Novoa said.\par \par \uc2 And so one of 2010's highest-profile murders - one that helped prompt Arizona's tough new immigration law - remains a mystery.\par \par \uc2 Many of the questions that surfaced in the days following Krentz's murder remain unanswered: Why would someone kill a man known to family and friends as a teddy bear? Was the killing to punish the Krentz family for a call his brother made to the Border Patrol the day before about bundles of marijuana found on their property? Was Krentz targeted or was the killing random? Did it mark a sea change in the long-held rule among smugglers that they lie low in the U.S. for the good of their business?\par \par \uc2 There's no closure for Krentz's heartbroken widow, children and grandchildren. There's no explanation for shaken ranchers desperate to know if they should be worried for their own safety in this remote valley near the Arizona-New Mexico state line.\par \par \uc2 "We would like to know what the heck happened," said Bill McDonald, a fifth-generation rancher east of Douglas. "It doesn't make any sense to us."\par \par \uc2 Cochise County Sheriff Larry Dever would not answer specific questions about the investigation but said his office believes the killer was involved in smuggling people or drugs in Cochise County.\par \par \uc2 "Rob Krentz was killed by a bad person with a bad agenda, and our porous borders continue to contribute to the potential for another event," Dever said via email.\par \par \uc2 The investigation has momentum in the U.S. and in Mexico, where officials have been extremely helpful, Dever wrote. There is a $45,000 reward for information.\par \par \uc2 "I will never rest until this killer is brought to justice," Dever wrote.\par \par \uc2 But as days and months pass, fewer people believe the murder will be solved.\par \par \uc2 "The older the case gets," said Richard Winkler, a Krentz family friend and former Cochise County Superior Court Judge, "the harder it gets to solve."\par \par \uc2 The case so far\par \par \uc2 Authorities didn't discover Krentz's body until just before midnight on March 27, giving the killer a nearly 14-hour head start to flee south to Mexico.\par \par \uc2 He was likely long gone by the time they followed his tracks to the border the next afternoon. Without a suspect to follow, investigators looked to the burglaries for clues. Immigration and Customs Enforcement officials hoped the call history of the two cellphones stolen from the campground near Portal would lead lead them closer to the killer.\par \par \uc2 One was used the day of the robbery to call two phone numbers, phone records obtained through a search warrant show. But the names of the people called that day didn't help: The numbers were registered to famed Mexican Revolution generals Pancho Villa and Emiliano Zapata.\par \par \uc2 In Mexico, authorities began searching for the killer the day after Krentz was found. State police looked for shoe prints and talked to ranchers near where he crossed over.\par \par \uc2 On the Monday after the killing, Agua Prieta police brought in about 100 people for questioning, fingerprints and photos in an attempt to find somebody who knew something about the crime, said Novoa, the Agua Prieta police chief. They didn't yet have any information about the size of the shoe or gun used, so they focused on people who had scrapes or bites, thinking that maybe the killer was bitten by Krentz's dog or otherwise hurt, Novoa said. But they didn't find anything.\par \par \uc2 In the U.S., investigators also interviewed people who might have information. One was a man arrested by the DEA on April 6 who officials thought might know something due to his associates and location of the arrest. He denied knowing anything about the murder.\par \par \uc2 Another was a suspected smuggler apprehended by the Border Patrol on April 8 who normally works in the corridor east of Douglas. He denied knowing anything about the crime but said the talk was that the "cartels were pissed because there was too much heat, and they were not able to easily get people and drugs through."\par \par \uc2 On April 9, Immigration and Customs Enforcement and the Border Patrol put out alerts to cover an area within a 15-mile radius of the crime scene with special emphasis on "6-foot-tall or taller smugglers, guides and repeat offenders," Cochise County Sheriff's Office reports show.\par \par \uc2 Chavez-Vasquez appears to be the only person being sought in the murder.\par \par \uc2 Who is Chavez-Vasquez?\par \par \uc2 Chavez-Vasquez has criminal convictions in four states - Colorado, Utah, Nevada and Oregon - and an immigration charge out of Arizona.\par \par \uc2 He spent two years in a Nevada prison, from 2002 to 2004, on a coercion conviction that stemmed from an arrest by Las Vegas police on suspicion that he attempted to sexually assault a woman.\par \par \uc2 He was paroled on April 15, 2004, from Nevada prisons, records from the Nevada Department of Corrections show.\par \par \uc2 A month later, he was arrested in Arizona and charged in U.S. District Court with illegal re-entry after deportation. He was given 36 months' supervised release and a fine of $100 in a plea agreement, federal records show.\par \par \uc2 Despite the deportation, it's unclear whether he is an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 . Clark County, Nev., court records show a Social Security number for Chavez-Vasquez that suggests he was born in California. Nevada officials could not confirm if the Social Security number was valid.\par \par \uc2 His criminal records show four birth dates that put him between 37 and 41 years old.\par \par \uc2 Though the Cochise County Sheriff's Office said Chavez-Vasquez was from Agua Prieta, the police chief there said he doesn't believe it.\par \par \uc2 "If somebody knows that 60 to 80 police officers are looking for a person, some kind of information arrives," Novoa said in Spanish.\par \par \uc2 family, ranchers feel loss\par \par \uc2 To say 2010 was a nightmare for Susan Krentz would be a gross understatement.\par \par \uc2 She lost her husband in March, and on Sept. 25 a suspected drunken driver hit her and a friend as they left church in Douglas. She suffered several skull and hip fractures and is still seeing doctors regularly, said her attorney, Paul Hoffman of Tucson. "She is lucky to have lived," Hoffman said.\par \par \uc2 In addition to dealing with her injuries, she misses her husband dearly. "All I can say is that my heart is broken, and I can't get over it," she said in a brief phone interview.\par \par \uc2 She desperately wants the crime solved, Hoffman said.\par \par \uc2 "We never asked to ride this horse that we are on, but it is saddled now and we must go on," said a family statement issued this month. "We are still searching for the truth of what happened that day and hope to someday put closure to this tragedy."\par \par \uc2 The Krentz family is frustrated with the investigation, said Don Kimble, a cousin of Sue Krentz's. Though a close friend of Sheriff Dever, Kimble doesn't hold back his criticism of the Sheriff's Office for waiting for the suspected killer to surface. "I think they should be more aggressive," Kimble said. "Hanging back and watching never gets nothing done.."\par \par \uc2 Kimble thinks authorities should more aggressively advertise in Mexico the cash reward for information about the murder. "I truly believe that if the money got placed in the right hands, the killer would show up," Kimble said.\par \par \uc2 Friends and neighbors in the hourglass-shaped San Bernardino and San Simon valleys near the Arizona-New Mexico state line are still troubled by the killing.\par \par \uc2 A noticeable boost in Border Patrol agents and technology there has slowed illegal activity a bit, but the smugglers keep coming. "The outlaws and dope and the guns are still here," said Ed Ashurstwho manages a ranch just north of the Krentzes and helped track the killer's footprints. "There is this combination of anger and depression and cynicism."\par \par \uc2 Ashurst believes his friend simply ran into a criminal who was intent on not getting caught and sent back to prison.\par \par \uc2 "I was worried the moment he got into Mexico that they were going to be able solve this," said fellow rancher Bill McDonald. "I continued to be worried despite assurances to the contrary."\par \par \uc2 Although authorities don't know whether Krentz's killer is still alive, what Sheriff Dever said about him during a press conference on March 29, 2010, still rings true a year later: "He is the only person living that knows exactly what happened out there that day."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Go to azstarnet.com/gallery for more photos.\par \par \uc2 Timeline\par \par \uc2 March 27, 2010: Robert Krentz sets out to check wells on his 35,000-acre ranch about 35 miles northeast of Douglas.\par \par \uc2 10 a.m. - Is heard on a handheld ranch radio telling his brother to contact the U.S. Border Patrol because he has found an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  who needs help.\par \par \uc2 11 a.m. - After getting no answer on radio and cell phones, his son, Frank Krentz, and brother, Phil Krentz, start searching for him.\par \par \uc2 6:22 p.m. - Neighboring rancher calls the Cochise County Sheriff's Office to report Krentz missing. Agency's search-and- rescue team arrives about two hours later.\par \par \uc2 11:43 p.m. - Search helicopter spots Krentz's body about a half- half mile from his last known position.\par \par \uc2 March 28, 6:10 a.m. - As the sun rises, investigators get a better look at the crime scene and begin tracking shoeprints south.\par \par \uc2 3:40 p.m. - Investigators - and a crew of trackers including mountain lion hunter Warner Glenn, his adult daughter, Kelly Glenn- Kimbro, and rancher Ed Ashurst - track footprints of the suspected killer about 20 miles due south to the border.\par \par \uc2 The tracks show the killer knew knew his way around the rugged terrain and was trying to conceal his path, Warner Glenn said.\par \par \uc2 Who was Robert Krentz?\par \par \uc2 * Born June 3, 1951, in Douglas.\par \par \uc2 * Attended elementary school in Apache, Ariz., then attended Douglas High School and played for the Douglas Bulldogs' 1968 state championship football team.\par \par \uc2 * Graduated from the University of Arizona in 1975 with a degree in animal science, then returned to the family ranch to work with his father and two uncles.\par \par \uc2 * Married Susan Kimble in 1977, and the couple had two sons and a daughter.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110412e73k0000i\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 ACCENT\par {\*\bkmkstart toc17}{\*\bkmkend toc17}\b \uc2 Horwitz, reporter partner helped bring justice in intern murder case\b0\par\par\uc2 ANN BROWN   \par \uc2 ANN BROWN, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,091 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 March 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par E5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Finding justice\par \par \uc2 Sari Horwitz selected this excerpt for the Star from "Finding Chandra: A True Washington Murder Mystery," which she co-authored with Scott Higham. The book is a finalist for the Edgar Allan Poe Award from the Mystery Writers of America, which will be presented April 28.\par \par \uc2 "In the fall of 2000 a young woman from an upper-middle class California family left the West Coast for Washington, D.C., to begin an internship at the Federal Bureau of Prisons. Chandra Ann Levy was not unlike the thousands of college and graduate students who arrive in Washington as interns each year. She wanted to leave the familiar surroundings of her home in the San Joaquin Valley and find her own way in the nation's epicenter of politics and power. At twenty- three, she hoped to become an agent for the FBI or the CIA one day. Seven months after arriving in Washington, Chandra signed off her computer inside her Dupont Circle apartment on a warm spring day and went for a walk in her gym clothes. She was never heard from again.\par \par \uc2 "D.C. detectives investigating her disappearance soon learned that Chandra had been carrying on a months-long affair with a married congressman from her home district in California. At fifty- two, Gary Condit was handsome and charismatic, a conservative Democrat who had been in Congress for eleven years. Word of the affair leaked and the news media became obsessed by the story of sex and suspicion. The coverage was incessant. During the summer of 2001, the story generated sensational headlines in newspapers around the world. The fledgling cable news shows that relied so heavily on fame, crime and scandal to energize their broadcasts updated the story every twelve minutes or so, and polls showed that nearly two- thirds of the nation was following every turn of the real-life soap opera. When Condit consented to a nationally televised interview late that summer, 24 million Americans tuned in. But nearly three weeks later, when terrorists struck the World Trade Center and the Pentagon, the story about the congressman and the intern became a curiosity of the pre-9/11 world and quickly faded.\par \par \uc2 "Six years later, two investigative reporters revisited Washington's most famous murder mystery."\par \par \uc2 Sari Horwitz wanted justice for Chandra Levy. A 24-year-old Washington, D.C., intern from California, Levy left her apartment in May 2001 and vanished. About a year later her bones were found scattered in a forested area of Rock Creek Park.\par \par \uc2 After a media and investigative frenzy singularly focused on California Congressman Gary Condit, with whom Levy had a relationship, the case went cold.\par \par \uc2 Investigators reopened Levy's case after Horwitz and Scott Higham of the Washington Post's investigation unit re-examined the murder and the surrounding circumstances in a newspaper series and in their book "Finding Chandra: A True Washington Murder Mystery."\par \par \uc2 Subsequently, Ingmar Guandique was arrested in 2009, found guilty of Levy's murder in November, and sentenced to 60 years in prison last month.\par \par \uc2 Longtime Tucsonans may remember Tucson-native Horwitz wrapping holiday presents at Crescent Jewelry, the store her late father owned. She said she's proud of being a Tucson High Badger - she was student-body president in 1975 - and last year was inducted into the Tucson High School Hall of Fame. Horwitz comes to Tucson every couple of months to visit her mother, Zella Horwitz.\par \par \uc2 Horwitz, who began as summer intern in 1984, is a three-time Pulitzer-Prize-winning member of the Post's investigation unit. Early in her career she said she fell in love with the police beat. Law enforcement has been the center of her long-term investigations.\par \par \uc2 While she did not report the original Chandra Levy story, she said she was "fascinated by a young woman from the West Coast with all these dreams who disappears in the nation's capital, not to be found."\par \par \uc2 In 2007 - six years after the case went bust - the editor of the Post's investigative team asked Horwitz and Higham to "go back and find out what happened. Take a year to look over and under every stone," Horwitz said in a phone interview.\par \par \uc2 "I'm so haunted by the story and so saddened," said Horwitz. "I wanted to find justice for Chandra."\par \par \uc2 Horwitz said they found mistakes in the investigation and found some fault with the media.\par \par \uc2 "It was a sexier story to talk about Gary Condit," said Horwitz. In a calmer atmosphere, Horwitz said she and Higham were able to take apart the case, piece by piece, interview by interview.\par \par \uc2 The result was a 13-part series, an experiment by the Post to bring narrative back into the paper. The series indentified an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  from El Salvador, who was serving time for assaulting two other women in the park where Levy's remains were found.\par \par \uc2 Horwitz and Higham reworked the series into the book. A chapter about the trial has been added to the paperback version, which will be available at the end of April.\par \par \uc2 "What we saw in the summer 2001 was criminal justice at its worst," said Horwitz. What happened later was criminal justice at its best: A strong case. Good lawyering. A jury that gave thoughtful consideration.\par \par \uc2 In this time of 24/7 journalism and blogs, there is pressure to be first but not necessarily right, Horwitz said.\par \par \uc2 "In these big cases, rumor and innuendo are flying all over," and the police and the media should not to rush to judgment, she said.\par \par \uc2 Horwitz was here on Jan. 8. Noting it was odd to file stories from her hometown and to call school friends as resources, Horwitz reported on the shooting and continues to cover the aftermath and U.S. Rep. Gabrielle Giffords' recovery for the Post.\par \par \uc2 Horwitz cites coverage of the shooting and the premature, inaccurate reporting that Giffords had died as an example of the precarious and emotionally damaging rush to be first that's plaguing the news industry.\par \par \uc2 While she helped find justice for Levy, Horwitz emphasized there will be never be closure. The Levys will never have their daughter.\par \par \uc2 IF You Go\par \par \uc2 Sari Horwitz with Gary Stuart - "True Crime: Chandra Levy and the Buddhist Temple Massacre" at 11:30 a.m. in Chemistry, Room 111; and "Writing about True Crime" workshop at 1 p.m. next Sunday in the Integrated Learning Center, Room 141.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110319e73600019\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc18}{\*\bkmkend toc18}\b \uc2 Single shot killed border agent\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,097 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 March 2011\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Files add some clarity to Terry's death; agents used beanbags against migrants, who replied with gunfire\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol agents shot beanbags at a group of suspected bandits before the men returned fire during a confrontation in a remote canyon, killing agent Brian Terry with a single gunshot, records show.\par \par \uc2 And an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  wounded in the gunbattle who is now the only person in custody linked to the slaying contends he never fired a shot, according to FBI search warrant requests filed in the U.S. District Court in Tucson.\par \par \uc2 The documents provide the most detailed version yet of what happened in the deadly gunbattle Dec. 14 in Peck Canyon, northwest of Nogales.\par \par \uc2 The documents say the group of illegal border entrants refused commands to drop their weapons after agents confronted them at about 11:15 p.m. Two agents fired beanbags at the migrants, who responded with gunfire. Two agents returned fire, one with a long gun and one with a pistol, but Terry was mortally wounded in the gunfight.\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol officials declined to answer questions about protocol for use of force, citing the ongoing investigation.\par \par \uc2 But Terry's brother, Kent Terry, said the other agents who were there that night told him that they were instructed to use the non- lethal beanbags first. It's a policy that doesn't make sense to Kent Terry.\par \par \uc2 "You go up against a bandit crew that is carrying AKs, and you walk out there with guns loaded with beanbags - I don't get it," Terry said in a phone interview from Michigan. "It's like going to the Iraqi war with one knife. It boggles my mind. ... These guys (Border Patrol agents) are professionals; they should be able to use their judgment call on their own."\par \par \uc2 On the night of the deadly encounter, agents were trying to apprehend at least five suspected illegal immigrants. One agent, using thermal binoculars, spotted two men carrying rifles. When the group came close, at least one agent identified himself as police and ordered the men to drop their weapons.\par \par \uc2 Here's how the rest of the events are described in the FBI document:\par \par \uc2 "When the suspected aliens did not drop their weapons, two Border Patrol agents deployed 'less than lethal' beanbags at the suspected aliens. At this time, at least one of the suspected aliens fired at the Border Patrol agents. Two Border Patrol agents returned fire, one with his long gun and one with his pistol.\par \par \uc2 "Border Patrol agent Brian Terry was shot with one bullet and died shortly after. One of the suspected illegal aliens, later identified as Manuel Osorio-Arellanes, was also shot."\par \par \uc2 The search warrants were requested to examine fingerprints and a hair sample from Osorio-Arellanes, who was one of four men arrested that night near the shooting scene. The other three arrested, illegal immigrants from Mexico, have been cleared in connection with the crime and deported back to their home countries.\par \par \uc2 Osorio-Arellanes has not been charged in connection with the fatal shooting. He has been charged only with illegal re-entry after deportation and is awaiting a May 10 trial. The FBI document represents the first time his name has been included in a public document related to the shooting.\par \par \uc2 Two days after the shooting, Osorio-Arellanes agreed to talk to FBI agents. He was traveling with four others that night, all of whom were armed, Osorio-Arellanes told investigators, according to the document.\par \par \uc2 "Osorio-Arellanes stated that he had raised his weapon towards the Border Patrol agents, but he did not fire because he realized that they were Border Patrol agents," the search warrant says. "At this time, he was shot."\par \par \uc2 Two firearms were recovered at the scene that are believed to belong to the suspects, the documents say. Officials were planning to take Osorio-Arellanes' fingerprints to compare with those found on the two weapons.\par \par \uc2 Officials also recovered five backpacks, three gloves, two sweat shirts, a pullover, a jacket, a knit hat, a baseball cap and a razor.\par \par \uc2 The summary provided in the search warrants is only a snapshot and does not include all facts known by investigators, FBI agents wrote in the three separate search-warrant requests filed in U.S. District Court in late December.\par \par \uc2 Terry, 40, of Michigan, was a member of a specially trained tactical unit known as Bortac. On the night of the shooting, Terry and his crew were targeting a "rip crew" that robbed and assaulted drug runners and illegal immigrants, said Homeland Security Secretary Janet Napolitano.\par \par \uc2 This week, the Terry family received the autopsy report, which shows that Terry was shot once in the lower back, about 29 inches down from the right shoulder, Kent Terry said. Brian Terry was trying to turn, likely for cover, when he was shot, Kent Terry said. The bullet found inside his body was one used with AK-47s, he said.\par \par \uc2 The report gave the family some closure, and it erased any doubt about friendly fire being a possibility in the fatal shooting, because agents don't use AK-47s, Kent Terry said. The FBI announced in mid-February that it had ruled out friendly fire, but Kent Terry remained skeptical because he hadn't seen the autopsy.\par \par \uc2 The Terry family remains upset about allegations that the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives allowed a gun smuggler it was investigating to purchase and smuggle into Mexico the weapons used in the shootout in which Terry died. The Justice Department has denied the allegations, but U.S. Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, continues to insist on the validity of the claims.\par \par \uc2 "Your government is telling you to use beanbags, but you are selling guns back to the Mexicans," Kent Terry said. "There's a lot of questions that they haven't answered."\par \par \uc2 The FBI investigation remains ongoing, said agency spokesman Manuel Johnson. No arrests have been made. The U.S. Attorney's Office in Arizona said investigators and prosecutors aim to bring criminal charges against the people responsible for Brian Terry's murder.\par \par \uc2 Terry, 40, was the 10th agent to die on duty in the Border Patrol's Tucson Sector since 1926 and the first agent shot to death since 1998. Terry was buried in his hometown of Detroit on Dec. 22, and hundreds attended his memorial service January in Tucson.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com.\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find extensive coverage of immigration issues at azstarnet.com/border\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110316e73300002\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc19}{\*\bkmkend toc19}\b \uc2 Aggression escalating in border marauders\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,331 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 December 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Bandits, around for a long time, now so bold they threaten chaos\par \par \uc2 Bandits such as the ones Border Patrol agent Brian Terry was trying to apprehend last week when he was shot and killed have been around for decades but have become more brazen in recent years, law enforcement officials say.\par \par \uc2 And it has become the Border Patrol's job to police these groups to make sure that chaos doesn't engulf Arizona's stretch of U.S.- Mexico border.\par \par \uc2 Scant details have been made public about what happened in the Dec. 14 gunbattle northwest of Nogales, but officials have confirmed that Terry and his fellow agents in a specially trained tactical unit known as Bortac were targeting a "rip crew" that robbed and assaulted drug runners and illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 That means Terry, a 40-year-old agent from Michigan, likely died performing the "savior" part of the Border Patrol's "hunter and savior" mission. While the agency's primary objective is stopping illegal immigrants and drug smugglers from making it north, the agency devotes considerable time and resources to rescuing illegal immigrants in distress and keeping armed and increasingly dangerous bandits in check.\par \par \uc2 "The Border Patrol is out there to prevent people from getting killed," said Anthony Coulson, a recently retired assistant special agent in charge of the Drug Enforcement Administration's Tucson office. "Even if they are partly responsible for putting themselves in this situation, there are people out there that you have an obligation to protect. It's the right thing to do. It's the humanitarian thing to do."\par \par \uc2 The bandits, also known as bajadores, often prey on men, women and children crossing Arizona's border illegally. They rob, attack and sometimes sexually assault them. More recently, Mexican drug- smuggling organizations have started using bandit crews to police their routes, ensuring that competitors don't use their hard-earned corridors, often stealing the loads.\par \par \uc2 They operate all along Arizona's international border, but the canyon-filled corridor west of Interstate 19 where Terry was killed has been a hot spot for bandits for years. In 2007, there were two fatal shootings involving bandits in the area.\par \par \uc2 Santa Cruz County Sheriff Tony Estrada said he is grateful that the Border Patrol targets the bandits - allowing them to operate freely would not only result in harm to illegal immigrants but could also put residents who live along the border in jeopardy.\par \par \uc2 "It provides assurances to residents in the area that law enforcement is around," Estrada said.\par \par \uc2 The Pima County Sheriff's Department formed a border-crimes unit in April 2007 after bandits shot two illegal immigrants to death. Among the 18-deputy unit's goals is to monitor bandit activity, said Sgt. Gilbert Dominguez, a supervisor of the unit.\par \par \uc2 "To prevent them from running the area themselves, you have to provide a law-enforcement presence in connection to Border Patrol to provide protection for those citizens who live out there and for those illegal immigrants who are victimized," Dominguez said.\par \par \uc2 As a Border Patrol agent working in Douglas in the 1970s, Lee Morgan regularly chased after border bandits who broke into homes and took the loot south.\par \par \uc2 Back then, they were called "border burglars," and they carried knives or shivs, said Morgan, who retired in 2006 after 31 years as a federal law-enforcement official with the Justice, Treasury and Homeland Security departments.\par \par \uc2 The rip crews became more violent in the 1980s and 1990s as they started working for the Mexican drug cartels and corrupt Mexican cops, Morgan said. They began carrying guns instead of knives, and during the mid-1990s bandits broke into homes in Bisbee and Naco and assaulted residents, he said.\par \par \uc2 "They have progressively gotten worse in Arizona from the 1970s to the 1990s to where you are at now," Morgan said.\par \par \uc2 Two kinds of bandits\par \par \uc2 Today, there are two main types of bandits - crews that try to rip off drug loads and those that try to rob illegal immigrants, said Lt. Raoul Rodriguez, operations division commander with the Santa Cruz County Sheriff's Office.\par \par \uc2 The crews usually consist of three to five men, dressed in dark clothes or fatigues, often wearing ski masks, Rodriguez said. They carry assault rifles or handguns.\par \par \uc2 Groups that target illegal immigrants will usually pop up close to the border, demanding money and valuables and warning the people that they will kill them if they look back. Assaults and sexual assaults are commonplace. Crews that rip off drugs usually do it farther north, often 15 to 30 miles north of the border.\par \par \uc2 The bandits robbing illegal immigrants are often independent criminals based in Tucson or Phoenix who were on the fringe of drug trafficking and who have banded together, Coulson said.\par \par \uc2 In the last year, Mexican drug-smuggling organizations have begun using bandit crews to police their desert smuggling routes, ensuring that competitors are not using their trails, Coulson said.\par \par \uc2 "You don't want independents out there running dope," Coulson said. "They are not paying the tax; they are not paying their dues for running that corridor."\par \par \uc2 UNCERTAIN FUTURE\par \par \uc2 Law enforcement officials are split on whether the fatal shooting of agent Terry is a sign that more violence is inevitable.\par \par \uc2 The paradigm on the border has long been that it was bad business for drug smugglers to harm or kill U.S. agents because it would bring unwanted attention that would make it more difficult to move their marijuana. Shooters have often been killed by angry cartel bosses upon their return to Mexico.\par \par \uc2 "I'm hoping that it's going to be an isolated incident," said Lt. Rodriguez of Santa Cruz County. "It's not a very smart move to engage law enforcement the way they do in Mexico."\par \par \uc2 But Pima County Sgt. Dominguez said he expects there to be more shootouts with bandits. And Coulson is even more worried. The old paradigm is history now, he said, predicting that there will be a major violent event within a year between Mexican drug cartels and U.S. law enforcement in the United States.\par \par \uc2 "We're in trouble," Coulson said. "It's not a matter of if violent activity is going to occur, it's a matter of when. And when it happens, it's going to be significant."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Funeral today in Michigan\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol agent Brian Terry will be buried today at the Michigan Memorial Cemetery near Detroit after a church service at the Greater Grace Temple in Detroit.\par \par \uc2 Violent encounters\par \par \uc2 A sampling of some of violent encounters between border bandits and illegal immigrants and federal agents:\par \par \uc2 * March 2, 2010 - A group of illegal border crossers fed up with being robbed a second time beat up two of the robbers, killing one, about 16 miles north of the border near Sasabe.\par \par \uc2 * March 22, 2008 - Bandits shoot and wound an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  on Madera Canyon Road.\par \par \uc2 * March 19, 2008 - Bandits shoot an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  in the leg near Arivaca.\par \par \uc2 * March 31, 2007 - Two Mexican men who told authorities they were trying to hijack a load of drugs open fire on a pickup truck filled with nearly two dozen illegal immigrants, killing two. The shooting occurs southwest of Green Valley.\par \par \uc2 * Feb. 27, 2007 - A member of a Border Patrol special-response team shoots and kills a suspected drug smuggler who had shot at him in the Rock Corral Canyon northwest of Rio Rico.\par \par \uc2 * Feb. 8, 2007 - Bandits open fire with AK-47s on a truck full of illegal immigrants northwest of Tucson, killing two men and one woman.\par \par \uc2 * Jan. 28, 2007 - Bandits attack a vehicle in Eloy containing 12 illegal entrants, killing one.\par \par \uc2 * Jan. 15, 2007 - A trio of bandits open fire on nine Mexican drug runners in the Tumacacori Mountains west of Tubac, killing two and wounding two. Four survivors walk into the community for help.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110129e6cm0003x\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc20}{\*\bkmkend toc20}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 447 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 December 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A8\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Midtown duplex fire is ruled an arson\par \par \uc2 The fire at a midtown duplex Monday night has been ruled arson, making it the third arson fire in Tucson in 10 days.\par \par \uc2 Firefighters went to the residence in the 2800 block of North Flanwill Boulevard at about 8:30 p.m., after receiving 911 calls, said Capt. Tricia Tracy, a Tucson Fire Department spokeswoman. They found one half of the duplex engulfed. That unit was destroyed.\par \par \uc2 Investigators determined the fire had several points of origin inside the home. No one was home at the time, Tracy said.\par \par \uc2 The fire caused about $70,000 in damage, she said.\par \par \uc2 A man living in the second unit was evacuated and displaced, Tracy said.\par \par \uc2 His home had minimal damage.\par \par \uc2 There is no indication that the three arson fires are related, Tracy said.\par \par \uc2 No injuries were reported.\par \par \uc2 Fernanda Echavarri\par \par \uc2 Migrant gets prison in attack on 2 agents\par \par \uc2 An \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  from Sonora was sentenced to prison this week for assaulting two Border Patrol agents during a foot chase near Nogales in which he was shot.\par \par \uc2 Jaime Martinez-Garcia, 26, of Guaymas, was sentenced to six years in prison by U.S. District Judge David C. Bury, according to a news release from the U.S. Attorney's Office.\par \par \uc2 A federal jury in Tucson convicted Martinez-Garcia in August of two counts of assaulting a federal officer and one count of Illegal re-entry after deportation.\par \par \uc2 The incident occurred in May 2009 in Potrero Canyon, west of Nogales, three days after Martinez-Garcia was deported.\par \par \uc2 He fought with one agent then struck a second agent with a large rock. Martinez-Garcia was shot as he was about to hit the second agent with another rock, the release said.\par \par \uc2 Hipolito Corella\par \par \uc2 2 families displaced in mobile-home fires\par \par \uc2 Two mobile home fires displaced two families Tuesday, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 The first blaze was reported at about 10:45 a.m. in Three Points, according to the fire district.\par \par \uc2 The fire, which was ruled accidental, started near a bathroom and water heater, according to the fire district.\par \par \uc2 It caused about $8,000 damage.\par \par \uc2 A mother and her two children - ages 2 and 6- were displaced. Red Cross provided food and clothing to the family.\par \par \uc2 The second fire on the far south side was reported just after 11:30 a.m. in the 10000 block of South Summit Park Road, near South Nogales Highway and Old Vail Connection Road.\par \par \uc2 The fire destroyed the home, leaving five people, including two children, homeless.\par \par \uc2 Investigators determined the blaze was caused by an electrical problem.\par \par \uc2 No injuries were reported in either fire.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110119e6c100035\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc21}{\*\bkmkend toc21}\b \uc2 Details still sketchy in shooting of crosser by Border Patrol agent\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 425 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 November 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 A suspected \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  was shot in the stomach Tuesday morning by a Border Patrol agent northwest of Nogales.\par \par \uc2 The man was still alive at a Tucson hospital as of Tuesday evening.\par \par \uc2 The shooting occurred at 9:30 a.m. in the Walker Canyon area, about two miles northeast of Pena Blanca Lake, said Santa Cruz County Sheriff Tony Estrada. The FBI has taken over the investigation, but the Santa Cruz Sheriff's Office learned the following about the incident:\par \par \uc2 It began when agents with the Border Patrol's horse patrol came upon a group of 12 illegal immigrants in the canyon. The group fled from the agents and one man got knocked down, either by tripping or being bumped by a horse, Estrada said.\par \par \uc2 Shortly after, an agent shot the man on the ground, according to a woman who witnessed the events. She was one of 11 illegal immigrants apprehended by the Border Patrol.\par \par \uc2 It's unknown if the Border Patrol agent intentionally or accidentally shot the man, Estrada said. The agent might have been trying to rein in the horse when the shots were fired, he said. He was shot at least once in the abdomen, Estrada said.\par \par \uc2 "We are not saying that he was shot intentionally," Estrada said. "We are just saying that he was shot."\par \par \uc2 Due the remoteness of the location, the Border Patrol had to walk the wounded man out of the rugged area to a spot where a helicopter could land.\par \par \uc2 The 30-year-old man from Nogales, Sonora, was flown to University Medical Center in Tucson where he was in intensive care Tuesday evening, said Julian Etienne, spokesman for the Mexican Consulate in Tucson. He was talking, which is a good sign, he said. His name was not released.\par \par \uc2 Santa Cruz deputies did not find any guns or drugs at the scene and do not know exactly what happened, Estrada said. The Border Patrol agent involved in the shooting hadn't given Estrada's deputies his account of the incident.\par \par \uc2 Deputies interviewed four of the 11 illegal immigrants in custody, including the woman who apparently was the only one who saw the shooting.\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol spokesman Mario Escalante said the agency couldn't discuss any details of the shooting, citing an FBI investigation.\par \par \uc2 Manuel Johnson, an FBI spokesman, said he couldn't discuss any details yet.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020110108e6bh00001\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc22}{\*\bkmkend toc22}\b \uc2 Border 101\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,788 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 October 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 From congressional races to the gubernatorial showdown, border issues have taken center stage in many campaigns this election season.\par \par \uc2 If you are dizzy from all the talk and rhetoric, you're not alone. So today, we sort out some of the most popular election- season facts, myths and half-truths:\par \par \uc2 Is the border more dangerous than ever?\par \par \uc2 Answer: For people illegally crossing it, yes. For people living near it in Mexico, probably. For people living on the U.S. side of the border, probably not.\par \par \uc2 Some will vehemently disagree with that last statement, pointing to the March killing of Cochise County rancher Robert Krentz and an increase in burglaries in the Portal area as evidence that the level of danger on the U.S. side of the border has increased. But while Cochise County investigators say they tracked footprints back to Mexico, the Krentz crime is unsolved.\par \par \uc2 The FBI's uniform crime reports show violent crime is no more prevalent in border cities than in nonborder cities.\par \par \uc2 Since 2001, the average violent-crime rate in eight border cities declined, and it has remained below the national violent-crime rate since 2005, said an August 2010 report by the Congressional Research Center, which reviewed FBI crime reports from 1998 to 2008.\par \par \uc2 In Tucson and Phoenix - the two largest cities on the smuggling route through Arizona - murder and violent crime decreased from 2005 to 2009, FBI data show.\par \par \uc2 The ratio of assaults on Border Patrol agents dipped 36 percent across the Southwest border from 2007 to 2010. But that ratio increased by 70 percent in the Tucson Sector over the same period. Most of the reported assaults are when rocks are thrown at agents.\par \par \uc2 The danger of crossing the border illegally has increased, though. Illegal immigrants are dying at greater rates than ever in Arizona, likely because the border buildup has prompted smugglers to lead crossers into more remote and dangerous areas.\par \par \uc2 The 252 illegal border crossers found dead along Arizona's stretch of the U.S.-Mexico border excluding Yuma in fiscal 2010 broke the previous record of 234, set in 2007.\par \par \uc2 Is Arizona the epicenter for illegal immigration?\par \par \uc2 Answer: Yes and no.\par \par \uc2 Arizona's stretch of the U.S.-Mexico border is the busiest for illegal immigration, drug smuggling and border deaths, accounting for more than half of all arrests and marijuana seizures. But the state is more of a transit point than a destination.\par \par \uc2 The estimate of 375,000 illegal immigrants living in Arizona puts the state eighth in the U.S. behind California, Texas, Florida, New York, Illinois, New Jersey and Georgia, a September report from the Pew Hispanic Center found.\par \par \uc2 And the number of illegal immigrants living in Arizona dropped from an estimated 475,000 in 2008, the Pew report found.\par \par \uc2 But Arizona has thrust itself into the national spotlight on this issue due to the numerous immigration-enforcement laws passed by the state, including SB 1070.\par \par \uc2 Has the federal government really done nothing to secure the border?\par \par \uc2 Answer: You can question the effectiveness of the billions spent, but there's no denying the massive buildup of border enforcement over the last five to 10 years:\par \par \uc2 * The budget for Customs and Border Protection - the Department of Homeland Security agency responsible for border security - soared to $11.4 billion in fiscal 2010, up 90 percent from $6 billion in fiscal year 2004. That's nearly twice the growth of the Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) budget, which increased 54 percent to $5.7 billion in fiscal 2010, up from $3.7 billion in 2004. ICE is responsible for immigration enforcement at worksites and across the interior of the country.\par \par \uc2 * The number of Border Patrol agents on the U.S.-Mexico border has increased to 17,500, up from 9,700 in 2004. The Tucson Sector, which stretches from New Mexico to Yuma County, now has 3,300 agents, up from 2,100 in 2004 and 1,500 in 2000.\par \par \uc2 * The miles of fencing along the border have grown exponentially. There are now 350 miles of pedestrian fence and 299 miles of vehicle barriers along the U.S.-Mexico border, for a total of 649 miles of barriers. That's up from 143 miles of barriers in 2006.\par \par \uc2 The Tucson Sector has 71 miles of pedestrian fences and 139 miles of vehicle barriers. In 2000, it had 11 miles of pedestrian fences and two miles of vehicle barriers.\par \par \uc2 Pedestrian fences are 12- to 18-foot-high barriers designed to stop, or at least slow down, people. Vehicle barriers are waist- to chest-high and are designed to stop cars.\par \par \uc2 * The agency has spent more than $1 billion since 2006 developing the SBInet "virtual fence," which tracks movement using a network of towers mounted with cameras, sensors and radar. But the program has been plagued by delays and glitches.\par \par \uc2 * In the past five years, the feds have twice sent the National Guard to the border to assist the Border Patrol. In Operation Jump Start, from 2006 to 2008, the government spent $1.2 billion to send 6,000 National Guard troops. In the current Operation Copper Cactus, the government is spending $135 million to send 1,200 troops.\par \par \uc2 * Homeland Security has devoted $225 million to border law enforcement agencies through Operation Stonegarden, including about $51 million to Arizona agencies. The program gives agencies money to pay officers who work overtime shifts aimed at securing the border. The money also buys four-wheel-drive trucks, radios and night- vision goggles.\par \par \uc2 Has the buildup of agents, fences and technology made the border more secure?\par \par \uc2 Answer: Probably, but to what degree is uncertain.\par \par \uc2 Fewer illegal immigrants are crossing the Southwest border, but it's difficult to determine how much of that is attributed to the buildup, because the decrease has coincided with the worst U.S. recession since the Depression.\par \par \uc2 The number of apprehensions by Border Patrol agents on the U.S.- Mexico border plummeted to 447,500 in fiscal year 2010, down from 1.1 million in fiscal year 2004.\par \par \uc2 Homeland Security Secretary Janet Napolitano acknowledges that the weak economy helps explain why fewer people are getting caught crossing the border illegally, and she also credited crackdowns on employers who hire illegal workers. But she said a big reason is enforcement.\par \par \uc2 "The manpower, the technology, the infrastructure all has enabled us to be able to really slow that flow of \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  traffic," she said at a news conference last week near San Diego.\par \par \uc2 Citing the seizures of more drugs, weapons and illicit cash along the Mexican border, Napolitano said: "We now have a border more secure than ever before."\par \par \uc2 But using the same rationale the feds apply to apprehensions - the lower the better - the buildup has not slowed the smuggling of drugs. Marijuana seizures along the U.S.-Mexico border by Border Patrol agents have increased to 2.5 million pounds in fiscal year 2009, up from 1.3 million in 2004.\par \par \uc2 So many people say, 'Build more fence.' Does it work?\par \par \uc2 Answer: Nobody knows for sure.\par \par \uc2 A 2009 report from the Government Accountability Office found that "despite a $2.4 billion investment to build 264 miles of fencing and 226 miles of vehicle barriers in the last five years, the impact of these barriers on border security is unknown because it has not been measured."\par \par \uc2 Proponents of border fencing point to double-layer fencing in San Diego and Yuma as proof that barriers work. Apprehensions dipped there after the fences went up, but the smugglers simply moved their routes.\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol's 262-mile-long Tucson Sector has 71 miles of fencing, but it remains the busiest people- and drug-smuggling route on the border, accounting for nearly half of all arrests and marijuana seizures.\par \par \uc2 The problem with fences is that motivated smugglers and border crossers find ways over, through and around them. Critics call them nothing more than a speed bump. And the international border's diverse terrain, which includes mountains, canyons and rivers, makes a 2,000-mile fence impossible.\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol officials acknowledge that the barriers are not a panacea. But they say they deter, slow and funnel traffic, helping agents gain the upper hand in the ongoing cat-and-mouse game with smugglers.\par \par \uc2 The government has spent $2.4 billion on new fences, and the GAO estimates the life-cycle cost of all the barriers to be $6.5 billion.\par \par \uc2 The buildup of fences and roads along the border could have environmental consequences, too. Fencing has caused flooding and erosion, and it could be fragmenting wildlife habitat.\par \par \uc2 Virtual fences are better for the environment, but despite more than $1 billion spent over five years, the SBInet program has been plagued by glitches and major delays, and has yet to produce a working system. The GAO has questioned whether the time and money spent are a prudent use of limited resources.\par \par \uc2 Has violence from Mexico's raging drug wars spilled over the border?\par \par \uc2 Answer: It's not entirely clear, but most indicators say no.\par \par \uc2 The public shootouts, beheadings and killings that are part of life in northern Mexico due to the ongoing turf battles between drug cartels do not occur in Arizona. But some violence in Arizona may be associated with the illegal smuggling of people and drugs.\par \par \uc2 And there's no way to say spillover violence won't happen.\par \par \uc2 "Currently, U.S. federal officials deny that the recent increase in drug-trafficking-related violence in Mexico has resulted in a spillover into the United States," said an August 2010 report from the Congressional Research Center. "But they acknowledge that the prospect is a serious concern."\par \par \uc2 Is it possible to seal the border?\par \par \uc2 Answer: Probably not.\par \par \uc2 There are some who believe it's possible, such as the Border Patrol agents' union. But even the commissioner of U.S. Customs and Border Protection says the focus should be on controlling the border, not sealing it.\par \par \uc2 "This is not about sealing the border," Commissioner Alan Bersin said in September while in Tucson. "Until we have a legitimate labor market between Mexico and the United States, people will attempt to come here to work."\par \par \uc2 History shows that as long as better-paying jobs await in the U.S., people from Mexico and Latin America will continue to find a way around, through, under and over the gantlet of enforcement.\par \par \uc2 Not even the worst U.S. recession since the Depression has stopped the stream of illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com The Associated Press contributed to this report.\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find extensive coverage of immigration issues at azstarnet.com/border\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020101127e6ao0000y\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc23}{\*\bkmkend toc23}\b \uc2 Illegal entrants are focus of debate\b0\par\par\uc2 ANDREA KELLY   \par \uc2 ANDREA KELLY, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 682 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 October 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Giffords, Kelly clash over 'amnesty' issue\par \par \uc2 In the first debate between candidates running for Congress in Arizona's border District 8, immigration was front and center.\par \par \uc2 The first three questions about amnesty and checkpoints took up nearly a quarter of the hour-long face-off Monday between incumbent Democrat U.S. Rep. Gabrielle Giffords, Republican challenger Jesse Kelly and Libertarian challenger Steve Stoltz.\par \par \uc2 The first question to Giffords was about her support for a path to citizenship for illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 "I don't support amnesty. No one supports amnesty; that's what President Reagan supported," she said. What she supports is the STRIVE Act, which also was sponsored by Republican U.S. Sens. John McCain and Jon Kyl, and Republican U.S. Rep. Jeff Flake, she said.\par \par \uc2 That bill allowed illegal immigrants who, among other things, paid back taxes, fees and fines, and passed a criminal background check, to qualify for citizenship, she said.\par \par \uc2 "You do all of those things - welcome to America," she said.\par \par \uc2 Kelly said the STRIVE Act was, in fact, amnesty. He said the government needs to build a double-layer border fence, and criticized Giffords for "defunding the border fence," referring to a vote Giffords cast against a bill involving funding for the fence. Giffords said the legislation would have taken money from high-tech security measures and put it toward the border fence, which was already funded in a different measure.\par \par \uc2 "What do we have, we have a checkpoint on I-19, and 50 percent of the drugs that come into the United States come through Arizona," Kelly said.\par \par \uc2 Stoltz had a simplified take on citizenship for immigrants.\par \par \uc2 "My rapid path to citizenship is anybody who understands the Constitution should be a citizen if they have a good understanding of English," he said.\par \par \uc2 Entitlement programs such as Social Security and Medicare need to be eliminated, and mixing national troops with local troops is unconstitutional, he said.\par \par \uc2 Kelly was asked how much money needs to be spent studying the effectiveness of checkpoints before a decision is made on whether to keep them.\par \par \uc2 "How much more money needs to be spent? Well, tell me how many more liberals we're going to elect to Washington, D.C.," he said.\par \par \uc2 Kelly said he does not support the DREAM Act, a provision in the STRIVE Act that would have allowed some \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  minors the opportunity for citizenship if they met certain criteria, including getting a college degree or serving in the military.\par \par \uc2 "I do not support the DREAM Act. The path to citizenship begins in your country of citizenship," Kelly said.\par \par \uc2 Giffords said the idea is a "realistic approach" and a "tremendous opportunity" for people who would qualify.\par \par \uc2 Stoltz said the proposal sounded nice but had hidden "gotcha" implications.\par \par \uc2 In her closing statement, Giffords said Kelly used the word "Arizona" a single time during the debate.\par \par \uc2 "I'm not sure who he wants to represent, but it's not us," she said.\par \par \uc2 In response, after the debate, Kelly said, "I said Arizona once; she bankrupted Arizona once," referring to her budget votes in the Legislature before she went to Congress, something he also mentioned during the debate.\par \par \uc2 "She joined with Janet Napolitano to bankrupt the state, then moved on to the federal government to join with (President) Obama and (House Speaker Nancy) Pelosi to bankrupt the country," he said during the debate.\par \par \uc2 The crowd filled 1,300 chairs in the University of Arizona ballroom, and some watched video of the event in an overflow room. People gathered hours before the debate to wave signs and wait in line for seats. The audience also frequently broke into shouts, boos and applause, drowning out the candidates in the debate.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Andrea Kelly at akelly@azstarnet.com or 807- 7790.\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Join a Nov. 2 election-night live chat on StarNet for discussion, updates, a scoreboard of major races, and fun with cartoonist David Fitzsimmons. Sign up now for an e-mail reminder: azstarnet.com/electionchat\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020101117e6aj0000r\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc24}{\*\bkmkend toc24}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 XXXXXXXXX   \par \uc2 XXXXXXXXX, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 545 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 October 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par B6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 3 injured, 2 seriously, in Nogales police chase\par \par \uc2 A 19-year-old man is facing assault charges on suspicion he tried to run down a Nogales, Ariz., police officer during a traffic stop, said Santa Cruz County Sheriff Tony Estrada.\par \par \uc2 Three people were injured, two seriously, when the man's car hit them as he fled, Estrada said.\par \par \uc2 The officer shot at suspect Ivan Aguirre multiple times, grazing him in the head, he said.\par \par \uc2 Estrada gave this account:\par \par \uc2 At about 5 a.m. an officer tried to stop a car for speeding. The car fled onto a dead-end street in downtown Nogales. When the officer approached, the driver drove toward him and the officer fired.\par \par \uc2 The man drove off and hit another vehicle, injuring a mother, her 14-year-old daughter and 9-year-old son. The mother and daughter were flown to Tucson with life-threatening injuries; the son was treated at the scene.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 Officials suspect man died of exposure\par \par \uc2 Authorities found the body of a 28-year-old Mexican man Saturday in a remote area near the Santa Cruz County line.\par \par \uc2 The man was an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  from Mexico, said Santa Cruz County Sheriff Tony Estrada.\par \par \uc2 There were no signs of trauma or foul play, he said. Authorities suspect the man died of exposure.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 Man is found dead on ranch near Elfrida\par \par \uc2 A man's body was found on a ranch northeast of Elfrida Saturday, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 The ranch owner called authorities just before 11 a.m., said Carol Capas, a Cochise County Sheriff's Office spokeswoman.\par \par \uc2 Sheriff's deputies found a man wrapped in a blanket with severe head trauma, Capas said. He was identified as James W. Green, 50, of Sunizona.\par \par \uc2 Authorities believe he was left on the property, about 110 miles southeast of Tucson, north of Douglas, between 8 a.m. and 10 a.m. Saturday. They did not yet know how long he had been dead.\par \par \uc2 An investigation is continuing.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 2 people rescued from apartment fire\par \par \uc2 Firefighters rescued two people and two dogs from a burning apartment complex on the south side Friday morning.\par \par \uc2 A woman called 911 around 7:30 a.m. to report a fire in her kitchen, said Capt. Trish Tracy, a spokeswoman for the Tucson Fire Department. Firefighters found smoke and flames coming from a second- floor apartment of the three-story unit, in the 2200 block of North Camino Castile, near South 12th Avenue and West Valencia Road.\par \par \uc2 Firefighters rescued the woman's dog, then began evacuating the entire unit, Tracy said. Two people and a dog were trapped in the unit directly upstairs from the woman's apartment, but firefighters took them to safety.\par \par \uc2 Two people were treated for minor injuries at the scene and a firefighter was taken to a hospital for evaluation.\par \par \uc2 The fire left seven people homeless, but management at the apartment complex is providing free housing until repairs can be made, Tracy said.\par \par \uc2 Officials estimate the damage at $25,000.\par \par \uc2 L. Anne Newell\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the city of Tucson, updated every morning with the previous day's data, at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020101113e6ah0000h\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc25}{\*\bkmkend toc25}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 393 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 October 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Man struck while crossing street on north side dies\par \par \uc2 A 59-year-old man was killed Wednesday while crossing a street on the north side.\par \par \uc2 The man walked into the path of an oncoming vehicle near North First Avenue and East Roger Road just before 6 a.m., said Sgt. Diana Lopez, a Tucson Police Department spokeswoman.\par \par \uc2 He was taken to University Medical Center, where he was pronounced dead, Lopez said.\par \par \uc2 The man was crossing from east to west near the intersection when he was hit, she said.\par \par \uc2 He was not in a crosswalk, she said.\par \par \uc2 No citations were issued.\par \par \uc2 The Police Department has not released the man's name pending notification of his relatives.\par \par \uc2 Alex Dalenberg and Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 15-month term ordered in human-smuggling case\par \par \uc2 A 52-year-old Tucson man who smuggled more than 100 illegal immigrants into the United States has been sentenced to 15 months in federal prison.\par \par \uc2 The human-smuggling organization Felizardo Soto-Soto was involved in used shuttle companies to move illegal immigrants from Tucson to stash houses in the Phoenix area, according to a news release from the U.S. Attorney's Office.\par \par \uc2 Soto-Soto pleaded guilty to conspiracy to transport and harbor illegal aliens and was sentenced Oct. 7 by U.S. District Judge Cindy Jorgenson.\par \par \uc2 He said he was paid between $50 and $75 for each \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  smuggled between August 2007 and April 2010.\par \par \uc2 Rikki Mitchell\par \par \uc2 Partially burned body discovered near airport\par \par \uc2 A truck driver found the partially burned body of a man Wednesday behind Tucson International Airport, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 Tucson Airport Authority police and Pima County sheriff's deputies went to the area near East Old Vail Road and South Swan Road after receiving a 911 call from the truck driver, who had stopped to stretch his legs, said Lt. Timothy Taylor, a Tucson Airport Authority Police Department spokesman.\par \par \uc2 Investigators were still trying to determine the cause of death, the victim's identity and how long the body had been in the desert, Taylor said.\par \par \uc2 Authorities said they suspect the body was burned to cover up evidence associated with the death.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the city of Tucson, updated every morning with the previous day's data, at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020101105e6ae0001f\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc26}{\*\bkmkend toc26}\b \uc2 Neighborhood Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 COLEY WARD, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 366 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 October 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par B6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 FOOTHILLS\par \par \uc2 St. Francis church launches 'Cultivating Compassion' series\par \par \uc2 St. Francis in the Foothills United Methodist Church will begin its four-part series, "Cultivating Compassion," today at the church, 4625 E. River Road.\par \par \uc2 The first session, a program on "Compassionate Communication," will begin at 10:45 a.m. It will discuss how world views and values shape language.\par \par \uc2 On Oct. 17, a panel discussion on "Compassion for People on the Margins" will feature an ex-offender, a person with mental illness and an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The next two programs will be "Compassion in the Workplace" on Oct. 24 and "Compassionate Conversations - Now We Take It Into the World" on Oct. 31.\par \par \uc2 For more information, call the church at 299-9063.\par \par \uc2 EAST SIDE\par \par \uc2 Interfaith Community Services to host volunteer orientations\par \par \uc2 Interfaith Community Services will host a volunteer orientation from 9:30 a.m. to noon Friday at Fountain of Life Lutheran Church, 710 S. Kolb Road.\par \par \uc2 The agency is looking for volunteers to transport seniors or disabled people to medical appointments or shopping, and help with calls or visits, home repairs, mail and paperwork. It also needs volunteers to answer phones at the agency's east-side office, 8701 E. Old Spanish Trail.\par \par \uc2 Working or retired nurses, social workers or other health- related professionals are needed to take health and safety assessments of seniors and disabled individuals interested in receiving services.\par \par \uc2 For more information, contact Sandi Brickley at 297-2738, Ext. 217, or sbrickley@icstucson.org\par \par \uc2 Interfaith Community Services will host two more volunteer orientations on Oct. 20 and Nov. 17 at the agency's office, 2820 W. Ina Road.\par \par \uc2 MIDTOWN\par \par \uc2 Jazz Sunday at St. Mark's church will showcase local musicians\par \par \uc2 St. Mark's Presbyterian Church will host its seventh annual Jazz Sunday on Oct. 17.\par \par \uc2 The service will start at 11 a.m. at the church, 3809 E. Third St.\par \par \uc2 The service will feature all jazz music and will showcase local jazz artists such as harpist Christine Vivona, and jazz trombonist and keyboardist Rob Boone.\par \par \uc2 For more information call the church at 325-1001.\par \par \uc2 E-mail Neighborhood briefs to Jamar Younger at jyounger@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020101102e6aa0000n\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc27}{\*\bkmkend toc27}\b \uc2 Illegal immigrant\uc2  is second here to get reprieve from deportation\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,347 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 September 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 A Tucson man scheduled for deportation today will be able to stay long enough to see his daughter graduate from high school after receiving a one-year federal deferral.\par \par \uc2 Alfonso Morales-Macias, a 40-year-old father of two who has has lived illegally in the U.S. for 20 years, learned Wednesday night that he won't be deported to Mexico, said Phoenix attorney Mel Rodis, who led a campaign to help him.\par \par \uc2 No one was more happy than his daughter, Ana Morales, 18, a senior at Sunnyside High School. She and her brother, 11-year-old Alfonso Morales Jr., were born in Tucson and are U.S. citizens.\par \par \uc2 "I'm really happy because he's going to be able to stay with us and he's going to be here for my graduation in May," said Morales, who hopes to study to be a veterinarian at the University of Arizona.\par \par \uc2 Morales-Macias is the second \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  living in Tucson who has been granted a once-rare deferral from deportation in the last two months. In early August, Marlen Moreno Peralta, a 28-year- old mother of two, was granted one-year deferred action on deportation orders.\par \par \uc2 Both Tucsonans appear to be among a growing contingent of illegal immigrants who are being allowed to stay in the U.S. because they were either brought here as children, like Moreno, or who have been living here since 1996, like Morales-Macias.\par \par \uc2 A leaked internal memo from U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services that surfaced during the summer reveals a suggestion to provide relief to two groups of illegal immigrants facing deportation: people brought here as children who would qualify for the DREAM (Development, Relief, and Education for Alien Minors) Act, and people who have been living here continuously since 1996. The year is a move that would bump up the qualifying date from Jan. 1, 1972, in a section of immigration law.\par \par \uc2 "Rather than making deferred action widely available to hundreds of thousands and as a non-legislative version of 'amnesty,' USCIS could tailor the use of this discretionary option for particular groups," the memo said.\par \par \uc2 Morales-Macias came to the U.S. more than two decades ago on a tourist visa and overstayed. He would fit into the second category for deferral. Moreno came to the U.S. illegally with her parents when she was 13 years old. She'd qualify under the DREAM Act, which was rejected this week by the Senate. Moreno was facing deportation stemming from a identity-theft case arrest at a north-side \uc2 Panda Express\uc2  restaurant in 2008.\par \par \uc2 Immigration and Customs Enforcement officials didn't divulge why Morales-Macias was given a deferral, but agency spokesman Vincent Picard said in an e-mailed statement that deferred action is one tool used to make sure the agency is using its limited resources to "achieve the greatest impact under the immigration laws." The agency focuses deportation efforts on criminal illegal immigrants, recent border violators and people who try to abuse the system through fraud, he said.\par \par \uc2 The agency considers several factors when deciding whom it grants deferred status to, including criminal history, immigration history and equities in the U.S., he said. The deferred action doesn't give Morales-Macias legal status, but it gives him more time to "normalize his status," Picard said.\par \par \uc2 Morales-Macias' attorney, Margo Cowan, said she doesn't know if he was chosen because he fits into the category outlined in the leaked memo or simply because he's an exemplary man with great kids. Immigration officials have long had the discretion to grant relief for cases such as his, she said.\par \par \uc2 The action, which will allow Morales-Macias to work legally, can be renewed for an additional year. But he still faces an uncertain future because his wife does not have legal status either, meaning he has no avenue to apply for legal residence.\par \par \uc2 "We're hoping there will be comprehensive immigration reform," Rodis said.\par \par \uc2 He said Morales-Macias and his wife came to Tucson 20 years ago from Nayarit, Mexico, with tourist visas. He has no criminal record and is an avid churchgoer, and his children are both outstanding students, Rodis said. Their son, Alfonso Morales Jr., is in the sixth grade at Sierra Middle School, where he is a student body treasurer and is in the gifted and talented classes.\par \par \uc2 "Someone who has been here for 20 years, a taxpayer, a hard worker, a homeowner, deserves to be here," Rodis said. "Deporting him would have been a miscarriage of justice."\par \par \uc2 Morales-Macias' troubles began in September 2007, when he was arrested by immigration agents while working for a contracted janitorial service at a Tucson Target store, Rodis said. After being held in detention, he posted an immigration bond that allowed him to stay with his family while he and his attorney challenged his deportation. But he had exhausted all of his options, and he was set to be deported today.\par \par \uc2 "We are all so happy that I can stay here," Morales-Macias said Thursday. "More than anything, this is for my daughter."\par \par \uc2 In the cases of both Morales-Macias and Moreno, Southern Arizona humanitarian groups launched campaigns that included phone calls, e- mails and faxes to the Department of Homeland Security asking for a reprieve. In both cases, news of the deferral came just days after supporters held news conferences to garner more support for their cases.\par \par \uc2 It's possible that the Obama administration is handpicking sympathetic people such as Moreno and Morales-Macias to grant deferral to gain favor with immigrant advocates while avoiding alienating mainstream voters who favor more immigration enforcement, said Steve Camarota, director of research for the Center for Immigration Studies, a Washington-based organization that advocates for slowing immigration.\par \par \uc2 "It's one guy; he's pretty sympathetic; nobody notices that much," Camarota said. "Whereas for the advocacy group that is pushing for it, and for this one guy, it means a lot."\par \par \uc2 Camarota said he's not opposed to selecting certain deserving people for pardons, but the problem is that too many people are manipulating the system. He points to the fact that there are still 500,000 fugitive illegal immigrants in the U.S. who were given deportation orders and never showed up.\par \par \uc2 "The basic idea of tempering justice with mercy is sound and we ought to have it, and this guy may well qualify," Camarota said. "But the rule of law is being mocked. The rule of law is so weak that we don't need to be thinking about making exceptions."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find extensive coverage of immigration issues at azstarnet.com/border\par \par \uc2 Leaked memo\par \par \uc2 This section from a leaked memo from U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services, titled "Administrative Alternatives to Comprehensive Immigration Reform," might explain why Alfonso Morales- Macias was granted a deferral from deportation:\par \par \uc2 "While it is theoretically possible to grant deferred action to an unrestricted number of unlawfully present individuals, doing so would likely be controversial, not to mention expensive. Presently no specific application form or fee is required to request or receive deferred action. Were USCIS to increase significantly the use of deferred action, the agency would either require a separate appropriation or independent funding stream. Alternatively, USCIS could design and seek expedited approval of a dedicated deferred action form and require a filing fee.\par \par \uc2 "Rather than making deferred action widely available to hundreds of thousands and as a non-legislative version of 'amnesty,' USCIS could tailor the use of this discretionary option for particular groups such as individuals who would be eligible for relief under the DREAM Act (an estimated 50,000), or under Section 249 of the Act (Registry), who have resided in the U.S. since 1996 (or as of a different date designed to move forward the Registry provision now limited to entries before January 1, 1972)."\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020101005e69o0005r\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc28}{\*\bkmkend toc28}\b \uc2 US allows new water stations by border\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,077 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 September 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 55-gallon drums for migrants are OK'd, but rules will be strict\par \par \uc2 A new U.S. Fish and Wildlife policy could open the door for more water stations on border public lands to aid illegal immigrants, but humanitarian groups will have to follow stringent rules.\par \par \uc2 A final compatibility determination released by the federal agency allows groups to request permits for stationary, 55-gallon water drums located near roads in already disturbed areas.\par \par \uc2 The regulations basically endorse the methods used for the last 10 years by Tucson-based Humane Borders, which has had three water tanks on the Buenos Aires National Wildlife Refuge but has been denied requests to put more on several occasions, including in October 2009.\par \par \uc2 Humane Borders founder Robin Hoover applauded the agency's decision.\par \par \uc2 "People ought to be applying for water stations across Southern Arizona right now," Hoover said. "You have a blueprint to do it."\par \par \uc2 Humanitarian groups put out water in an effort to save lives. Nearly 2,000 illegal borders crossers have been found dead in Arizona since 2001, and this year has been one of the worst yet.\par \par \uc2 The ruling didn't go over well with all Southern Arizona humanitarian aid groups, though. It prohibits the methods used by No More Deaths and Samaritans. They put out water in one-gallon jugs along trails.\par \par \uc2 "We are not pleased," said Gene Lefebvre, a retired minister and co-founder of No More Deaths. "We are not going to take any big action, but we are not pleased."\par \par \uc2 No More Deaths officials are upset because they reached a compromise with Buenos Aires National Wildlife Refuge and Fish and Wildlife officials earlier this year that said they would be able to put 1-gallon waters jugs at specified locations as long as they were tethered to trees.\par \par \uc2 The deal culminated a nearly two-year standoff between the two sides that included 15 volunteers being issued littering tickets for putting out the jugs. After the compromise was reached, a federal prosecutor asked the court to dismiss charges against 13 people who had been cited.\par \par \uc2 In the Fish and Wildlife draft compatibility determination issued in April, the agency said it was "evaluating" allowing more water stations, from 1-gallon to 55 gallons. It said the stations could be placed "strategically" on or near existing trails.\par \par \uc2 But following an agency review and public comment period where they received more than 1,100 comments from 811 people, Fish and Wildlife officials concluded the 1-gallon jugs were not the best approach, said agency spokesman Jose Viramontes.\par \par \uc2 One reason was concern about litter.\par \par \uc2 "If an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  is not carrying his or her own container, there is a possibility that tethered containers could be cut from the tether, carried along the trail and later discarded on the refuge," the document says. "Hundreds of unpermitted 1-gallon containers previously deposited (not tethered) on \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  trails have been found discarded throughout the refuge."\par \par \uc2 Another concern was that putting out water on existing smuggling trails could promote more illegal traffic through the refuge, Viramontes said.\par \par \uc2 "It may actually promote passage through the refuge," Viramontes said.\par \par \uc2 Lefebvre and fellow No More Deaths volunteer Dan Millis scoffed at that contention. Millis called it "ridiculous to say our water lures people anywhere." Millis had his 2008 littering conviction overturned by a federal appeals court.\par \par \uc2 "Our water is not what's causing people to come through the desert," said Millis, who works for the Grand Canyon Chapter of the Sierra Club. "The failed U.S. border policy of militarizing the border is what has caused people to come through the desert."\par \par \uc2 Lefebvre declined to say whether No More Deaths volunteers will continue to put out 1-gallon water jugs on the refuge, only saying, "We are just going ahead of with our work. We've got to stand by our commitment to give humanitarian aid to migrants."\par \par \uc2 Fish and Wildlife officials say they will continue to issue citations to people they observe not complying with the new guidelines. But Viramontes said the agency is hopeful there will be no more issues with No More Deaths volunteers.\par \par \uc2 "Our hope is that No More Deaths will come forward with some requests similar to this, so we can permit this activity," Viramontes said. "We are open to more water stations on the refuge."\par \par \uc2 But while No More Deaths is pleased that Humane Borders may be able to set up more stationary water stations they still believe the 1-gallon jugs are the best tool in remote terrain, Lefebvre said.\par \par \uc2 Humane Borders' new executive director, Sofia Gomez, said the organization is currently re-assessing the locations of all of its 38 water stations in Arizona to make sure they are in locations being used by illegal immigrants. They are looking at their own data of water usage and other data from No More Deaths, the Border Patrol and the Pima County Medical Examiner's Office, she said.\par \par \uc2 "We are working to assess our water distribution," Gomez said. "Where we need to be now versus where we were when we started out 10 years ago."\par \par \uc2 It's possible they'll ask for additional water stations on the Buenos Aires refuge but they haven't made that decision yet, she said. They may also ask to put their blue flags on existing water wells, Gomez said. The organization is pleased with the rules, and said they just need to clarify a few of the stipulations.\par \par \uc2 Hoover said No More Deaths should put their energies toward fighting to get permission to put out water stations on the Tohono O'odham Reservation and other dangerous lands.\par \par \uc2 "They are fighting a good battle to put water in the desert, but they are fighting the wrong battle when they are fighting over the size of the water container," Hoover said.\par \par \uc2 Humane Borders restarted conversations with Tohono O'odham Nation officials this summer about putting water stations out there but nothing has changed yet, Gomez said.\par \par \uc2 More bodies are found along the 75 miles of international border the Tohono O'odham Nation shares with Mexico than any other stretch of Arizona's border. But the nation has never allowed humanitarian groups to put out water stations.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@.com.\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find extensive coverage of border and immigration issues at azstarnet.com/border\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100918e69400016\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc29}{\*\bkmkend toc29}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 460 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 August 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Man, 20, indicted in death during brawl\par \par \uc2 A 20-year-old Tucson man has been indicted on a manslaughter charge in connection with the death of another man during a brawl outside an east-side convenience store.\par \par \uc2 Harold Franklin Kimmel is accused of killing Joseph Kaplinski, 28, on July 24, according to an indictment returned Tuesday afternoon in Pima County Superior Court.\par \par \uc2 Tucson police received a report about a fight at the Catalina Mart, 7910 E. Golf Links Road, at about 12:30 a.m., and when they arrived, they found Kaplinski in the parking lot with life- threatening injuries. He died at University Medical Center, and Kimmel was arrested on suspicion of second-degree murder.\par \par \uc2 Grand jurors indicted Kimmel on the less serious charge of manslaughter, however.\par \par \uc2 Kim Smith\par \par \uc2 Today's locations for police radar vans\par \par \uc2 The city's two police radar vans are scheduled to snap photographs of speeders at these locations today, according to the Tucson Police Department:\par \par \uc2 * 6 to 9 a.m.: On East Grant Road between North Campbell Avenue and North Country Club Road; and on East Fifth Street between North Country Club Road and North Alvernon Way.\par \par \uc2 * 9:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m.: On East Limberlost Road between North First Avenue and North Mountain Avenue; and on East Fort Lowell Road between North Campbell Avenue and North Tucson Boulevard.\par \par \uc2 * 1:30 to 4:30 p.m.: On East Fort Lowell Road between North Columbus Boulevard and North Alvernon Way; and on South Park Avenue between East Ajo Way and East Irvington Road.\par \par \uc2 * 5 to 8:30 p.m.: On North Rosemont Boulevard between East Broadway and East Fifth Street; and on East Fort Lowell between North Columbus Boulevard and North Alvernon Way.\par \par \uc2 2 Mexicans admit taking hostages\par \par \uc2 Two Mexican citizens face between eight and 12 years in federal prison after pleading guilty Tuesday to involvement in an armed standoff with federal agents at an \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  stash house south of Tucson.\par \par \uc2 Faustino Chiquete-Reyes, 20, and Nestor Chiquete-Reyes, 27, each pleaded guilty to one count of hostage taking, according to documents filed in U.S. District Court.\par \par \uc2 They were among five people arrested on Dec. 1 at a house near South Nogales Highway and Old Vail Connection Road where 19 illegal immigrants were discovered, court records say.\par \par \uc2 Two other men arrested in the raid have pleaded guilty and face similar eight- to 12-year sentences. A fifth defendant, 25-year-old Maria Lourdes Ibarra, is scheduled for trial in October.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the city of Tucson, updated every morning with the previous day's data, at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100818e68500016\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc30}{\*\bkmkend toc30}\b \uc2 WHAT JUDGE BOLTON blocked - and THE REASONS SHE GAVE\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 405 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 July 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Requiring police officers to attempt to check the immigration status of those they have stopped if there is reason to suspect they are in the U.S. illegally.\par \par \uc2 Why: "Legal residents will certainly be swept up by this requirement," and "their liberty will be restricted while their status is checked."\par \par \uc2 Forbidding police to release anyone they have arrested until that person's immigration status is determined.\par \par \uc2 Why: In Tucson alone, nearly 37,000 people per year who are "arrested" by police are cited and released at the scene. Checking all of them is "likely to burden Immigration and Customs Enforcement" and divert resources from other federal responsibilities.\par \par \uc2 Making it a violation of Arizona law for anyone who is not a citizen to fail to carry documentation.\par \par \uc2 Why: The provision "imposes an unacceptable burden on lawfully present aliens. ... The federal government has long rejected a system by which aliens' papers are routinely demanded and checked."\par \par \uc2 Creating a new state crime for trying to secure work while not a legal resident.\par \par \uc2 Why: It "conflicts with a comprehensive federal scheme" that does not penalize people who look for work.\par \par \uc2 Allowing police to make warrantless arrests when there is a belief that the people have committed offenses that allow them to be removed from the United States.\par \par \uc2 Why: The laws determining if an immigrant can be deported are complex. "There is a substantial likelihood that officers will wrongfully arrest legal resident aliens."\par \par \uc2 What was left in / Page A6\par \par \uc2 What was left IN\par \par \uc2 * Making it a crime to stop a vehicle in traffic to hire a day laborer or for someone looking for work to get into a stopped vehicle.\par \par \uc2 * Requiring state officials to work with the federal government regarding illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 * Allowing state residents to file suit against any agency, official, city or county for adopting policies that restrict the ability of workers to enforce federal immigration law "to less than the full extent permitted by federal law."\par \par \uc2 Why: The Obama administration did not challenge those provisions of the law.\par \par \uc2 * Creating a separate crime for transporting or harboring an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , or encouraging or inducing an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  to come to or live in Arizona.\par \par \uc2 Why: The judge rejected arguments that this interferes with interstate commerce.\par \par \uc2 Compiled by reporter Howard Fischer of Capitol Media Services from U.S. District Judge Susan Bolton's 36-page ruling\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100810e67t0001x\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc31}{\*\bkmkend toc31}\b \uc2 Immigration issue for GOP in ACC primary\b0\par\par\uc2 DAVID WICHNER   \par \uc2 DAVID WICHNER, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,075 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 July 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 The usually staid election race for the Arizona Corporation Commission has been sidetracked by a hot-button issue over which the utility panel has little control: illegal immigration.\par \par \uc2 But three Republican candidates for the commission have plenty of more normal issues to talk about, as two seats on the five-member commission are up for grabs in November.\par \par \uc2 Squaring off in the Republican primary are incumbent Gary Pierce, a former auto dealer and state legislator; former state Senate President Brenda Burns; and Barry Wong, a Phoenix business attorney who served on the commission as an appointee for six months in 2006.\par \par \uc2 The campaign has been marked by the fallout of comments made by Wong regarding Arizona's tough new immigration law.\par \par \uc2 Wong made national news recently when he said the Corporation Commission could help curb illegal immigration by requiring utilities to deny service to people who can't prove U.S. citizenship.\par \par \uc2 Pierce joined the fray, saying he would do what he can to stop the flow of Arizona-generated electricity to Los Angeles in response to that city's vote to boycott Arizona over SB 1070.\par \par \uc2 But beyond the uproar over those statements, neither of which is possible, the candidates have plenty of bread-and-butter utility issues on their plates.\par \par \uc2 Pierce, 57, says his major priority is keeping utility rates stable and balanced.\par \par \uc2 "To attract more business, we have to have stable rates," he said.\par \par \uc2 He also wants to streamline the commission's operations, particularly the process for incorporating limited liability companies (LLCs) by using more online filing.\par \par \uc2 Burns, 59, says her top priority is "meeting the needs of our growing population while keeping rates as low as possible."\par \par \uc2 "I'm a huge proponent of long-term planning," she said, praising a recent move by the commission to require electric utilities to file reports every two years on how they plan to meet energy needs over the next 15 years.\par \par \uc2 She also wants to streamline commission operations, to shorten the time it takes to approve new rates, allow the public to access more information and monitor hearings online, and limit fees the commission charges.\par \par \uc2 Wong, a University of Arizona law school alumnus, says among his top goals is careful planning to meet energy needs he believes will rise rapidly when the recession gives way to new growth.\par \par \uc2 "We need to have a very broad mix of energy sources, which would include nuclear power, renewables like solar and wind, natural gas and clean coal," he said.\par \par \uc2 Wong say's he'll work to keep rates as low as possible, citing his experience on an \uc2 Arizona Public Service Co\uc2 . rate case during his 2006 stint on the commission and his background in law and accounting.\par \par \uc2 Wong said denying electric service to illegal immigrants is part of his rate strategy, contending a rising \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  population hastens the need to build new power plants.\par \par \uc2 Wong also said he would focus on water conservation, prompting the state's 300-plus regulated water companies to take conservation steps and limiting the use of groundwater by power-plant operators.\par \par \uc2 All three Republican contenders say they support the state's Renewable Energy Standard, which requires utilities to get 15 percent of their power from renewable sources by 2025.\par \par \uc2 To push renewable energy, the commission has created a system of rebates for renewable-energy installations like rooftop solar water heaters and photovoltaics, paid for by monthly surcharges on ratepayers' bills.\par \par \uc2 The rebates have become so popular money has run out in some cases, prompting utilities including TEP to seek lower rebates and higher surcharges.\par \par \uc2 Wong said he remains a big backer of so-called "distributed" solar energy - installations on the site of users, such as rooftop photovoltaics. Wong, who serves on the Arizona Power Plant and Transmission Line Siting Committee, said utility-operated solar power plants are important, but he's concerned with water usage.\par \par \uc2 Burns said she strongly supports the renewable standard, but amid concerns surcharges are getting too high, she said she would look for other ways to fund the program, though she didn't have specifics.\par \par \uc2 "We need to make sure the ratepayer is getting the economic and environmental benefit," she said, adding she hopes falling prices for solar equipment will help drive future installations without the need for rebates.\par \par \uc2 Pierce said the standard is fine the way it is, and the market will dictate any increase in the standard.\par \par \uc2 "That's the way this is intended to go, that we'd reduce and remove subsidies because renewables become a way of life," he said.\par \par \uc2 All three Republicans said they would revisit commission decisions in APS and TEP rate cases which changed the rules for extending power lines to new homes, shifting thousands of dollars in costs for each line to developers or homeowners.\par \par \uc2 Addressing complaints the extension costs are stifling rural development, the commission is currently holding statewide public meetings on the issue.\par \par \uc2 "It's really harming rural Arizona, because what the commission decided was, new customers were not of value, and that's simply not the case," Pierce said.\par \par \uc2 Pierce said that after initially voting for the first APS rate case that cut the extensions, he has since tried to restore the free extension footage and pushed for the current public discussions.\par \par \uc2 Burns said she is closely monitoring the public meetings on the extension issue and is concerned about the impact on development.\par \par \uc2 Wong said he's heard some of the complaints and is committed to finding a "middle ground" that would help rural development while protecting ratepayers.\par \par \uc2 All three Republicans say they oppose - and the state should oppose - a move by the federal government to impose any kind of "carbon tax" or cap-and-trade regulation on utilities and other industries.\par \par \uc2 Contact Assistant Business Editor David Wichner at dwichner@azstarnet.com or 573-4181.\par \par \uc2 CANDIDATEs' BACKGROUNDS\par \par \uc2 Brenda Burns\par \par \uc2 Home: Scottsdale\par \par \uc2 Age: 59\par \par \uc2 Occupation: Former real-estate agent and consultant\par \par \uc2 Political experience: State representative 1987 to 1994 (two years as majority leader) state senator, 1995 to 2002, (four years as president.)\par \par \uc2 Gary Pierce\par \par \uc2 Home: Mesa\par \par \uc2 Age: 57\par \par \uc2 Occupation: Corporation Commissioner; marketing consultant; former auto dealer.\par \par \uc2 Political experience: State representative, 2001-2006 (majority whip, 2005-2006); former Yuma County supervisor\par \par \uc2 Barry Wong\par \par \uc2 Home: Phoenix\par \par \uc2 Age: 51\par \par \uc2 Occupation: Business attorney\par \par \uc2 Political experience: State representative, 1993-2000; Corporation Commission appointed member, 2006\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100810e67r00005\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc32}{\*\bkmkend toc32}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 561 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 July 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Officials seek robber of Kinney Road bank\par \par \uc2 A woman who appeared to be in her 60s robbed a bank in the Tucson Mountains area on Wednesday afternoon, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 The woman entered the \uc2 Bank of the West\uc2  branch at 3041 S. Kinney Road at about 3 p.m., flashed a handgun at a teller and demanded money, a Pima County Sheriff's Department news release says.\par \par \uc2 The woman left the bank with an undisclosed amount of cash and drove off in a white, two-door Hyundai Tiburon, the release said.\par \par \uc2 The woman is believed to be 60 to 70 years old and about 5 feet, 6 inches tall. Anyone with information is asked to call 911 or 88- CRIME.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 24-year term possible in illegal-migrant case\par \par \uc2 A 21-year-old Mexican citizen faces 11 to 24 years in federal prison after pleading guilty to orchestrating an \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  drop house on the northwest side.\par \par \uc2 Oscar Fernando Monroy-Reyes was one of four people arrested on March 25 when Pima County sheriff's deputies were called to a home near West Ina Road and North Camino de la Tierra where four illegal immigrants had been held hostage for several days, U.S. District Court documents state.\par \par \uc2 The drop house was discovered after one of the men being held in the house escaped and sought refuge at a neighboring house, court records say.\par \par \uc2 The immigrants told authorities they had been held at gunpoint for several days after each was unable to pay his smuggling fee, which had been raised from $1,500 to $3,500 after the group's arrival at the drop house, court records say.\par \par \uc2 One of the smugglers struck a migrant in the head with the butt of a handgun, causing injury, the records say.\par \par \uc2 Monroy-Reyes was arrested along with fellow Mexican nationals Elsa Carillo-Banuelos, 26, Jose Luis Bautista-Barajas and a 17-year- old boy, who was later transferred to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement custody and was returned to Mexico, court records say.\par \par \uc2 Monroy-Reyes, Carillo-Banuelos and Bautista-Barajas were each indicted in April on federal alien-smuggling, hostage-taking and weapons charges.\par \par \uc2 Monroy-Reyes' plea agreement calls for a sentence of about 111/4 to 24 1/2 years. The cases against the two other defendants are still pending.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Suspect in local killing arrested in Las Vegas\par \par \uc2 A Tucson man wanted in connection with Saturday's east-side shooting death of a 36-year-old man was arrested in Las Vegas, police said.\par \par \uc2 Aaron Wade Smiley, 30, was arrested on Thursday by U.S. marshals and Nevada authorities. He is suspected of killing Johnny Isaac Meza, who was a guest at a home in the 7600 block of East Queen Palm Circle, near South Pantano and East Escalante roads, according to a Tucson Police Department news release.\par \par \uc2 Meza was dropped off at St. Joseph's Hospital, where he died of his injuries, police said.\par \par \uc2 Tucson police said they obtained an arrest warrant for Smiley after he fled from the scene of the shooting.\par \par \uc2 Smiley, who is awaiting extradition to Tucson, faces a first- degree murder charge.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the city of Tucson at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100805e67n0000i\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc33}{\*\bkmkend toc33}\b \uc2 GAO: US can do better in fighting smuggling\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 677 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 July 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 DHS also faulted on success gauge\par \par \uc2 The Department of Homeland Security should use its anti- smuggling resources more wisely and do more to measure the effectiveness of its initiatives, the government's investigative arm said in a report.\par \par \uc2 A Government Accountability Office examination of the department's investigative efforts aimed at slowing \uc2 illegal- immigrant\uc2  smuggling concluded that despite an increase in time spent on investigations, "an opportunity exists to better leverage resources," the report says.\par \par \uc2 The report, which was presented Thursday during a House hearing on the government's anti-smuggling efforts, singled out the Mexican Interior Repatriation Program as an example of where the agency has failed to develop measures to gauge if the program has met its objectives.\par \par \uc2 Under the voluntary program that runs each summer, non-criminal Mexican illegal immigrants caught by the Border Patrol in Arizona are offered flights home to Mexico City. The program's objective is to disrupt the smuggling cycle and save lives during the hottest months. It is currently going on for the seventh consecutive year.\par \par \uc2 The report says Immigration and Customs Enforcement, the Homeland Security agency that runs the repatriation program, doesn't know whether it is effective "because it lacks performance measures for the program."\par \par \uc2 Further, it says "lack of accurate and consistent data" has limited the ability of Customs and Border Protection, parent agency of the Border Patrol, to evaluate its programs to curtail \uc2 illegal- immigrant\uc2  smuggling.\par \par \uc2 Homeland Security officials did not agree with the GAO's recommendation to measure the program's performance because the agency "believes that doing so would shift its focus away from the program's original lifesaving intent," the report says.\par \par \uc2 Since the binational Mexican Interior Repatriation Program began in 2004, the U.S. government has spent about $71 million to fly nearly 93,000 non-criminal Mexican illegal immigrants to Mexico City.\par \par \uc2 More than 1,850 illegal border crossers have been found dead in Arizona's desert in the last decade, with the yearly death toll hovering around 200 a year.\par \par \uc2 It's not the first time the effectiveness of the program has been questioned. A 2008 article by the Arizona Daily Star found that evidence showed the binational program had not made any substantial difference in border smuggling or desert deaths.\par \par \uc2 And two years earlier, the GAO concluded that the then 2-year- old program had done nothing to reduce desert deaths.\par \par \uc2 In addition to the recommendation regarding the repatriation program, this latest GAO report urges Homeland Security to study the possibility of expanding a program where ICE's Office of Detention and Removal Operations transports and processes apprehended illegal immigrants, freeing up ICE investigators to focus on targeting the smuggling organizations. The program has been used in Phoenix since 2006 but is not used elsewhere.\par \par \uc2 The GAO also recommended that the agency develop performance measures for its asset seizures and consider using financial investigative techniques used by the Arizona attorney general task force to disrupt smuggling operations by seizing assets.\par \par \uc2 "The task force seized millions of dollars and disrupted alien smuggling operations by following cash transactions flowing through money transmitters that serve as the primary method of payment to those individuals responsible for smuggling aliens," the report says.\par \par \uc2 Arizona Attorney General Terry Goddard spoke about these efforts during his testimony at Thursday's hearing.\par \par \uc2 "We need to recognize the seriousness and proximity of the cartel threat to American security and eliminate that threat quickly," said Goddard, according to his written testimony. "Perhaps the biggest failure of our national debate on border security is that the cartel threat seems to have taken a back seat to discussions about immigration. Yet, if we eliminate the cartel organizations, the ability of large numbers to illegally cross our Southwest border would be dramatically reduced."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 on the net\par \par \uc2 To read the GAO report, go to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.gao.gov/cgi-bin/getrpt?GAO-10"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.gao.gov/cgi-bin/getrpt?GAO-10}}}\uc2 - 328\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100805e67n00002\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc34}{\*\bkmkend toc34}\b \uc2 US suit jacks up drama over immigration law\b0\par\par\uc2 HOWARD FISCHER   \par \uc2 HOWARD FISCHER CAPITOL MEDIA SERVICES AND BRADY MCCOMBS,; ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 2,068 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 July 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Arizona accused of seeking to pre-empt, 'second-guess' federal policies\par \par \uc2 The federal government's lawsuit against the immigration enforcement law in Arizona magnified the divisiveness of SB 1070 and sets the stage for a milestone ruling that could resonate across the country.\par \par \uc2 The Obama administration's lawsuit Tuesday comes weeks before the law is to take effect and seeks to prevent other states from duplicating the measure.\par \par \uc2 SB 1070 "is pre-empted by federal law and therefore violates the Supremacy Clause of the United States Constitution," legal papers filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court in Phoenix contend. The lawsuit says the legislation conflicts with the federal government's need to balance the competing interests of enforcing federal immigration law with the country's diplomatic relations with other nations, including Mexico.\par \par \uc2 The law "attempts to second-guess federal policies and re-order federal priorities in the area of immigration enforcement and to directly regulate immigration and the condition of an alien's entry and presence in the United States despite the fact that those subjects are federal domains and do not involve any legitimate state interest," wrote Assistant Attorney General Tony West, who heads the civil division of the Department of Justice.\par \par \uc2 Five other lawsuits have been filed challenging the law, but none carries the weight of the suit filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court in Phoenix by the Department of Justice. The case will now be assigned to a judge who will decide whether to grant a preliminary injunction to temporarily block the law from taking effect on July 29 as scheduled.\par \par \uc2 While Gov. Jan Brewer and other supporters of the measure defend its constitutionality, one of Arizona's leading legal scholars is predicting the lawsuit will be enough to deliver a knockout blow to the law.\par \par \uc2 "There's a very realistic chance that this marks the end of SB 1070," said Gabriel "Jack" Chin, of the University of Arizona's James E. Rogers College of Law. "It's one thing for the ACLU and MALDEF to say that SB 1070 interferes with federal immigration authority, but it's not their direct concern. It's much more credible, much more powerful to have the United States come in and make the argument."\par \par \uc2 Chin predicts a judge will order an injunction and goes further to say the law will never go into effect.\par \par \uc2 "In order for Arizona to win, Arizona has to persuade a district judge that either Arizona or federal courts are in a better position to determine foreign policy concerns than the secretary of state and the federal government," said Chin, who has been reading statutes for 25 years. "And that's a tall order."\par \par \uc2 Pinal County Attorney James Walsh stopped short of predicting an outcome but said he also has serious doubts about the state law's constitutionality. He welcomed the lawsuit because it will provide a sorely-needed answer. Walsh said he believes a court could make a decision before the end of the month.\par \par \uc2 The federal filing may be stronger than the other five lawsuits pending, said Walsh, because none of the plaintiffs in those other claims may have legal standing or ability to show any specific harm on the issue of federal supremacy, something the federal government is not required to prove.\par \par \uc2 The law requires police to question those they have stopped for some other reason about their immigration status if there is "reasonable suspicion" they are in this country illegally. It also imposes criminal penalties on foreigners who fail to federally register or carry their immigration documents.\par \par \uc2 Other provisions make it a state crime for undocumented workers to seek employment in Arizona and for people to knowingly harbor or transport those who are illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 The Arizona Legislature passed the measure after years of frustration stemming from being ground zero for illegal immigration and drug smuggling. Arizona's section of U.S.-Mexico border accounts for nearly half of all illegal immigrants apprehended and marijuana seized in the U.S. There are an estimated 460,000 illegal immigrants living in the state.\par \par \uc2 Other states have said they want to take similar action - a scenario the government cited as a reason for bringing the lawsuit.\par \par \uc2 "The Constitution and the federal immigration laws do not permit the development of a patchwork of state and local immigration policies throughout the country," the suit says.\par \par \uc2 The lawsuit has only one purpose, said Sen. Russell Pearce, the Mesa Republican who crafted the law and pushed it through the Legislature. "This is about the Obamas' policy of nonenforcement," he said. "This interferes with their plan for amnesty."\par \par \uc2 The administration has no interest in dealing with illegal immigration itself and now wants to block Arizona from doing what the federal government refuses to do, Pearce said.\par \par \uc2 "They are complicit," Pearce said of the administration.\par \par \uc2 "They are aiding and abetting the enemy," Pearce said and are violating their oath of office. "They ought to be impeached."\par \par \uc2 Gov. Jan Brewer, in a prepared response, said she believes the law is "both reasonable and constitutional."\par \par \uc2 Brewer also rejected the contention that SB 1070 is preempted by federal law, saying it is "designed to complement, not supplant, enforcement of federal immigration laws."\par \par \uc2 "As a direct result of failed and inconsistent federal enforcement, Arizona is under attack from violent Mexican drug and immigrant smuggling cartels. Now, Arizona is under attack in federal court from President Obama and his Department of Justice," Brewer said. "Today's filing is nothing more than a massive waste of taxpayer funds."\par \par \uc2 Brewer said she was glad the federal lawsuit did not claim the law will lead to racial profiling, a claim in some of the five other lawsuits already filed challenging the law.\par \par \uc2 But that may be just a temporary victory: A top Justice Department official said Tuesday that racial profiling is a separate legal issue. He said that if SB 1070 does take effect as scheduled on July 29, his agency's civil-rights division will monitor how the law is implemented and, if necessary, file a separate action.\par \par \uc2 Kris Kobach, the University of Missouri-Kansas City law professor who helped draft the Arizona law, said he's not surprised by the Justice Department's challenge and called it "unnecessary."\par \par \uc2 He noted that the law already is being challenged by the American Civil Liberties Union and other groups opposed to the new statute.\par \par \uc2 "The issue was already teed up in the courts. There's no reason for the Justice Department to get involved. The Justice Department doesn't add anything by bringing their own lawsuit," Kobach said in an interview.\par \par \uc2 Central to the case is whether the Arizona law interferes with what West said is the need of the federal government to decide exactly how and when to enforce immigration laws.\par \par \uc2 "Assuring effective enforcement of the provisions against illegal immigration and unlawful presence is a highly important interest," wrote West, the assistant U.S. attorney general. "But it is not the singular goal of federal immigration laws."\par \par \uc2 West said the laws also take into account "uniquely national interests" like facilitating trade and commerce, welcoming foreign nationals who visit, and making sure the treatment of foreign nationals here "does not harm our foreign relations with the countries from which they come or jeopardize the treatment of U.S. citizens abroad."\par \par \uc2 Pearce said SB 1070 simply lets the state enforce existing federal immigration laws. But West said that's not the case.\par \par \uc2 For example, he said federal law does make it illegal to hire an undocumented worker. And there are separate laws aimed at would-be workers who present presenting fraudulent documents.\par \par \uc2 But nothing in any of those laws, West said, makes it a crime for an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  to seek work.\par \par \uc2 "In fact (Congress) decided that criminal sanctions for seeking or obtaining employment would run counter to the purposes of the immigration system," he wrote.\par \par \uc2 Pearce said West is off-base with his objections.\par \par \uc2 "It's a felony to hire them," Pearce said. "So it ought to be a crime to solicit."\par \par \uc2 West had similar problems with the requirement of police to check the immigration status of those they suspect are in this country illegally. At the same time, SB 1070 also says any legal Arizona resident can file suit against any official or agency that adopts or implements a policy that restricts enforcement of federal immigration laws.\par \par \uc2 He said that undermines what had been the discretion of police of whether to verify someone's immigration status. Nor was West convinced that the requirement for "reasonable suspicion" is sufficient to protect rights.\par \par \uc2 "Arizona's alien inspection scheme therefore will subject lawful aliens to the possibility of inquisitorial practices and police surveillance, a form of treatment which Congress has plainly guarded against in crafting a balanced, federally directed immigration enforcement scheme."\par \par \uc2 Both Brewer and Pearce also chided the Obama administration for what they see as a selective approach to claiming federal supremacy in enforcing immigration laws. Pearce said that ignores various local policies and practices that now instruct police not to inquire about someone's immigration status.\par \par \uc2 "These patchwork local 'sanctuary' policies instruct the police not to cooperate with federal immigration officials," Brewer said.\par \par \uc2 In a prepared statement, Attorney General Eric Holder said Arizonans "are understandably frustrated with illegal immigration." And he said the federal government has a responsibility to comprehensively address those concerns. "But diverting federal resources away from dangerous aliens such as terrorism suspects and aliens with criminal records will impact the entire country's safety," the statement said.\par \par \uc2 "Setting immigration policy and enforcing immigration laws is a national responsibility," Holder continued. "Seeking to address the issue through a patchwork of state laws will only create more problems than it solves."\par \par \uc2 The Associated Press contributed to this story.\par \par \uc2 Read the full text of the United States of America vs. the State of Arizona at azstarnet.com/pdf\par \par \uc2 We want to hear from you. Share your opinion of the lawsuit in the comments section of this story at azstarnet.com/border\par \par \uc2 MORE INSIDE\par \par \uc2 * Reactions from Southern Arizona's law- enforcement leaders. Page A4\par \par \uc2 * Arizona's law creates discord for this year's border governors' conference. Page A12\par \par \uc2 "Arizonans are understandably frustrated with illegal immigration, and the federal government has a responsibility to comprehensively address those concerns. But diverting federal resources away from dangerous aliens such as terrorism suspects and aliens with criminal records will impact the entire country's safety." U.S. Attorney General Eric Holder\par \par \uc2 SenS. John McCain and Jon Kyl\par \par \uc2 "The Obama administration has not done everything it can do to protect the people of Arizona from the violence and crime illegal immigration brings to our state. Until it does, the federal government should not be suing Arizona on the grounds that immigration enforcement is solely a federal responsibility."\par \par \uc2 Gov. Jan Brewer\par \par \uc2 "As a direct result of failed and inconsistent federal enforcement, Arizona is under attack from violent Mexican drug- and immigrant- smuggling cartels. Now, Arizona is under attack in federal court from President Obama and his Department of Justice."\par \par \uc2 Rep. Gabrielle Giffords\par \par \uc2 "Both the law and the lawsuit challenging the law are unnecessary distractions. Arizonans want our nation to control its borders and bring a halt to the violence, smugglers and drugs that threaten our way of life. ... Federal lawyers arguing with state lawyers will do nothing to strengthen border security or to fix our broken immigration laws."\par \par \uc2 Rep. Raul Grijalva\par \par \uc2 "For people to say we shouldn't even challenge the law is horribly un-American. I would want to know as an elected official that I'm upholding a law that is constitutionally valid. Now we're going to get that test. If it passes muster, then we'll live with the consequences of that. If it doesn't, we'll all be relieved we're not trying to enforce a law that is constitutionally a problem."\par \par \uc2 Tucson Police Chief Roberto Villasenor\par \par \uc2 "The impact of illegal immigration on Arizona's well-being cannot be denied. But to require local police to act as immigration agents when a lack of local resources already makes enforcing criminal laws and ordinances a challenging proposition, is not realistic. "\par \par \uc2 The following fields overflowed:\par \par \uc2 BYLINE = HOWARD FISCHER\par \par \uc2 CAPITOL MEDIA SERVICES\par \par \uc2 AND BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100717e6770000o\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc35}{\*\bkmkend toc35}\b \uc2 Border issue no longer a bright political divide\b0\par\par\uc2 TIM STELLER   \par \uc2 TIM STELLER, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 2,203 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 July 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Ariz. Dems, GOP talk tough even as enforcement grows\par \par \uc2 Fewer people are crossing Arizona's border from Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Fewer "criminal aliens" are being sent to Arizona's prisons.\par \par \uc2 More officers are patrolling Arizona's southern frontier.\par \par \uc2 The number of illegal immigrants in Arizona has declined by 100,000 or more.\par \par \uc2 Yet border security and illegal immigration are the hottest topic in Arizona's politics this year, returning the state to the center of a national debate.\par \par \uc2 On Thursday, President Obama cited Arizona's new immigration- enforcement law, SB 1070, when he launched a drive for "comprehensive" reform of the country's immigration laws. Gov. Jan Brewer has centered her election campaign on fighting illegal immigration, and her competitors have tried to match her border toughness.\par \par \uc2 Even Democrats, who traditionally have favored a way for illegal residents to become legal, are flexing their border muscles. After Obama's speech Thursday, U.S. Rep. Gabrielle Giffords said via Twitter: "Mr. President I will personally show you what AZ needs: tough border security."\par \par \uc2 No matter the candidate or the office, it seems, border issues top the state's political agenda this year. Among the reasons:\par \par \uc2 * Drug violence continues to flare up just across the border in Mexico. In the worst recent example, 21 people died Thursday in a shootout between smuggling gangs 12 miles south of the Arizona border.\par \par \uc2 * Rancher Robert Krentz was murdered and Pinal County Deputy Louis Puroll was shot - both possibly by smugglers - as the state debated SB 1070.\par \par \uc2 * The anti-government sentiment that has colored Obama's tenure found a comfortable home in the border-security debate. Many candidates and voters blame the federal government for doing too little to secure the U.S.-Mexico border.\par \par \uc2 * Janet Napolitano's departure from the governor's seat let the Republican legislation escape her prolific veto stamp and become law.\par \par \uc2 * Former U.S. Rep. J.D. Hayworth challenged Sen. John McCain in the Republican primary, confronting McCain on border and immigration issues. McCain responded with an intense effort to build credentials as a border-security hawk.\par \par \uc2 The issue has been near the top of Arizona voters' priority list for more than a decade, Republican pollster Margaret Kenski said.\par \par \uc2 "I think the widespread perception is that the border is not secure, that it's fairly porous. That's what people are responding to," she said.\par \par \uc2 More officers on the border\par \par \uc2 More law enforcement officers than ever are patrolling Arizona's southern border, including increasing numbers who aren't Border Patrol agents.\par \par \uc2 One of them is Pima County Sheriff's Deputy Scott Woodworth. One night in late June, he stopped his duty vehicle, a Chevrolet Tahoe, on unpaved West Silverbell Road, about 40 miles northwest of downtown Tucson. He pulled out a sandwich, his dinner, and took in the quiet, moonlit evening while he waited.\par \par \uc2 It's often quiet like this for Woodworth, one of 18 members of the Pima County Sheriff's Department's border crime unit. He and the other members go to the remote regions of the county looking for drug smugglers, lost border crossers, stolen vehicles and loads of money headed south.\par \par \uc2 Working the border these days can be boring, but it is seldom lonely.\par \par \uc2 During his shift, Woodworth stayed in contact with members of his squad, who were scouring an area farther west, near the Tohono O'odham Nation. He also ran into a Bureau of Land Management ranger on Ironwood National Monument and two Marana police officers out patrolling the remote areas as part of the federal Operation Stonegarden, which pays local law-enforcement officers to patrol border areas.\par \par \uc2 The Border Patrol's Tucson sector employs about 3,200 agents, more than double the number it had eight years ago. Add to that agents sent in temporarily from different sectors, sheriff's deputies in border counties, rangers on federal lands, officers working Stonegarden assignments and a temporary National Guard deployment. Arizona's border is patrolled more heavily than ever.\par \par \uc2 Thanks to hundreds more agents and miles of new fencing, the entire Yuma Sector is considered under "operational control," said sector spokesman Kenneth Quillin, a supervisory Border Patrol agent.\par \par \uc2 In the Tucson Sector, agents have gained "operational control" of several segments of the border, said Brandon Judd, president of the agents' union local. Assignments in and near the border towns, where the main objective is to maintain control by deterring crossings, can be inactive.\par \par \uc2 "It's insanely boring," Judd said.\par \par \uc2 Apprehensions of illegal immigrants in the Arizona's two Border Patrol sectors peaked at about 590,000 in 2004 and dropped to about 249,000 last year. There is wide agreement that the drop reflects a steep decrease in attempts to cross, due mostly to the recession but also to increased enforcement.\par \par \uc2 "There really has been a huge drop of inflows in undocumented immigrants and especially Mexican immigrants," said Jeff Passel, senior demographer at the Pew Hispanic Center.\par \par \uc2 Border hot spots\par \par \uc2 But there still is action along Arizona's border. Judd points to the Huachuca Mountains, the corridor near the Chiricahua Mountains and some routes through the Tohono O'odham Nation as hot spots.\par \par \uc2 Rancher and cowboy poet Bud Strom is out on his property near the southern end of the Huachucas daily, and he says the illegal traffic has slowed dramatically in the year or so since the federal government finished a nearby 18-foot-high border fence. Pedestrian crossings of his ranch, which he had estimated at 1,000 per week, have dwindled to 50 to 100, Strom said. Vehicles no longer cross there.\par \par \uc2 "But it still ticks me off that they leave trash on the ranch," he said.\par \par \uc2 While Strom counts crossers by the dozens, Pam Saxman and her husband can count incidents on one hand in the four years since they moved from central Tucson to the remote hills in the western Avra Valley. Someone tried to steal a horse once, and recently a group of 40 people approached their home, about 70 miles north of the border. Still, that irks her.\par \par \uc2 "I don't think any of it's tolerable," she said.\par \par \uc2 Robert Krentz was working his family's ranch northeast of Douglas, in one of those hot corridors, when he was shot and killed March 27. Authorities don't know who attacked Krentz, but he radioed before he was killed that he was going to check on an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  he had encountered.\par \par \uc2 The killing happened amid a rash of burglaries around nearby Portal that residents attributed to cross-border criminals. And it happened as the state was debating SB 1070, which requires law enforcement officers to check the immigration status of people whom they question for another reason if they have reasonable suspicion that those people are in the country illegally.\par \par \uc2 After Krentz's slaying, "candidates immediately jumped on the bandwagon," said Jennifer Allen, executive director of the Tucson- based Border Action Network, which works on behalf of legal and illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 Attorney General Terry Goddard, the only Democrat in the governor's race, speculated on television after the slaying that the killer was "a trained professional."\par \par \uc2 "These are commandos, these are paramilitary professionals who unfortunately are throughout the high desert in Southern Arizona," he said, clarifying later that he was supposing this to be true.\par \par \uc2 Krentz's murder galvanized support for SB 1070, partly because "he was a rancher on his own property, minding his own business," said Tucsonan John Munger, who dropped out of the race for governor in May.\par \par \uc2 Napolitano, who vetoed a record 180 bills as governor, would have vetoed the law had she not become Obama's secretary of homeland security, Munger said. But Brewer signed it, citing "the crisis caused by illegal immigration and Arizona's porous border."\par \par \uc2 Fear drug violence\par \par \uc2 In signing 1070, Brewer also cited another concern - that drug- war violence in Mexico could cross the border into Arizona.\par \par \uc2 "We cannot delay while the destruction happening south of our international border creeps its way north," she said.\par \par \uc2 Incidents reinforcing that fear occur regularly. On Monday, gunmen in Tamaulipas, a Mexican state that borders Texas, shot to death the leading candidate for governor in today's Mexican elections. On Thursday morning, a shootout between suspected smuggling gangs killed 21 people south of the Arizona border, between the Sonoran towns of Saric and Tubutama.\par \par \uc2 In Arizona, crime related to smuggling has existed for decades. But the Krentz killing and incidents such as the April 30 shooting of Pinal County Deputy Puroll, allegedly by smugglers, reinforced the idea that things are getting worse.\par \par \uc2 Crime data, though, shows crime rates steady or down for Arizona's border towns and the state as a whole.\par \par \uc2 The number of "criminal aliens" admitted to Arizona's prisons is down in the fiscal year that ended June 30. The number peaked in fiscal 2009 at 3,436 and dropped last year to 2,743.\par \par \uc2 And the number of illegal immigrants estimated to be living in Arizona dropped from 560,000 in January 2008 to 460,000 in January 2009, the Department of Homeland Security estimates. The recession has likely pushed that population down more, said Passel of the Pew center.\par \par \uc2 Border security has been "a top-tier worry in Arizona for years," said Democratic pollster Lisa Grove. "What I think is new is heightened concern about border violence. As people are hearing about cartels, gangs, drug smugglers and human traffickers, the ante is up for voters."\par \par \uc2 The risk of violence crossing the border is real, said Fred Burton, vice president of intelligence for the Austin, Texas-based firm Stratfor Global Intelligence. But the data is lacking to say whether it's happening because, for example, a person who disappears in Texas may not be listed as a murder victim if his body turns up in Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Also, the cartels have reason not to challenge the stronger civil authorities in the United States, he said:\par \par \uc2 "They run the risk, if they come into the U.S. and assassinate the wrong person, of a more concerted law enforcement effort to go after them."\par \par \uc2 Key element of campaigns\par \par \uc2 Most candidates for Arizona governor and other offices have made border security a key component of their races.\par \par \uc2 On May 27, state Treasurer and would-be governor Dean Martin established a fund for donations from people concerned about border security. So far, it has $1,035. On June 8 he announced a border plan that includes a "tent city" for "illegal aliens convicted of crimes in Arizona."\par \par \uc2 For some voters, he said, "you can be right with them on everything, but if you're for amnesty, forget it. They're not going to support you."\par \par \uc2 Brewer has a border-security fund of her own - an account to pay for the legal defense of SB 1070 - with about $138,000 in contributions. The fund is a minor part of a major effort to show herself as tough on border security and illegal immigration.\par \par \uc2 She has gone even beyond the bounds of the facts, saying in June that most illegal immigrants are smuggling drugs and implying that beheadings have occurred in Arizona.\par \par \uc2 And she has picked a fight with the president, accusing Obama of leaving Arizona unprotected. In an online video, Brewer stands next to a sign warning of smuggling activity in a spot 80 miles from the border.\par \par \uc2 "Washington says the border is as safe as it's ever been. Does this look safe to you?" she says, before addressing Obama directly: "Do your job! Protect our borders!"\par \par \uc2 As a Republican gubernatorial debate wound down on June 15, candidate Matt Jette wound up the other candidates by telling Brewer: "You act as if the state of Arizona is being terrorized by illegal immigrants."\par \par \uc2 "It is," candidate Buz Mills interjected.\par \par \uc2 "I have been to the border," Mills said. "The folks down there are living in fear and intimidation. They're terrorized down there."\par \par \uc2 In an interview last week, Mills acknowledged that border security isn't necessarily the most important issue facing Arizona, and he accused the governor of avoiding issues like the state budget and joblessness by talking about the border.\par \par \uc2 Brewer did not respond to a request for an interview.\par \par \uc2 Democrat Goddard has also staked out a position as tough on border crime and illegal immigration.\par \par \uc2 "I've always had my hair on fire about this," he told the Arizona Daily Star editorial board. "The cartels are a security threat to the United States, and we've been fools to ignore it."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Tim Steller at tsteller@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Measuring Arizona's border security\par \par \uc2 Measure 2005 2006 2007 2008 2009\par \par \uc2 Arizona apprehensions*: 577,517 510,623 416,231 326,059 248,624\par \par \uc2 Arizona-based Border Patrol agents**: 3,024 3,384 3692 3,965 4,170\par \par \uc2 Arizona marijuana seizures***: 884,204 879,523 1,264,095 1,132,323 1,655,265\par \par \uc2 Arizona \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  population****: 510,000 490,000 530,000 560,000 460,000\par \par \uc2 * U.S. Border Patrol, Yuma and Tucson sectors ** Sources: Yuma Sector, Star archives *** Source Arizona HIDTA. Refers to all seizures over 20 lbs. **** Department of Homeland Security\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100714e6740000p\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc36}{\*\bkmkend toc36}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 BRIAN J PEDERSEN; KIM SMITH   \par \uc2 BRIAN J. PEDERSEN AND KIM SMITH, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 936 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 June 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Burglary suspect, 17, dies at hospital\par \par \uc2 A 17-year-old who had been housed at the Pima County jail died last week, nine days after being found unresponsive in the jail's medical unit.\par \par \uc2 Mordecai "Joey" Harrelson was pronounced dead June 11 at a hospital, said Deputy Jason Ogan, a Pima County Sheriff's Department spokesman.\par \par \uc2 Ogan did not know why Harrelson, who was booked into jail April 1 on suspicion of burglary, had been in the medical unit. He said Harrelson was found unconscious June 2 and then hospitalized. The cause of death is undetermined, and officials are awaiting autopsy results, Ogan said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Man, 21, arrested in shootings at eatery\par \par \uc2 Sierra Vista police arrested a 21-year-old man Tuesday who is suspected of shooting at homeless men outside a fast-food restaurant.\par \par \uc2 Vernon F. Armstrong-Kearney was booked into the Cochise County jail on two counts of suspicion of attempted murder and an outstanding auto theft warrant out of Douglas, according to a Sierra Vista Police Department news release.\par \par \uc2 Police went to the Carl's Jr. on East Fry Boulevard about 5:15 p.m. Monday after getting reports of gunshots, the release said.\par \par \uc2 Two men were seen in a white vehicle, with one of them suspected of firing several shots at two homeless men outside the restaurant, the release said.\par \par \uc2 Police found the vehicle abandoned Tuesday morning. Armstrong- Kearney was arrested a short time later.\par \par \uc2 Angel Smith, 19, was also arrested on suspicion of hindering prosecution, the release said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Registered sex offender gets 36 years in rape\par \par \uc2 A 52-year-old registered sex offender who raped a pregnant Tucson woman during an attack that was recorded during the woman's call to 911 was sentenced to 36 years in prison Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Pima County Superior Court Judge Howard Fell ordered the sentence to run consecutive to the two years Gerardo S. Lopez is already serving in an unrelated drug case, said Fran Maffetone, a deputy county attorney. A Pima County jury convicted Lopez two months ago of sexual assault, sexual abuse, attempted sexual assault and kidnapping.\par \par \uc2 The victim, a 34-year-old woman, had asked Lopez and others for direction after getting lost after taking a bus to the city's south side.\par \par \uc2 Kim Smith\par \par \uc2 Tucson man gets 39 years for crimes\par \par \uc2 A Tucson man who says he robbed six convenience stores and committed a carjacking to support the baby he fathered with a 13- year-old girl was sentenced to 39 years in prison Monday by Pima County Superior Court Judge Richard Nichols.\par \par \uc2 Charles Edward Flowers could have received as few as 23 1/2 years and as many as 170 years in prison, under plea deal he agreed to in return for many of the charges against him being dropped.\par \par \uc2 Authorities believe Flowers, 21, and a group of other young men robbed three convenience stores Aug. 30, 2008, and three more Sept. 15, 2008.\par \par \uc2 The carjacking and sex assault occurred in September 2008. Flowers was indicted on 77 counts, including those pertaining to his underage girlfriend.\par \par \uc2 Flowers' attorney Chip Plowman and Deputy Pima County Attorney Rona Kreamer negotiated a plea agreement rather than force the victims to testify at trial.\par \par \uc2 On Monday, Deputy Pima County Attorney Rona Kreamer asked Nichols for a sentence of no less than 54 years.\par \par \uc2 Kim Smith\par \par \uc2 Man gets 5 years in pot conspiracy\par \par \uc2 A 34-year-old Mexican man who was once accused of participating in the slayings of two men was sentenced to five years in prison Monday by Pima County Superior Court Judge Richard Fields.\par \par \uc2 Jose Daniel Alvarez, 23, and Jesus Martinez Gonzales, 24, were shot to death and found at Feliz Paseos Park, near North Camino de Oeste and West Speedway, in December 2008.\par \par \uc2 Lopez pleaded guilty last month to conspiracy to possess marijuana for sale, agreeing to serve somewhere between 2 1/2 and seven years in prison. The murder and kidnapping charges were dropped.\par \par \uc2 He was given credit for 552 days time served awaiting the resolution of his case.\par \par \uc2 Once released from prison, he faces deportation because he is in the country illegally.\par \par \uc2 Kim Smith\par \par \uc2 Mexican man guilty of killing ranch hand\par \par \uc2 A Mexican national was found guilty Monday in federal court in the 2003 killing of a ranch hand on the Tohono O'odham Nation.\par \par \uc2 A jury found Victor Manuel Reza-Ramos, 49, guilty of first- degree murder after a two-week trial in U.S. District Court in Tucson, according to a U.S. Attorney's Office news release.\par \par \uc2 Jose L. Flores was found beaten to death on March 25, 2003 at the Kisto Ranch, where he served as caretaker, the release said.\par \par \uc2 Flores was beaten with a metal fireplace shovel and a 6-pound rock, suffering more than 60 injuries mostly to the head and neck, according to the release.\par \par \uc2 The jury determined Reza-Ramos, an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , had killed Flores while crossing the ranch in order to steal a pickup truck on the ranch, the release said.\par \par \uc2 Reza-Ramos was initially linked to the crime through a bloody palm print left at the scene, according to the release. He was indicted on in June 2006 but was not arrested until March 2008 after being extradited from Mexico, court records show.\par \par \uc2 Reza-Ramos faces a mandatory life sentence for the conviction. U.S. District Judge Frank Zapata will determine on Aug. 20 whether Reza-Ramos will be eligible for parole.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100629e66h0002j\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc37}{\*\bkmkend toc37}\b \uc2 Rancher Krentz was shot more than once\b0\par\par\uc2 TIM STELLER   \par \uc2 TIM STELLER, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 320 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 June 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Autopsy report blacks out details\par \par \uc2 Rancher Robert Krentz received multiple gunshot wounds when he was killed on his property in Cochise County March 27, according to an autopsy report.\par \par \uc2 The report, by deputy medical examiner Avneesh Gupta, was released in response to a public-records request by the Arizona Daily Star. However, about half of the five pages are redacted.\par \par \uc2 That's because those sections contained information known only to the killer and investigators, said Rod Rothrock, chief deputy of the Cochise County Sheriff's Office. Releasing it publicly would keep the department from knowing whether information it receives is from a knowledgeable source or just someone who has read the news.\par \par \uc2 "We have to have a method for screening information out of Mexico that has any validity," he said.\par \par \uc2 The report mentions injuries to Krentz's torso, but the details of the shooting and injuries are blacked out.\par \par \uc2 Asked about progress in the investigation, Rothrock said, "Let's just say that it is not at a dead end."\par \par \uc2 "We have information on hand that has us looking 