2 Parada told authorities she was doing a favor for a friend of her husband's, to whom she owed money. She said smuggling the children was meant to settle the $250 debt with a man identified in courts records only as "Chileo."\par \par \uc2 Parada is scheduled to be arraigned June 10.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Immigrant hitching train ride falls, dies\par \par \uc2 An \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  was killed Wednesday near Tubac when he fell off a train he was trying to hitch a ride on, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 U.S. Border Patrol agents discovered the body of a 29-year-old man between two railroad cars on a Union Pacific line near Bridge Road, Santa Cruz County Sheriff Tony Estrada said.\par \par \uc2 Agents called in the Sheriff's Office, which has been working with the Mexican Consulate to contact the family of the man, who is from Nogales, Sonora, Estrada said.\par \par \uc2 It appeared the man had been trying to ride on the train when he fell between the cars and was crushed by the steel couplings that hold the cars together, Estrada said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100608e65s0000o\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc39}{\*\bkmkend toc39}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 723 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 May 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A9\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 3 charged following west-side robberies\par \par \uc2 Tucson police have arrested three men in connection with two home invasions that occurred in an apartment complex on the west side.\par \par \uc2 Pierre Holness, 22, Heath Williams, 18, and Domonick McCoy, 18, face charges of armed robbery, aggravated robbery and kidnapping. They were arrested on Tuesday and Wednesday and booked into the Pima County jail.\par \par \uc2 The first incident occurred at 9:30 p.m. May 5. Officers received a report of a residential robbery at the complex in the 2500 block of West Anklam Road.\par \par \uc2 Two men entered the residence, demanded drugs and money and then pistol-whipped the victim, said Sgt. Diana Lopez, a police spokeswoman. The victim got away and called police. The home invaders took several items and fled before police arrived. The victim was treated at a hospital.\par \par \uc2 On Tuesday, a home invasion was reported to police at about 7 a.m. at the same complex. In that incident, two men entered a residence and held a person at gunpoint. The robbers demanded drugs and took several items from the residence before leaving.\par \par \uc2 The department's Home Invasion Unit developed information that led to the arrests, Lopez said.\par \par \uc2 Man who killed prairie dog fined $885\par \par \uc2 An Oro Valley man who killed a protected prairie dog near Sonoita was fined and had his hunting license suspended at a hearing Friday.\par \par \uc2 The Arizona Game and Fish Commission fined Terry Lee Metteer $885 and suspended his license for five years in a hearing at Game and Fish headquarters in Phoenix, spokesman Mark Hart said.\par \par \uc2 Metteer, 59, pleaded guilty in December in Pima County Justice Court to a misdemeanor charge of taking wildlife during a closed season, court records show.\par \par \uc2 He was fined $175 after admitting to shooting and killing a black- tailed prairie dog on Oct. 23 in a remote area east of Sonoita and north of Arizona 82 where signs were posted indicating hunting the animals was prohibited, Hart said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Body of man found not far from border\par \par \uc2 U.S. Border Patrol agents on Friday morning discovered the remains of a suspected \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  just north of the U.S.- Mexico border. The man's body was found east of Sasabe, about 9,000 feet north of the border, said Deputy Jason Ogan, a Pima County Sheriff's Department spokesman.\par \par \uc2 The department was called in because the body had head trauma, Ogan said. It is believed the man may have fallen off a cliff, he said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Fire not likely work of church arsonist\par \par \uc2 A small fire outside the Diocese of Tucson's downtown offices is not likely the work of a serial arsonist responsible for four recent church fires, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 The Tucson Fire Department was called about 8:30 p.m. Thursday for a fire outside the diocese offices at 192 S. Stone Ave., said fire spokeswoman Capt. Trish Tracy. The fire started in a planter near the building's entrance, was put out quickly and did not spread inside, Tracy said.\par \par \uc2 Investigators are still looking into the incident but say there's no indication it's linked to fires at four northwest-side churches, Tracy said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Graduation prompts sobriety checkpoints\par \par \uc2 Both the Pima County Sheriff's Department and the Tucson Police Department will put up sobriety checkpoints on Saturday night, the agencies announced Friday. The deployments are designed to curb drunken driving in conjunction with area college and high school graduation parties, officials said.\par \par \uc2 The Sheriff's Department had three DUI checkpoints last week, nabbing 100 suspected drunken drivers during the deployment.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Fire forces family out, leaves 7 pets dead\par \par \uc2 A family of three was displaced and seven pets died in a house fire near the Tucson Mountains on Friday afternoon. The fire at 5630 N. Blue Bonnet Road, which was ruled accidental, was burning for some time before a neighbor saw smoke and called 911 at 1:44 p.m., said Northwest Fire Capt. Adam Goldberg.\par \par \uc2 The fire was burning through the roof as firefighters arrived. The family came home from running errands as fire crews battled the blaze.\par \par \uc2 Two chihuahuas, two cats, two guinea pigs and a hamster died. Three other dogs, two horses and seven chickens survived.\par \par \uc2 Becky Pallack\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100526e65f00031\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSON\par {\*\bkmkstart toc40}{\*\bkmkend toc40}\b \uc2 Buscan a asesino de Krentz en EU\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSoN; ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 537 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 May 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par 17\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 El asesinato del ranchero del Sur de Arizona, el cual origino protestas para asegurar las fronteras no fue por casualidad, y los investigadores se estan enfocando en un sospechoso en Estados Unidos, se entero el periodico Arizona Daily Star.\par \par \uc2 Altas autoridades gubernamentales con informacion fehaciente hablaron con el Star, expresando un deseo de acallar la furia sobre la inmigracion de personas indocumentadas y el contrabando de drogas desatada por el homicidio con arma de fuego del ranchero Robert Krentz, acontecido el pasado 27 de marzo.\par \par \uc2 Dijeron que el sheriff del Condado de Cochise, Larry Dever, esta investigando a una persona dentro de Estados Unidos, no en Mexico, en relacion al asesinato.\par \par \uc2 La politica del periodico Star es no utilizar fuentes anonimas, excepto cuando la informacion sea de gran interes publico.\par \par \uc2 Dever no hizo comentario alguno cuando fue contactado via telefonica el pasado domingo.\par \par \uc2 Krentz fue encontrado muerto de un disparo en su rancho ubicado al Noreste de Douglas, un dia despues de que su hermano hubiera reportado a la Patrulla Fronteriza actividad de contrabando de drogas, lo cual dio como resultado la confiscacion de 290 libras de marihuana y el arresto de ocho personas