enforcement leaders for more troops and resources to the border.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100519e6570000i\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc41}{\*\bkmkend toc41}\b \uc2 American is focus in Krentz killing\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 774 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 May 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 CORRECTION RAN MAY 4, 2010, A1\par \par \uc2 An article and headline Monday on A1 incorrectly referred to the possible suspect in the Krentz killing investigation as "American." The story - as originally reported - said the suspect is believed to be in the United States. It was changed to "American" in the editing process. While the suspect is believed to be in the United States, the nationality is unknown.\par \par \uc2 Authorities say Cochise slaying that sparked outcry over border security was not random\par \par \uc2 The killing of a Southern Arizona rancher that sparked an outcry to secure the border was not random, and investigators are focusing on an American suspect, the Arizona Daily Star has learned.\par \par \uc2 High-ranking government officials with credible information spoke to the Star, citing a desire to quell the fury over illegal immigration and drug smuggling set off by the shooting death of longtime rancher Robert Krentz on March 27.\par \par \uc2 They said Cochise County Sheriff Larry Dever is investigating a person in the United States, not in Mexico, in connection with the shooting.\par \par \uc2 The Star's policy is not to use unnamed sources except in instances in which the information is of high public interest.\par \par \uc2 Reached Sunday by telephone, Dever would not comment.\par \par \uc2 Krentz was found gunned down on his ranch northeast of Douglas a day after his brother reported drug-smuggling activity to the Border Patrol that led to the seizure of 290 pounds of marijuana and the arrest of eight people on the ranch.\par \par \uc2 The night of the killing, officers followed a single set of footprints to the U.S.-Mexico border, Dever said.\par \par \uc2 That sparked widespread speculation that Krentz was killed by an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  or a drug smuggler from Mexico. In the ensuing weeks, the killing became symbolic of Arizona's porous and violent border, setting off a flurry of demands from residents, politicians and law enforcement leaders for more troops and resources to the border.\par \par \uc2 "Rob has become a martyr for this cause, a symbol," U.S. Senate candidate J.D. Hayworth said at a community meeting held on March 31 in the unincorporated community of Apache, near where the Krentz family has worked its 35,000-acre ranch for 100 years.\par \par \uc2 Many, including Dever, believe the killing propelled into law an immigration-enforcement bill passed by the Legislature and signed by Gov. Jan Brewer that has thrust Arizona into the international spotlight.\par \par \uc2 "The fact that it got passed has a lot to do with the reflection and response to the Rob Krentz murder," Dever said from Washington, D.C., on April 20 after testifying before the U.S. Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs.\par \par \uc2 During testimony that day, Dever said Krentz "was senselessly gunned down on his own property" and that "his murderer was tracked to the Mexican border, and has since evaded capture," according to a copy of the testimony.\par \par \uc2 "We cannot sit by while our citizens are terrorized, robbed and murdered by ruthless and desperate people who enter our country illegally," Dever said.\par \par \uc2 Forty-eight hours after the killing, Dever told reporters that investigators believed the shooting was carried out by one person, but that they didn't know if it was a man or a woman, or the person's nationality. But Dever said they had reports that Krentz made reference to an "illegal alien" over a two-way radio he used to communicate with his brother while working that day on the southern part of their ranch.\par \par \uc2 "Given the location, (I) guarantee it was not somebody on their way to \uc2 Walmart\uc2  to go shopping," Dever said on March 29.\par \par \uc2 The Southeastern Arizona valley where Krentz was killed is a heavily trafficked people- and drug-smuggling corridor that has seen an increase in burglaries in recent years. Sheriff's investigators and most residents believe the crimes are being committed by drug smugglers heading back to Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Ranchers and residents in the valley said the Krentz killing had cemented the transformation of illegal border activity from irritating to deadly.\par \par \uc2 Politicians from both parties across the country have weighed in on the killing and proposed plans for how to protect border residents.\par \par \uc2 Dever himself has appeared in political ads for candidates advocating for more border enforcement, including a new radio spot for Sen. John McCain.\par \par \uc2 In it, Dever says, "The drug wars in Mexico spilled over into our state - burglaries, home invasions, even murder."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find extensive coverage of immigration and border issues at azstarnet.com/news/local/border\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100518e6530001o\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc42}{\*\bkmkend toc42}\b \uc2 Experts go over SB 1070's key points\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 2,305 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 May 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Law professors, others decode language in controversial law\par \par \uc2 The full impact of the state's new immigration enforcement law may not be clear for months - attorneys and law enforcement officials need to make sense of its language, and legal challenges will be settled in court.\par \par \uc2 But here are seven things we do know about SB 1070, which Gov. Jan Brewer signed into law April 23 and is scheduled to go into effect in mid-August:\par \par \uc2 1. It requires police officers to determine the immigration status of everybody they arrest before that person is released.\par \par \uc2 * The law says: "Any person who is arrested shall have the person's immigration status determined before the person is released. The person's immigration status shall be verified with the federal government pursuant to 8 United States code section 1373(c)."\par \par \uc2 * What that means: This could mean lots of extra work for local police officers, who have to make the initial determination and then contact federal agents for verification, said Raymond Michalowski, an Arizona regents professor of criminology at Northern Arizona University. The law does not spell out how the determination and verification must be done.\par \par \uc2 Police officers almost always get identification from people they arrest, but most police departments don't use that information to check everybody's immigration status, he said.\par \par \uc2 "This becomes a very large, unfunded mandate for police departments," Michalowski said.\par \par \uc2 2. During any stop, detention or arrest, a police officer must try to determine a person's immigration status if the officer has reason to suspect the person is here illegally. An exception exists if making that determination might obstruct an investigation.\par \par \uc2 * The law says: "For any lawful stop, detention or arrest made by a law enforcement official or a law enforcement agency of this state or a law enforcement official or a law enforcement agency of a county, city, town or other political subdivision of this state in the enforcement of any other law or ordinance of a county, city or town of this state where reasonable suspicion exists that the person is an alien and is unlawfully present in the United States, a reasonable attempt shall be made, when practicable, to determine the immigration status of the person, except if the determination may hinder or obstruct an investigation."\par \par \uc2 * What it means: The language - which was changed Thursday night to clarify lawful contact - effectively makes checking immigration status a "secondary enforcement" akin to the state's seat-belt laws, said Paul Senseman, the governor's spokesman.\par \par \uc2 The law doesn't force officers to go out looking for illegal immigrants, only to call immigration officials to determine the status when the officer develops a reasonable suspicion, Kris Kobach, a University of Missouri at Kansas City law professor who helped draft the bill, said in an interview with National Public Radio.\par \par \uc2 Kobach was Attorney General John Ashcroft's chief adviser on immigration law and border security from 2001 to 2003. He did not return phone calls from the Arizona Daily Star for this story.\par \par \uc2 He wrote in an op-ed for The New York Times that the law will most likely come into play after a traffic stop.\par \par \uc2 "A police officer pulls a minivan over for speeding. A dozen passengers are crammed in. None has identification. The highway is a known alien-smuggling corridor. The driver is acting evasively. Those factors combine to create reasonable suspicion that the occupants are not in the country legally," he wrote.\par \par \uc2 It's unclear if the law requires this determination to be made by a federal agent in person or over the phone.\par \par \uc2 The change in wording from "lawful contact" to "lawful stop, detention or arrest" would appear to exempt victims and witnesses from the law, but the statute still dictates a significant change in traditional priorities of law enforcement agencies, said Gabriel "Jack" Chin, of the University of Arizona's James E. Rogers College of Law. Chin has been reading statutes for 25 years and an article he co-wrote was mentioned five times in a recent U.S. Supreme Court decision, Padilla v. Kentucky, regarding the rights of illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 It will force officers to inquire about the immigration status of everyone they stop, detain or arrest, if there is a reasonable suspicion they are illegal immigrants, rather than focusing on determining the immigration status of people who have committed serious crimes or investigating more serious crimes, as they do now, Chin said.\par \par \uc2 "Police have to have priorities," Chin said. "They can't enforce every law against everybody. They have to decide what is most important and focus on that. Traditionally, they have focused on the most serious crimes."\par \par \uc2 The language also leaves much to the discretion of individual officers, which means it could be implemented quite differently by agencies and within agencies, regents professor Michalowski said.\par \par \uc2 And he's not sure the clarification in wording will help with the damage that might have already been done in terms of losing trust in immigrant communities that now fear any contact with police could lead to deportation.\par \par \uc2 "Once widespread fear has been created as it has in Latino communities in Arizona, a few minor word changes will not get the genie back into the bottle," Michalowski said.\par \par \uc2 Many law enforcement leaders have expressed concern that the law will discourage illegal immigrants from reporting crime to police for fear of deportation. That could diminish public safety for all residents if, for instance, a murderer or rapist is on the loose.\par \par \uc2 A Tucson police officer filed a lawsuit Thursday challenging the bill on this basis, claiming the legislation would hinder investigations in Latino neighborhoods.\par \par \uc2 3. People who officers suspect are here illegally must show one of four approved identification cards to prove they are in the county legally.\par \par \uc2 * The law says: "A person is presumed to not be an alien who is unlawfully present in the United States if the person provides to the law enforcement officer or agency any of the following:\par \par \uc2 * A valid Arizona driver license.\par \par \uc2 * A valid Arizona non-operating identification license.\par \par \uc2 * A valid tribal enrollment card or other form of tribal identification.\par \par \uc2 * If the entity requires proof of legal presence in the United States before issuance, any valid United States federal, state or local government issued identification."\par \par \uc2 What that means: If you are worried you might raise the suspicion of an officer because of your ethnicity or accent, it's best to carry your Arizona driver license or other documents that show you are here lawfully, immigrant advocates say.\par \par \uc2 Although a citizen or legal resident cannot be convicted under the new law, carrying proper ID will help to avoid having to go to jail while your immigration status is confirmed, Chin said.\par \par \uc2 But Kobach downplayed the need for anybody to carry identification in The New York Times op-ed.\par \par \uc2 "Arizona's law does not require anyone, alien or otherwise, to carry a driver's license," he wrote. "Rather, it gives any alien with a license a free pass if his immigration status is in doubt. Because Arizona allows only lawful residents to obtain licenses, an officer must presume that someone who produces one is legally in the country."\par \par \uc2 4. In a change made Thursday night by the bill's sponsors, the law prohibits police from using race to establish reasonable suspicion that someone is here illegally. The original bill prohibited using "solely" race.\par \par \uc2 * The law says: "A law enforcement official or agency of this state or a county, city, town or other political subdivision of this state may not consider race, color or national origin in implementing the requirements of this subsection except to the extent permitted by the United States or Arizona Constitution."\par \par \uc2 * What that means: The bill's sponsor, Rep. Russell Pearce, R- Mesa, said the original provision was relevant because 90 percent of people in the country illegally are from Mexico and Latin America. But after the change, he said the provision is probably unnecessary, as the U.S. Constitution already precludes racial profiling. What the change does, Pearce said, is remove a target for foes, both those in court and those criticizing the measure in speeches and demonstrations.\par \par \uc2 In The New York Times op-ed, Kobach wrote, "The Arizona law actually reduces the likelihood of race-based harassment by compelling police officers to contact the federal government as soon as is practicable when they suspect a person is an illegal alien, as opposed to letting them make arrests on their own assessment."\par \par \uc2 But Chin and Michalowski said the word alteration doesn't change the fact that this is a racial-profiling law. Michalowski said the removal of "solely" was a "public-relations" maneuver that likely won't change anything.\par \par \uc2 "With or without that one word the law increases the number of instances in which officers inclined to racially profile can do so," Michalowski said.\par \par \uc2 5. The law makes it a state crime to transport, conceal, harbor or shield illegal immigrants. There is an exception for child- protective-services workers, first responders, ambulance attendants and emergency medical technicians.\par \par \uc2 * The law says: "It is unlawful for a person who is in violation of a criminal offense to:\par \par \uc2 "1. Transport or move or attempt to transport or move an alien in this state, in furtherance of the illegal presence of the alien in the United States, in a means of transportation if the person knows or recklessly disregards the fact that the alien has come to, has entered or remains in the United States in violation of law.\par \par \uc2 "2. Conceal, harbor or shield or attempt to conceal, harbor or shield an alien from detection in any place in this state, including any building or any means of transportation, if the person knows or recklessly disregards the fact that the alien has come to, has entered or remains in the United States in violation of law.\par \par \uc2 "3. Encourage or induce an alien to come to or reside in this state if the person knows or recklessly disregards the fact that such coming to, entering or residing in this state is or will be in violation of law."\par \par \uc2 * What that means: The passage is borrowed from federal law and only applies to people who know or recklessly disregard the fact that the person is an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , Kobach told The Arizona Republic.\par \par \uc2 But Michalowski said the law puts friends and family members of illegal immigrants in danger of violating the law when they are together. The law "makes citizens and legal residents criminals for providing aid to these family members and friends," he said.\par \par \uc2 "There is nothing in SB 1070 that says the law cannot be turned on them if they initiate contact with or are questioned by police in relationship to some other criminal matter," he said.\par \par \uc2 Those scenarios probably wouldn't put somebody at risk, Chin said, but he's not sure because of the inclusion of the exceptions.\par \par \uc2 6. The law makes it a state crime for illegal immigrants to work in Arizona.\par \par \uc2 * The law says: "It is unlawful for a person who is unlawfully present in the United States and who is an unauthorized alien to knowingly apply for work, solicit work in a public place or perform work as an employee or independent contractor in this state."\par \par \uc2 * What that means: This is the most clearly written part of the statute and what should be the headline of any story about the new law, Chin said.\par \par \uc2 This makes any \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  who is working or trying to get work - for example, by showing up at popular gathering spots for day laborers - at risk of being arrested by an Arizona law enforcement officer. This is a big change, because previously, a non-citizen did not commit a state crime by working or seeking work, Chin said.\par \par \uc2 7. The law also makes it a state crime for somebody to stop on the street and pick up somebody for work, although it may be hard to prove - and because of the way the law is written this may still be OK as long as the driver pulls off the road first.\par \par \uc2 * Passage: "It is unlawful for an occupant of a motor vehicle that is stopped on a street, roadway or highway to attempt to hire or hire and pick up passengers for work at a different location if the motor vehicle blocks or impedes the normal movement of traffic. ... It is unlawful for a person to enter a motor vehicle that is stopped on a street, roadway or highway in order to be hired by an occupant of the motor vehicle and to be transported to work at a different location if the motor vehicle blocks or impedes the normal movement of traffic."\par \par \uc2 * What it means: This is an attempt to make it a state crime to hire day laborers, but the way it's written it may be hard to prove without getting a confession, Chin said. As written, it seems to only make it illegal to block traffic in the street, Chin said.\par \par \uc2 The confusion in this section is a theme throughout the law, Chin said.\par \par \uc2 "I have never read a statute that was attempting to regulate an area but left so many issues open and ambiguous," he said.\par \par \uc2 But Kobach dismisses the arguments against the law as misrepresentations and defends its usefulness.\par \par \uc2 "The Arizona law hardly creates a police state," he wrote in The New York Times op-ed. "It takes a measured, reasonable step to give Arizona police officers another tool when they come into contact with illegal aliens during their normal law enforcement duties."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at bmccombs@azstarnet.com or 573- 4213. Howard Fischer of Capitol Media Services contributed to this report.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100518e65200015\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc43}{\*\bkmkend toc43}\b \uc2 400 protest at rally; voices of support at McCain forum\b0\par\par\uc2 RHONDA BODFIELD   \par \uc2 RHONDA BODFIELD, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,152 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 April 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 FUROR OVER AZ IMMIGRATION LAW\par \par \uc2 Immigration continued to dominate the political conversation Saturday at a rally with U.S. Rep. Raul Grijalva, in a town hall with U.S. Sen. John McCain - and in a Twitter posting from President Obama.\par \par \uc2 As many as 400 people - some carrying signs with slogans like "Deport the Arizona Legislature. They are the Real Danger to Our Community," and "This is what happens when we don't vote" - showed up at Grijalva's campaign headquarters on South Stone Avenue to protest Arizona's new immigration law, which authorizes police during any lawful contact to determine a person's legal status if reasonable suspicion exists.\par \par \uc2 Just as Republicans hope health-care reform will galvanize their voters for the November elections, opponents of the immigration law hope it will serve as a catalyst for their voters. Every speaker at the Grijalva rally implored the crowd to get organized and vote. And several applauded Grijalva's call for conventions to boycott Arizona.\par \par \uc2 The crowd cheered students who took to the streets for demonstrations. And they cheered when they heard the American Immigration Lawyers Association canceled its fall convention in Scottsdale, issuing a statement saying, "We cannot in good conscience spend association dollars in a state that dehumanizes the people we represent and fight for."\par \par \uc2 Richard Elias, chairman of the Board of Supervisors, echoed statements by a litany of speakers that the law will infringe on civil rights. "Yesterday, people of color lost their right to due process here in Arizona," he said, while City Council member Regina Romero called Friday "one of the darkest days in Arizona."\par \par \uc2 Brewer's signature came even as former Arizona governor and now Homeland Security Secretary Janet Napolitano said in interviews Friday "the border itself is more under control than it has ever been."\par \par \uc2 And the president, who has already said he will look into the civil rights implication of the law, sent out a "tweet" early Saturday afternoon saying the law "threatens to undermine basic notions of fairness that we cherish as Americans."\par \par \uc2 That's what worries 23-year-old Iliana Vargas, a research technician at the Grijalva rally. "It's racial profiling. There's no other way to look at it. I just see Arizona going backward."\par \par \uc2 And 21-year-old university student Jaimie Jackson said she wasn't mollified by Brewer's assurance of more officer training or of the law's language that legal status can be questioned only during a "lawful contact." "They can stop you for anything," she said, saying it's inconvenient for people to have to carry important registration documents at all times, even for quick trips to the mall or the grocery store.\par \par \uc2 Grijalva, a Democrat, said the economic boycott will be trivial compared with the money Arizona will lose in tourism and retail sales. And he called on Congress to "show the spine and the humanity to reform immigration laws," warning that otherwise, the new law will be a harbinger of things to come in other states.\par \par \uc2 He also continued his call for the U.S. government to refuse to cooperate. Since federal law has supremacy, he said, if the federal government refuses to detain or process the cases, then the new law is moot. He called for a "cleansing" at the state Legislature, which he said for too long has been tolerated as "silly extremists."\par \par \uc2 "Well, they're silly, but they're dangerous," he said, urging the crowd to continue nonviolent opposition.\par \par \uc2 Across town, about 80 people came to a McCain town hall where immigration also dominated the discussion.\par \par \uc2 Although McCain had sounded a note of support for the bill, calling it a "good tool" for law enforcement, he stopped short of fully endorsing the measure. "I haven't had a chance to look at all the aspects, but I do understand why the Legislature would act," he said. Even though it wasn't clear to him "whether all of it is legal or not," he said state lawmakers "acted out of frustration because the federal government didn't do its job."\par \par \uc2 He spoke of his 10-point plan to do that, including boosting border troops, paying them more, finishing the fence, improving communications equipment and giving more resources to local law enforcement.\par \par \uc2 Several in the crowd said they support the new law and expressed frustration about the lack of border enforcement.\par \par \uc2 Bob Foy, a 68-year-old retired lieutenant in the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department, said holes in border enforcement are allowing the free flow of narcotics and weapons into the country. "We're in such imminent danger that we don't have another 100 years to get this straight," he said. The new law, while "not the perfect answer, is an answer," he said.\par \par \uc2 One woman said she lives near the Buenos Aires National Wildlife Refuge, which is being "trashed" by border crossers. Another said her daughter's boyfriend is an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  who has been in prison three times and keeps coming back.\par \par \uc2 One man chimed in that he was concerned about the mood, saying he was getting a vibe of animosity toward Mexican people in general.\par \par \uc2 McCain responded, "I am worried about anti-Hispanic feeling in this country, and I am concerned about condemning good, honest citizens of Hispanic origin because of this (immigration) problem." He noted Tucson was a Spanish-speaking city before it was English and he cherished the Latino heritage.\par \par \uc2 But pointing to the murder of rancher Robert Krentz, he said border problems need to be addressed not only for citizens here but for immigrants, who aren't protected under American laws and are preyed upon by criminal elements.\par \par \uc2 Pressed by one woman to call Grijalva's boycott irresponsible, McCain said he strongly disagrees with it, especially since the economy is hurting.\par \par \uc2 McCain, a Republican who has previously backed efforts to strengthen border security while creating a path to citizenship for illegal immigrants, has been speaking almost exclusively about border security this election season. The primary race pits him against former U.S. Congressman J.D. Hayworth, who is painting himself as the more conservative option.\par \par \uc2 McCain's border stance sits just fine with 60-year-old Patricia Patterson, a concierge. "I was on the fence about a few things, and then I saw him shift away from amnesty, and that brought me back to his side," she said.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, 29-year-old film student Omar Martinez said he's leaning toward McCain also. "I was crushed by the new law," he said. While he's fearful that people of Mexican descent like himself will be made scapegoats, particularly given deep economic frustrations, he said he was pleased with McCain's comments respecting his culture.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Rhonda Bodfield at 573-4243 or rbodfield@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100512e64p00042\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc44}{\*\bkmkend toc44}\b \uc2 Poll: Arizonans like immigration bill\b0\par\par\uc2 RHONDA BODFIELD   \par \uc2 RHONDA BODFIELD, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 584 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 April 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 A majority of likely voters appear willing to swap tougher enforcement for civil-rights protections, according to a new poll that found 70 percent of likely voters support a measure authorizing police to check the immigration status of anyone they suspect of being an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Although critics have staged rallies and protests, fearful it will lead to racial profiling, a Rasmussen Reports poll of 500 likely voters found only 23 percent say they oppose the law, which still must be signed by the governor.\par \par \uc2 Even so, about 53 percent of voters say they're concerned that the efforts could violate the rights of some U.S. citizens.\par \par \uc2 When broken down by party, Republicans are more supportive - at 84 percent - than are Democrats, who are more closely divided with 51 percent in favor.\par \par \uc2 More than 80 percent of voters surveyed said a candidate's position on immigration is an important factor in how they will vote.\par \par \uc2 Republican Gov. Jan Brewer has not said whether she'll sign SB 1070, although all three of her front line challengers say they support it. Businessman Buz Mills said, "For too long, we've waited for federal officials to do their job and secure the border," while state Treasurer Dean Martin said he supports giving law enforcement more tools to do their job.\par \par \uc2 Tucson attorney John Munger said he wants to secure the border using the Department of Public Safety and the National Guard. "We cannot keep waiting for the federal government to solve this problem for us, especially when we have the means and the authority to take action ourselves," he said.\par \par \uc2 On the other side of the political spectrum, the Border Action Network invited opponents to a mock funeral for the state Monday to mark its passage, saying the son of "responsibility and common good" had passed, but was survived by "hope, mercy and justice."\par \par \uc2 Democratic Attorney General Terry Goddard also is against it, as is U.S. Rep. Raul Grijalva, who is calling on businesses and national organizations to boycott Arizona as a destination. He noted a Super Bowl ban was effective in overturning the state's refusal to recognize Martin Luther King Jr. Day.\par \par \uc2 "Turning every police officer in the state into a roving immigration official, armed with a racial profiling mandate, is un- American on its face and cannot withstand even casual legal scrutiny," Grijalva said.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Republican U.S. Sen. Jon Kyl expressed sarcastic disapproval of Grijalva's comments.\par \par \uc2 "That's very helpful. An Arizona congressman calling for folks to boycott his home state?" Kyl said in the Washington Times. "That'll really help job creation. End of comment."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Rhonda Bodfield at 573-4243 or rbodfield@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 hear candidates' views\par \par \uc2 Want to know where high-profile GOP candidates stand on immigration and other important issues facing the state? This is your weekend.\par \par \uc2 On Friday, three of the four top Republican candidates for governor - state Treasurer Dean Martin, Tucson attorney John Munger and businessman Buz Mills - will debate at Sabino High School, 5000 N. Bowes Road. The two-hour debate kicks off at 6:30 p.m. Doors open at 6 p.m.\par \par \uc2 Then, on Saturday, Republican U.S. Sen. John McCain will host a community town hall at Pima Community College, where he will field questions. The event, which begins at 11 a.m., will be at the East Campus, 8181 E. Irvington Road.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100512e64m0000y\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc45}{\*\bkmkend toc45}\b \uc2 1 sought in burglaries; Krentz link is possible\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 374 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 April 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A8\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 The Cochise County Sheriff's Office is looking for a person of interest in several burglaries this year in the Portal area in southeastern Arizona.\par \par \uc2 It is looking for Alejandro Chavez-Vasquez, who has given authorities various birth dates and lives in Agua Prieta, Mexico. Officials say he has a criminal history with convictions that include sex crimes, auto theft and being in and returning the the U.S. after being deported, according to a news release.\par \par \uc2 The news release doesn't identify Chavez-Vasquez as a person of interest in the killing of longtime rancher Robert Krentz on March 27, but a news release of this type is unusual for the department, and the Portal area is just north of where Krentz was found dead on his ranch.\par \par \uc2 Chavez-Vasquez is currently only a person of interest in the burglaries.\par \par \uc2 But Cochise County Sheriff's spokeswoman Carol Capas said she didn't dismiss the possibility that Chavez-Vasquez could provide useful information in the Krentz investigation. "It would depend on what he would be able to tell us about other burglaries or other open cases we have," Capas said.\par \par \uc2 As of now, there are no suspects or persons of interest in the Krentz case, she said.\par \par \uc2 Krentz was found shot and killed on his ATV on his ranch, about 25 miles northeast of Douglas.\par \par \uc2 Investigators don't know who shot him, but they followed a single set of tracks back to Mexico, fueling speculation that the killer was an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  or smuggler.\par \par \uc2 During a Senate hearing Tuesday in Washington, D.C., Cochise County Sheriff Larry Dever said investigators have reason to believe the shooter was a scout for a drug-smuggling organization.\par \par \uc2 At a March 29 news conference, Dever said there was another incident in the area involving a gun within 24 hours of the shooting that could be connected to the Krentz case. He would not elaborate.\par \par \uc2 Anyone with information about Chavez-Vasquez is asked to call the Cochise County Sheriff's Office at 520-432-9500 or 1-800-362-0812.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100512e64m0000x\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc46}{\*\bkmkend toc46}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 BRIAN J PEDERSEN & PHIL VILLARREAL   \par \uc2 BRIAN J. PEDERSEN & PHIL VILLARREAL, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 607 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 April 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A9\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Drop house brings 10 counts of guilty\par \par \uc2 A Mexican national has been convicted of 10 federal charges in connection with a \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  drop house found last year on Tucson's south side.\par \par \uc2 Paulino Rios-Ledezma, 41, was found guilty Thursday in U.S. District Court of three counts of possession of a firearm during a crime of violence, two counts of hostage taking, two counts of harboring illegal aliens, one count of conspiracy to commit hostage taking, one count of conspiracy to harbor and transport illegal aliens and one count of illegal alien in possession of a firearm, court records show.\par \par \uc2 Rios-Ledezma was one of five men arrested by Tucson police on March 31, 2009, after someone called 911 to say someone had been kidnapped and was being held at a home in the 800 block of West Valencia Road, court records show.\par \par \uc2 When police arrived they found 36 people inside the home, all of them later identified as Mexican citizens who were in the U.S. illegally, according to court records.\par \par \uc2 Officers found an AK-47 assault rifle and a 9 mm handgun inside the home, and witnesses said Rios-Ledezma and four other men took turns pointing them at the hostages, court records show.\par \par \uc2 Two of Rios-Ledezma's co-defendants pleaded guilty in September to hostage-taking and weapons charges and were sentenced to 14 and 12 years, respectively. A third defendant is scheduled to be sentenced April 26 and a fourth was committed to a psychiatric facility last fall.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Boy, 15, gets 4 years in drive-by shooting\par \par \uc2 A 15-year-old boy who said he was trying to defend his family from neighborhood harassment was sentenced Friday to two years in state prison for his role in a New Year's Eve drive-by-shooting.\par \par \uc2 Elias Hernandez was 14 at the time of the incident, which occurred Dec. 31 near East 29th Street and South Winstel Boulevard, the neighborhood where Hernandez and his family lived, according to Pima County Superior Court records.\par \par \uc2 Assistant Pima County Legal Defender Jordan Cohen said Hernandez shot at three men from inside a vehicle because he was trying to get the men to stop tormenting him and his family, something that had occurred for the four months the family had lived in the neighborhood.\par \par \uc2 "This was a case of an immature young man who lost his cool," Cohen said. "He felt he had no choice but to stand up for his family."\par \par \uc2 One of the men Hernandez shot at was injured, court records show.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Van likely carrying migrants crashes\par \par \uc2 A minivan believed to be carrying illegal immigrants crashed into an irrigation ditch Friday morning on Interstate 10 near Marana Road.\par \par \uc2 There were 15 people in the van when it crashed just before 8:30 a.m., said Officer Quentin G. Mehr, Arizona Department of Public Safety spokesman. Two people were injured and taken to a hospital, he said.\par \par \uc2 U.S. Border Patrol officers had stopped the minivan along the freeway, but once the officers got out of their vehicle the van sped away before crashing into the irrigation ditch, Border Patrol spokeswoman Colleen Agle said.\par \par \uc2 All 15 people are in Border Patrol custody, including two people who are being identified as suspects, she said.\par \par \uc2 Phil Villarreal and Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the city of Tucson, updated every morning with the previous day's data, at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100511e64h0000j\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc47}{\*\bkmkend toc47}\b \uc2 68 arrested in smuggling raid\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,272 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 April 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 ICE-led operation targets shuttle firms in effort to halt \uc2 illegal- immigrant\uc2  traffic\par \par \uc2 Immigration agents raided four shuttle companies on Tucson's south side Thursday morning as part of a major binational operation targeting an \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  smuggling network.\par \par \uc2 Officials mobilized more than 800 federal, state and local law enforcement officers to arrest 68 total people in Tucson, Phoenix, Rio Rico, Nogales, Ariz., and Nogales, Sonora, Immigration and Customs Enforcement officials said.\par \par \uc2 The arrests marked the culmination of a yearlong investigation named "Operation in Plain Sight" that ICE officials called the largest \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  smuggling investigation in the agency's seven-year history.\par \par \uc2 Fifty-one of the people arrested were owners and employees of four Tucson shuttle companies, and a fifth from Phoenix, that ran a smuggling ring that transported thousands of illegal immigrants from the border to Tucson and Phoenix, officials said. Mexican officials arrested Claudio Ramirez-Morales who was described as the Mexican- based manager of a smuggling organization.\par \par \uc2 The other 17 arrested were illegal immigrants agents encountered as they served search warrants in Phoenix and Tucson.\par \par \uc2 Thursday's busts were a major shift in how ICE and other federal agencies deal with illegal immigration, said John Morton, assistant secretary of Homeland Security for Immigration and Customs Enforcement.\par \par \uc2 "We are not seeking to prosecute a given smuggler, a given shuttle company, a given driver,'' he said. "We are seeking to take down an entire human-smuggling industry."\par \par \uc2 But while ICE championed the busts, many of Tucson's south-side residents and immigrant advocates questioned the show of force and hordes of media invited to watch.\par \par \uc2 "This is an intimidating tactic," said Carmen Sanchez, who lives nearby and came to watch. "This is putting fear into the Hispanic community."\par \par \uc2 Several arrested, vans seized\par \par \uc2 The raids brought traffic on South Sixth Avenue to a near standstill Thursday morning as immigration agents raided shuttle companies in front of a throng of cameras and reporters the agency had invited to watch, dozens of curious residents, immigrant advocates and Mexican Consulate officials looking on from across the street.\par \par \uc2 At Sahuaro Roadrunner Shuttle, 4207 S. Sixth Ave., two Immigration and Customs Enforcement agents escorted a handcuffed man from inside into an unmarked white Tahoe. They seized five vans from that location.\par \par \uc2 At the next door Sonora Shuttle, 4201 S. Sixth Ave., passengers from a van that had just arrived from Nogales were asked to get out of the van and agents checked the identifications of several. An ICE official said this particular van was not involved in the investigation.\par \par \uc2 Agents seized Andrew Provencio's shuttle, which he runs out of the Sahuaro Roadrunner location. Agents told him the shuttle was being used for people smuggling. But Provencio and his son, Ricardo Gomez, said they aren't involved in any smuggling. Gomez, who drives the shuttle to and from Nogales and was in the van at the time of the seizure, was questioned by ICE agents but was not arrested.\par \par \uc2 Provencio, who was visibly upset, said he bought the 2007 van last year and was just starting to pay off a loan on the $22,000 vehicle. Without making daily trips, he won't be able to make his $400 monthly payment.\par \par \uc2 "You are not even involved in what's going on and they seize everything," Provencio said. "We are clean. We are not that stupid to be bringing people."\par \par \uc2 Gomez said he and other shuttle drivers are prohibited from asking passengers about their immigration status. The owner of Sahuaro Shuttle, Vidal Ramirez, agreed.\par \par \uc2 "I don't have the right to ask for papers," Ramirez said. "I sell the ticket and that's it."\par \par \uc2 His company, which runs trips from Tucson to Douglas, Phoenix and Nogales, was not raided or visited by immigration agents. He said he wasn't scared when he saw the immigration agents but was alarmed at the size of the media and law enforcement presence.\par \par \uc2 "It's a big, big circus," Ramirez said.\par \par \uc2 He wasn't alone in his assessment of the raids.\par \par \uc2 Ushering the man out of Sahuaro Roadrunner in front of the cameras was a "disgusting perp walk," said Kat Rodriguez of Coalicion de Derechos Humanos.\par \par \uc2 "I hope they are ashamed of themselves," she said.\par \par \uc2 The massive show of force terrorized Tucson's south-side community and destroyed trust in the community, she said. She received calls all day from people worried about going to work or taking their children to school.\par \par \uc2 Border Action Network director Jennifer Allen said her organization supports action to curtail smugglers that exploit illegal immigrants but questioned the way the raids were conducted.\par \par \uc2 "It was such a heavy show of force," Allen said.\par \par \uc2 Rick Crocker, ICE deputy special agent in charge in Tucson, said Tucson police were there to provide officer and public safety. And he said that even though they were targeting the criminal leaders of the smuggling ring, they couldn't turn their back when they encountered illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 How it works\par \par \uc2 According to Immigration and Customs Enforcement officials, here how's the smuggling operation usually worked:\par \par \uc2 People were smuggled across the border and escorted to Tucson in private vehicles or in some cases, by waling around the checkpoint on Interstate 19.\par \par \uc2 In Tucson, they were passed off to shuttle companies "who are in cahoots with the smugglers," Morton said. They were housed at shuttle companies or drop houses.\par \par \uc2 Illegal immigrants would pay the shuttle companies a fee of $100 or more and be given fake fare receipts in the amount of $30 to make shuttle trips to Phoenix appear legitimate.\par \par \uc2 In Phoenix, they were taken to drop houses where other smuggling organizations took over, getting the illegal immigrants to their final destinations throughout the country.\par \par \uc2 Most of the smuggled illegal border crossers were from Mexico and Central America, but some came from as far away as China.\par \par \uc2 Those arrested are facing several federal violations, including money laundering, \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  smuggling and conspiracy. Those arrested in Arizona are expected to make their initial appearances in federal courts in Phoenix and Tucson today.\par \par \uc2 ICE seized about $10 million worth of assets, including more than 50 vehicles. During the arrests, agents found several weapons including an AK-47, Morton said.\par \par \uc2 The criminal heads of smuggling organizations are bad people, Crocker said.\par \par \uc2 "These are not good people. These are the people that hold them hostage," Crocker said. "The people that we arrested are not the people that come north looking for work."\par \par \uc2 Two months, ICE made a similar set of arrests of shuttle operators in the Houston area. More are likely, Morton said.\par \par \uc2 "The veil has been lifted over these shuttle companies,'' Morton said. "We're going to go after them wherever they are and we're going to expose them for what they are, and that is fronts for criminal networks.''\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com. The Associated Press and Howard Fischer of Capitol Media Services contributed to this report.\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Go to azstarnet.com/databases to track deportations by country or year.\par \par \uc2 Raided shuttle companies\par \par \uc2 Tucson\par \par \uc2 * Sahuaro Roadrunner Shuttles\par \par \uc2 * America's Shuttles\par \par \uc2 * Sonoran Shuttles\par \par \uc2 * Nogales Express Shuttles\par \par \uc2 Phoenix\par \par \uc2 * Sergio's Shuttle\par \par \uc2 68 total arrests\par \par \uc2 Tucson\par \par \uc2 * 21 criminal suspects, most of whom are U.S. citizens and legal permanent residents.\par \par \uc2 * 7 illegal immigrants arrested.\par \par \uc2 Nogales/Rio Rico\par \par \uc2 * 5 criminal suspects, most of whom are U.S. citizens and legal permanent residents.\par \par \uc2 Phoenix\par \par \uc2 * 23 criminal suspects, most of whom are U.S. citizens and legal permanent residents.\par \par \uc2 * 10 illegal immigrants arrested.\par \par \uc2 Nogales, Sonora\par \par \uc2 * 2 criminal arrests\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100511e64g0005r\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc48}{\*\bkmkend toc48}\b \uc2 Plan would clear way for water stations on Buenos Aires refuge\b0\par\par\uc2 DALE QUINN   \par \uc2 DALE QUINN, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 620 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 April 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par B1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Aid groups had run afoul for placing jugs\par \par \uc2 Officials are asking for public input on a proposal to establish and maintain drinking water stations in the Buenos Aires National Wildlife Refuge to prevent migrant deaths in the rugged terrain southwest of Tucson.\par \par \uc2 The proposal signals a resolution to a standoff between refuge officials and humanitarian groups that have left gallon-jugs of water on \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  trails southeast of Arivaca.\par \par \uc2 "We tried to reach a happy medium," said refuge manager Michael Hawkes.\par \par \uc2 Refuge staffers and representatives from the aid organizations have been working together for months on ideas about positioning water stations in a way that causes the least impact to sensitive wildlife, said Gene Lefebvre, a retired minister and co-founder of No More Deaths.\par \par \uc2 Volunteers from No More Deaths, Samaritans and Humane Borders have received littering tickets in several instances over the past two years for putting out jugs on refuge land.\par \par \uc2 A prosecutor recently asked the court to dismiss charges against 13 people who had placed water jugs, Lefebvre said.\par \par \uc2 Hawkes, who has been critical of those placing the water jugs, said the U.S. government asked for the dismissal because the humanitarian groups made a good-faith effort to secure proper permits.\par \par \uc2 Since 2001, the refuge has issued a special-use permit to Humane Borders to maintain three water stations that consist of two 55- gallon drums. The draft assessment now under consideration looks at adding drinking water stations. The new stations would have containers tethered so they couldn't be removed by people traveling on foot.\par \par \uc2 "Drinking water stations would be strategically placed on or near existing trails," the draft assessment says. "Refuge management would ensure that water stations would not be placed in areas that may impact threatened or endangered species, sensitive habitat areas, or frequently used visitor areas such as designated camping sites and recreational trails."\par \par \uc2 Details about the locations of the water stations and the amount of water placed there are still being worked out, Lefebvre said. But the humanitarian groups have been pleased with the negotiations.\par \par \uc2 "It looks like it's going to be a workable plan," Lefebvre said.\par \par \uc2 The assessment concludes the additional water sites could both hurt and help the refuge. The stations could result in wildlife habitat loss and increased trash, and could alter migrant trails through the refuge. They could also affect visitors' experiences, the draft says.\par \par \uc2 While humanitarian groups say their goal is to reduce or eliminate \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  deaths in the refuge, the draft says no studies exist on whether providing water is an effective way to prevent deaths.\par \par \uc2 "If the numbers of deaths are not reduced by this activity, the need for permitting water stations on the refuge would be re- evaluated and could be reduced or eliminated," the draft says.\par \par \uc2 Still, Lefebvre was optimistic his group and refuge officials would be able to reach an effective compromise.\par \par \uc2 "We don't want to be in any kind of engagement with law enforcement," Lefebvre said. "We just want to get to our humanitarian work."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Dale Quinn at 573-4197 or dquinn@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 To comment:\par \par \uc2 Federal law requires that the Buenos Aires National Wildlife Refuge manager provide a 30-day window for public review and comment on the draft assessment.\par \par \uc2 Those interested have until May 3 to provide written comments to Refuge Headquarters, P.O. Box 109, Sasabe, 85633. Written comments may be sent by fax to (520) 823-4247 or e-mailed to Mike_Hawkes@fws.gov\par \par \uc2 To view a copy of the draft, go to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.fws.gov/southwest"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.fws.gov/southwest}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100422e6440000y\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc49}{\*\bkmkend toc49}\b \uc2 Chiricahua neighbors fearful as never before\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,170 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 April 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Feeling spreads in ranch country after slaying of Robert Krentz\par \par \uc2 NEAR PORTAL - The hour- glass-shaped San Bernardino and San Simon valleys where rancher Robert Krentz was killed a week ago are nestled between the snow-capped Chiricahua Mountains to the west and the Peloncillo Mountains to the east.\par \par \uc2 It's a sparsely populated area on the eastern edge of Arizona along a 70-mile stretch from the U.S.-Mexico border to Interstate 10. There are a mix of longtime ranching families like the Krentzes, newer "40-acre ranchers," retirees and others who came for open space and solitude.\par \par \uc2 The smuggling of people and drugs across their backyards is something residents here have dealt with for decades. But, they say the killing of Krentz cements a disturbing evolution that began a few years ago - illegal border activity has gone from irritating to deadly dangerous.\par \par \uc2 "I've never felt more unsafe in my whole life," said Bill McDonald, a fifth-generation rancher who's property shares a fence with the 35,000-acre Krentz ranch. "I wonder if I want my kids and grandkids to live here. I've never had that feeling."\par \par \uc2 Cochise County Sheriff Larry Dever has called the killing a senseless act by a sick person. Investigators believe the killer fled into Mexico. However, investigators don't have a motive and don't know anything about the suspect, including whether the killer is Mexican or a U.S. citizen.\par \par \uc2 Sheriff's investigators attribute the spike in burglaries there over the past two years to illegal immigrants and smugglers.\par \par \uc2 The Krentz family said in a statement this week that Robert Krentz, 58, was killed by a suspected \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 . Most residents here say they believe the killer was a Mexican drug smuggler.\par \par \uc2 "We are being invaded now by some nasty people who are perfectly willing to kill," said Chuck Osgood, 66. "These are not people coming for a better life."\par \par \uc2 Not all residents feel they are being invaded. But most agree they will be more cautious when they encounter smugglers and illegal border crossers. Craig McEwan, who moved to the area from Missouri six years ago, said he'll keep taking his frequent jogs and hikes through the Chiricahuas but says he feels more vulnerable.\par \par \uc2 Many blame the U.S. government for ignoring their warnings about the increased criminal activity and for failing to protect them. The Krentz family says it holds no malice toward Mexican people. They say political forces in U.S and Mexico are accountable for the death.\par \par \uc2 "Their disregard of our repeated pleas and warnings of impending violence towards our community fell on deaf ears shrouded in political correctness," the family statement says. "As a result, we have paid the ultimate price for their negligence."\par \par \uc2 Burglaries and break-ins\par \par \uc2 Like many families in the valleys, the Osgoods' home has been broken into. Sherri Osgood takes her gun with her even when she's putting laundry on a clothesline outside.\par \par \uc2 "We are afraid for our lives," Sherri Osgood said. "You don't know who's coming over the mountain."\par \par \uc2 In 2009, Cochise County deputies went to the area 53 times on calls about burglaries, property damage and suspicious activity. So far this year, they've gone 21 times, figures provided by department spokeswoman Carol Capas show. Some arrests have been made, but many crimes are unsolved. The sheriff's department didn't track such incidents by specific area before 2009, but Capas said there has clearly been an increase.\par \par \uc2 Some of the crimes in the area have been violent. On Jan. 20, suspects forced their way into the home and bound the older couple who lives there with duct tape. The intruders stole a bank card and the couple's 2004 Chevy Avalanche. Two men were arrested shortly after in Lordsburg, N.M. Capas said both were illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 Most residents believe the robberies are being committed by drug smugglers heading back to Mexico. Unlike northbound groups of illegal border crossers who sometimes take food, water and clothes, smugglers covet valuables they can use or sell including guns, vehicles, binoculars and telescopes, residents say.\par \par \uc2 The extension of border fencing and vehicle barriers east of Douglas toward the New Mexico line by the Department of Homeland Security in the last three years has pushed smugglers farther east and through the valley, McDonald said. His family's 103-year-old ranch is located there, about 30 miles east of Douglas and five miles north of the border on Geronimo Trail. Trekking through the Pelocillo or Chiricahua Mountains doesn't deter drug runners, he said.\par \par \uc2 "These are extremely determined people with a strong profit incentive," said McDonald, who is executive director of the Malpai Borderlands Group, an organization of conservation-minded ranchers.\par \par \uc2 The spotty cell-phone service adds to the feeling of insecurity. Residents say it can take a long time for sheriff's deputies or Border Patrol agents to arrive.\par \par \uc2 The Cochise County Sheriff's Office has recently assigned all of its deputies working overtime hours under the Department of Homeland Security's Operation Stonegarden grant program to the area. And the Border Patrol opened a base in the area staffed around the clock.\par \par \uc2 Investigation\par \par \uc2 Friends and neighbors of Krentz can't fathom why anybody would want to kill a kind and compassionate man. "He's not a person who would instigate a violent confrontation," McDonald said.\par \par \uc2 Some wonder if a call made to the Border Patrol the day before by Phil Krentz, the victim's brother, about marijuana found on the property led to a retaliation killing. The Border Patrol says it recovered 290 pounds of marijuana on the ranch and arrested eight people nearby. But, they weren't able to prosecute them for lack of evidence.\par \par \uc2 Other residents, including a longtime friend, Nick Forsythe of Douglas, think Krentz was in the wrong place at the wrong time and came upon a person who simply wasn't going to let himself be apprehended. He doesn't buy the retaliation theory.\par \par \uc2 "Three-hundred pounds to these guys is nothing," Forsythe said of the seized pot load. "It's like you losing a pitching wedge at the golf course. It's not worth killing a rancher, because they know the huge repercussions."\par \par \uc2 Billy Darnell, a fourth-generation rancher and former Hidalgo County sheriff in New Mexico, said its important for investigators to keep an open mind about what have happened to Krentz. While it appears the shooter was likely a Mexican drug runner, that's not set in stone, said Darnell, who grew up near Apache.\par \par \uc2 "You don't want to put all your eggs in one basket," said Darnell, 66. "It'll get you in trouble."\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 More online\par \par \uc2 To read more about the facts of the investigation, go to Brady McCombs' blog, Border Boletin, at: azstarnet.com/news/blogs/border- boletin\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100421e6430001m\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc50}{\*\bkmkend toc50}\b \uc2 Cochise ranch area outraged by killing\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,098 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 March 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 NEAR PORTAL - Neighbor ranchers of the slain Robert Krentz say they had been warning U.S. officials for years that somebody would be killed if they didn't gain control of this dangerous smuggling corridor where armed burglaries have become a daily occurrence.\par \par \uc2 Now, they're demanding immediate action.\par \par \uc2 Krentz, a longtime rancher, was shot and killed Saturday in Cochise County, by a likely southbound smuggler, who authorities believe escaped into Mexico.\par \par \uc2 "The Mexican outlaws have total control, and it's going to get worse," said Ed Ashurst, whose 53,000-acre ranch is just east of the Krentz ranch. "There is going to be more bloodshed."\par \par \uc2 On Monday, in reaction to the killing, Gov. Jan Brewer reiterated a March 2009 request to send 250 additional National Guard soldiers to Arizona's border.\par \par \uc2 Rancher Dean Nelson said the National Guard should have already been called. "If the government doesn't call out the Guard, they don't care about us," Nelson said.\par \par \uc2 But Ashurst said the National Guard won't improve safety unless its personnel are given the green light to shoot at smugglers.\par \par \uc2 "They are going to have to kill some of those outlaws," Ashurst said. "I am going to protect myself and I will use deadly force. . . . I have a gun, and if an illegal alien ever gets in my house, he's dead."\par \par \uc2 The desire for a more aggressive stance at the border is shared by others in the area.\par \par \uc2 "Dig a ditch 20-feet deep and when they cross it, that's where they stay," said Hal Mortensen, a retired rancher and lifelong Cochise County resident who had known Krentz for 40 years.\par \par \uc2 Ranchers in the unincorporated community of Apache, about 25 miles northeast of Douglas, say they'll now be more vigilant when they encounter illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 Ashurst, Nelson and Mortensen described Krentz as a good man who didn't have enemies.\par \par \uc2 Cochise County Sheriff Larry Dever called the incident a "senseless shooting." He said there is no evidence to suggest there was any confrontation.\par \par \uc2 "There is absolutely no reason this had to happen other than the bad intentions of one sick, sorry individual that we hope to be able to catch up to very quickly," Dever said.\par \par \uc2 The sheriff said he's worried angry ranchers may take matters into their own hands with smugglers.\par \par \uc2 "I'm angry as well, but the law is the law, and we have to act within certain constraints, and we'll encourage everybody else to do the same," Dever said.\par \par \uc2 Krentz, who was out checking water lines and fencing on his family's 35,000-acre ranch, had weapons with him on the ATV he was riding, but he did not use them, Dever said.\par \par \uc2 Investigators have determined the shooting was carried out by one person, but they don't know anything about the person.\par \par \uc2 They believe it was an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  because Krentz was heard telling his brother on two-way radio "illegal alien" and because the area is a known smuggling corridor.\par \par \uc2 They have no motive.\par \par \uc2 Dever said Krentz was frustrated and fed up with the illegal activity like many ranchers in the area. But he said he was compassionate and regularly helped illegal immigrants in distress.\par \par \uc2 "There is no reason to believe anything else other than what happened that day with Rob," said Dever.\par \par \uc2 Krentz was found about 1,000 feet from where they believe the shooting occurred, dead on his ATV. The ATV still had its lights on and the engine running, Dever said. There were spin-out marks in the dirt, leading investigators to believe that he was trying to get away, Dever said.\par \par \uc2 Investigators believe the shooter was headed toward the border when Krentz encountered him. Law enforcement tracked a single set of footprints - believed to be the shooter's - for 20 miles to the U.S.- Mexico border. They also contacted Mexican authorities, but so far there is no information about the killer.\par \par \uc2 Dever said it will be very difficult to find the shooter and would likely require that the shooter talk about the incident with somebody.\par \par \uc2 While investigators don't have a motive yet, retaliation has been raised as a possibility, Dever said.\par \par \uc2 The day before the shooting, the victim's brother, Phil Krentz, reported drug smuggling on the ranch to the Border Patrol.\par \par \uc2 Agents found 290 pounds of marijuana on the ranch and followed tracks to where they found and arrested eight illegal immigrants, said Robert Boatright, deputy chief of the Border Patrol's Tucson Sector. None were prosecuted because of a lack of evidence. They were all in custody when the shooting occurred, he said.\par \par \uc2 Krentz regularly called the Border Patrol to let it know about illegal activity on the ranch, the agency said.\par \par \uc2 Dever also said there was another incident within 24 hours of the shooting that could be connected involving a gun, but he would not elaborate.\par \par \uc2 The area where the shooting occurred is a well-known drug- and people-smuggling corridor, Boatright said. In the summer of 2009, after seeing a spike in activity in the area, the agency opened a base staffed around the clock with 20 agents.\par \par \uc2 Dever said his deputies have responded to several calls from residents in the area about burglaries, property damage and even a few home invasions. Recently, the county had assigned all of the deputies working overtime hours under a Department of Homeland Security grant program to the area.\par \par \uc2 "There has been a prevailing sense for sometime in the community that something like this was going to happen," Dever said.\par \par \uc2 Krentz was a member of the board of directors of the Malpai Borderlands Group, an organization of conservation-minded ranchers.\par \par \uc2 Krentz's family had been ranching their property since 1907, and in 2008 the Krentz Ranch was inducted into the Arizona Farming and Ranching Hall of Fame.\par \par \uc2 "His impact on ranching in Southern Arizona can't be overstated nor can his contributions to Cochise County," said former state Sen. Jonathan Paton of Tucson. "Mr. Krentz's compassion and spirit will be remembered by many as we try to understand this senseless tragedy."\par \par \uc2 There is a community meeting planned for 6 p.m. Wednesday in the schoolhouse in Apache to discuss safety issues.\par \par \uc2 Star reporters Brian J. Pedersen and Tim Steller contributed to this report. Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Read more about border-related issues in Brady McCombs' blog at go.azstarnet.com/borderboletin\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100414e63u0002n\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc51}{\*\bkmkend toc51}\b \uc2 Well-known Douglas-area rancher is found slain\b0\par\par\uc2 MEGAN NEIGHBOR; ANDREA RIVERA   \par \uc2 MEGAN NEIGHBOR AND ANDREA RIVERA, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 598 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 March 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 A longtime rancher was killed on his Douglas-area property over the weekend, and neighbors worried that his homicide was connected to increasing border-related crime in the area.\par \par \uc2 The Cochise County Sheriff's Office offered little information into the late-Saturday shooting death of 58-year-old Robert Krentz, whose family began the Krentz Ranch more than 100 years ago.\par \par \uc2 Krentz's body was found on his land, which is about 35 miles northeast of Douglas, just before midnight Saturday, said Carol Capas, a spokeswoman for the Sheriff's Office.\par \par \uc2 The Sheriff's Office, aided by the U.S. Border Patrol, had no suspects Sunday and continued to follow leads, Capas said. She declined to comment on reports from neighbors and border activists that Krentz's death was related to smuggling in the area.\par \par \uc2 Area residents said Krentz had no enemies, and they could think of no motive for his death other than the possibility it was related to what they called the growing level of crime in the area related to illegal immigrants and drug smugglers.\par \par \uc2 Tom Tancredo, a former U.S. representative from Colorado, was visiting ranchers near Douglas to discuss border issues when he heard of Krentz's death.\par \par \uc2 Tancredo said he and Krentz were friends and that he was "a mild- mannered guy" who was known for providing illegal immigrants with food and water.\par \par \uc2 Tancredo and Chris Simcox, co-founder of the Minuteman Civil Defense Corps, said Krentz phoned a family member Saturday afternoon to say he was out near his watering hole, providing one or more illegal immigrants with aid.\par \par \uc2 That's the last his family heard from him, Simcox and Tancredo said.\par \par \uc2 "He looked the other way so often," Tancredo said. "It's so ironic that he, of all people, got murdered."\par \par \uc2 If Krentz's killing was caused by an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  or a drug smuggler, U.S. Border Patrol spokesman Omar Candelaria said, it would be a first for the area, to his recollection.\par \par \uc2 "We haven't seen any instances of illegal immigrants or drug smugglers attacking U.S. citizens," Candelaria said.\par \par \uc2 Others who live nearby were unwilling to disclose their names when they spoke about the homicide Sunday because, they said, they were afraid of possible repercussions. A person at the Krentz home also declined to comment.\par \par \uc2 In a 1999 PBS interview, Robert Krentz and his wife, Susan, said illegal immigrants once stole property from their ranch, but that incident didn't stop him from aiding other trespassers.\par \par \uc2 "You know, we've personally been broke in once. And they took about $700 worth of stuff. And you know, if they come in and ask for water, I'll still give them water. I, you know, that's just my nature," Krentz was quoted as saying in written transcripts of the interview.\par \par \uc2 The longtime rancher's homicide already has caught U.S. Rep. Gabrielle Giffords' attention.\par \par \uc2 Sometime this week, the Arizona Democrat will travel to Douglas for a briefing on the homicide, said Giffords' spokesman, C.J. Karamargin.\par \par \uc2 "Rob Krentz was a pillar of the Cochise County ranching community," Giffords said in a press release. "He will be greatly missed."\par \par \uc2 The Krentz family's cattle ranch was inducted into the Arizona Farming and Ranching Hall of Fame in 2008. The family started the ranch in 1907.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporters Megan Neighbor at 307-0579 or mneighbor@azstarnet.com and Andrea Rivera at arivera@azstarnet.com or 807-8430.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100414e63t0001v\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc52}{\*\bkmkend toc52}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 766 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 March 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Masked man sought in 14 local robberies\par \par \uc2 Police are looking for a man they say has committed at least 14 violent armed robberies since mid-February at a variety of Tucson- area businesses, including two Gadabout hair salons in the past week.\par \par \uc2 The Tucson Police Department, Pima County Sheriff's Department and Marana Police Department are working together on the investigation, according to a news release.\par \par \uc2 The robberies have occurred since Feb. 16 and include a variety of businesses, including gas stations, clothing stores, coffee shops, pizza parlors, juice bars, electronics stores, fast-food restaurants and video-game stores, said Sgt. Diana Lopez, a Tucson police spokeswoman.\par \par \uc2 The majority of the robberies occurred within city limits, Lopez said.\par \par \uc2 The robber, who has been masked each time, is described as 6 feet 3 inches, 20 to 25 years old, with brown hair and a thin build, according to the release.\par \par \uc2 Anyone with information is asked to call 911 or 88-CRIME.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Wrong-way driver killed on E. 22nd St.\par \par \uc2 A man driving the wrong way on the city's east side was killed Wednesday morning in a four-vehicle crash that shut down part of an intersection, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 Ambrose D'Arpino, 63, was eastbound in the westbound lanes of East 22nd Street about 8:30 a.m. when he crashed head-on into two vehicles just west of South Kolb Road, said Sgt. Diana Lopez, a Tucson Police Department spokeswoman.\par \par \uc2 Firefighters needed to use the Jaws of Life to rescue the drivers of two of the vehicles, said Capt. Tricia Tracy, a Tucson Fire Department spokeswoman.\par \par \uc2 Both drivers were taken to hospitals, where D'Arpino was pronounced dead, Lopez said.\par \par \uc2 The third driver had minor injuries, she said.\par \par \uc2 Traffic detectives determined D'Arpino was driving his 2007 truck in the eastbound lanes when he rear-ended a vehicle in the curb lane. His truck crossed the raised median and drove into oncoming traffic.\par \par \uc2 D'Arpino sideswiped a sport utility vehicle before colliding with a truck transporting several golf carts, said Sgt. Fabian Pacheco, a police spokesman.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen and Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 Drop house raided; 5 crossers in custody\par \par \uc2 Five people are in custody after Pima County sheriff's deputies discovered an \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  drop house on the northwest side.\par \par \uc2 At least five illegal immigrants were being held in a home in the 3400 block of West Green Trees Drive, near West Ina Road and North Camino de la Tierra, said Deputy Dawn Barkman, a Pima County Sheriff's Department spokeswoman.\par \par \uc2 Deputies were called to the home around 10 a.m. Wednesday after receiving 911 calls that people being held at the home had escaped and were seeking help from people in neighboring homes, Barkman said.\par \par \uc2 One of the five people being held was treated for minor injuries, she said.\par \par \uc2 A search of the area caused a temporary lockdown of Richardson Elementary School, which is across the street from the home, Barkman said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Nogales sergeant quits after Taser incident\par \par \uc2 A Nogales Police Department sergeant has resigned after being put on administrative leave for zapping a fellow officer in the crotch with a Taser.\par \par \uc2 Police Chief Jeffrey Scott Kirkham confirmed that Sgt. Sergio Bon resigned last week for the incident that occurred in mid-February at the Nogales police station. The victim was a lower-ranking police officer.\par \par \uc2 "There was apparently some animosity and some joking around," Kirkham said. "The sergeant became agitated, pulled out his Taser and hit him in the groin."\par \par \uc2 Both officers were on duty at the time, he said.\par \par \uc2 Bon had been with the department for 18 years; the victim has been with the department about a decade.\par \par \uc2 The victim officer did not file any charges, but Bon would likely have been terminated had he not submitted his resignation, Kirkham said.\par \par \uc2 Devlin Houser\par \par \uc2 Motorcyclist, 79, dies in crash with pickup\par \par \uc2 An 79-year-old man was killed Wednesday when his motorcycle collided with a pickup truck near Saguaro National Park West, according to the Pima County Sheriff's Department.\par \par \uc2 The crash occurred about 2:18 p.m. when the man, northbound on North Sandario Road near Golden Gate Road, drifted into the southbound lane before crashing into the truck, said Deputy Dawn Barkman, a sheriff's spokeswoman.\par \par \uc2 The pickup truck driver was taken to a hospital, Barkman said.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the city of Tucson, updated every morning with the previous day's data, at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100407e63p0001o\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSON\par {\*\bkmkstart toc53}{\*\bkmkend toc53}\b \uc2 No habra cargos contra agente de Border Patrol\b0\par\par\uc2 CASEY CROWE, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 589 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 March 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par 17\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Por Brady McCombs\par \par \uc2 La Estrella de Tucson\par \par \uc2 Los cargos contra un agente de la Patrulla Fronteriza que mato a un indocumentado en enero cerca de Douglas, seran retirados de acuerdo a la Fiscalia General del Condado Cochise.\par \par \uc2 Jorge Alfredo Solis Palma, de 28 anos, murio luego de que el agente Miguel Torres-Vasquez le disparara. Segun Doyle Johnstun, diputado del fiscal general del condado, los disparos eran legalmente justificados.\par \par \uc2 El incidente ocurrio el 4 de enero al Este de Douglas, de acuerdo a un reporte de la Oficina del Sheriff del Condado Cochise.\par \par \uc2 Los agentes estaban rastreando a tres personas cuando encontraron a Solis escondido debajo de un arbol.\par \par \uc2 El reporte dice que Solis se rehuso a salir, cosa que dio pie a una pelea. Solis le tiro piedras a los agentes y a un perro de la agencia mientras trataba de escapar.\par \par \uc2 Un agente le disparo dos veces. Solis murio en camino a un hospital en Tucson.\par \par \uc2 La oficina del sheriff investigo el incidente y entrego los resultados a la fiscalia, encargada de decidir si los cargos estaban justificados.\par \par \uc2 El 9 de marzo, dos meses despues del incidente, Johnstun expidio un comunicado de un parrafo explicando su decision.\par \par \uc2 "He examinado los reportes, fotos y videos", escribio Johnstun.\par \par \uc2 "Basado en la evidencia que estudie, he concluido que no hay evidencia fisica, forense o medica que contradiga lo que dijo sobre el incidente el agente de la Patrulla Fronteriza".\par \par \uc2 Torres-Vasquez regreso al trabajo luego de estar ausente tres dias, tal como requiere la agencia de cualquier agente que haga un disparo, dijo Omar Candelaria, vocero de la Patrulla Fronteriza.\par \par \uc2 El consul de Mexico en Douglas, Oscar Antonio de la Torre Amezcua, no estuvo disponible para comentar sobre la decision.\par \par \uc2 Contacta a Brady McCombs al 573-4213 o en bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 ENGLISH VERSION:\par \par \uc2 A Border Patrol agent who shot and killed an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  in January near Douglas won't be charged in the case, the Cochise County Attorney's Office announced last week.\par \par \uc2 The shooting of Jorge Alfredo Solis Palma, 28, by agent Miguel Torres-Vasquez was legally justified, found Doyle Johnstun, chief criminal deputy county attorney.\par \par \uc2 The shooting occurred the morning of Jan. 4 east of Douglas, according to a Cochise County Sheriff's Office report.\par \par \uc2 Agents were tracking three people when they found Solis hiding under a tree.\par \par \uc2 Solis refused to come out and a struggle began, the report says. Solis threw rocks at agents and an agency dog as he tried to flee.\par \par \uc2 An agent fired two shots at Solis, who died on the way to a Tucson hospital.\par \par \uc2 The sheriff's office investigated the incident and handed its findings over to the County Attorney's Office, which was tasked with deciding if charges were warranted. On Tuesday, two months after the shooting, Johnstun issued a one-paragraph statement explaining his decision.\par \par \uc2 "I have reviewed the reports, photographs and videos," Johnstun wrote.\par \par \uc2 "Based on the evidence reviewed, I have concluded that there is no physical, forensic or medical evidence which contradicts the Border Patrol agents' accounts of the shooting."\par \par \uc2 Torres-Vasquez returned to duty after he took the mandatory three days off that the agency requires for any agent involved in a shooting, said Border Patrol spokesman Omar Candelaria.\par \par \uc2 The Mexican consul in Douglas, Oscar Antonio de la Torre Amezcua, was not available for comment.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100402e63j0001y\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc54}{\*\bkmkend toc54}\b \uc2 Agent cleared in crosser's killing\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 395 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 March 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Jan. 4 shooting outside Douglas is ruled justified\par \par \uc2 A Border Patrol agent who shot and killed an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  in January near Douglas won't be charged in the case, the Cochise County Attorney's Office announced Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 The shooting of Jorge Alfredo Solis Palma, 28, by agent Miguel Torres-Vasquez was legally justified, found Doyle Johnstun, chief criminal deputy county attorney.\par \par \uc2 The shooting occurred the morning of Jan. 4 east of Douglas, according to a Cochise County Sheriff's Office report.\par \par \uc2 Agents were tracking three people when they found Solis hiding under a tree.\par \par \uc2 Solis, of Veracruz, Mexico, refused to come out and a struggle began, the report says. Solis threw rocks at agents and an agency dog as he tried to flee.\par \par \uc2 An agent fired two shots at Solis, who died on the way to a Tucson hospital.\par \par \uc2 The sheriff's office investigated the incident and handed its findings over to the County Attorney's Office, which was tasked with deciding if charges were warranted. On Tuesday, two months after the shooting, Johnstun issued a one-paragraph statement explaining his decision.\par \par \uc2 "I have reviewed the reports, photographs and videos," Johnstun wrote.\par \par \uc2 "Based on the evidence reviewed, I have concluded that there is no physical, forensic or medical evidence which contradicts the Border Patrol agents' accounts of the shooting."\par \par \uc2 Torres-Vasquez returned to duty after he took the mandatory three days off that the agency requires for any agent involved in a shooting, said Border Patrol spokesman Omar Candelaria.\par \par \uc2 The Mexican consul in Douglas, Oscar Antonio de la Torre Amezcua, was not available for comment.\par \par \uc2 Court records show that Solis had been arrested in 2005 by the Border Patrol and was later charged with a felony drug offense. On Sept. 8, 2005, near Douglas, agents found Solis and another man hiding in the brush near four large bags of marijuana that weighed 108 pounds.\par \par \uc2 Solis and the other man admitted they were hired in Mexico to transport the marijuana into the U.S. in exchange for transportation to Phoenix.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Read more border and immigration news online at azstarnet.com/news/local/border or at the Border Boletin blog at azstarnet.com/news/blogs/ border-boletin\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100327e63b00003\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSON\par {\*\bkmkstart toc55}{\*\bkmkend toc55}\b \uc2 Crea grupo bolsos con ropa encontrada en el desierto\b0\par\par\uc2 PHIL VILLARREAL, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,091 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 March 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par 22\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Buscan crear conciencia sobre muertes de inmigrantes\par \par \uc2 Por Devlin Houser\par \par \uc2 LA ESTRELLA\uc2  DE TUCSON\par \par \uc2 Para algunos, los pantalones de mezclilla, las mochilas y las camisas de franela que los inmigrantes indocumentados dejan en su camino al dirigirse hacia el Norte, no es mas que basura. Para Jody Ipsen, es materia prima.\par \par \uc2 "Se me ocurrio que podiamos hacer algo con estas telas", explico Ipsen.\par \par \uc2 Ella penso en esta idea de volver a usar los materiales mientras estaba recogiendo basura en el desierto con la organizacion Fronteras Compasivas (Humane Borders) en el 2007.\par \par \uc2 El ano pasado, ella formo el grupo Los Desconocidos, un grupo sin fines de lucro dedicado a promover la conciencia sobre las muertes de las personas indocumentadas a lo largo de la frontera, creando y vendiendo bolsas hechas con los materiales que se recogen en el desierto. El nombre en ingles de dicho grupo es "The Unknowns".\par \par \uc2 Ispen por lo general lleva los articulos que ella encuentra a un lavado de carros para lavarlos a chorro de presion antes de lavarlos en una lavanderia. Despues le pasa los articulos a una costurera quien cose a mano las bolsas.\par \par \uc2 Una bolsa luce el bolsillo de un pantalon de mezclilla en un costado, adornada con lo que parece ser una blusa de mujer con flores rosas.\par \par \uc2 Las bolsas, a las que llaman bolsos de Sonora, estan hechas, casi en su totalidad, con materiales que se han encontrado, donde los inmigrantes sin documentos dejan tambien botellas de agua, cepillos de dientes y panales. Las bolsas cuestan entre 10 y 65 dolares. El dinero que se recauda se utiliza para apoyar economicamente otros proyectos.\par \par \uc2 Ipsen tambien esta planeando la produccion de una serie de colchas con objetos encontrados, cada una de estas dedicada a una seccion de la frontera por cada ano fiscal. Cada parche de la colcha llevara el nombre de un inmigrante indocumentado que haya muerto, o si no se conoce el nombre, simplemente dira "Desconocido".\par \par \uc2 La primera colcha, la cual es un tributo a las muertes de los indocumentados en el Sector Tucson de la Patrulla Fronteriza por el ano fiscal 2004, se termino en diciembre. Algunos parches estan decorados con corazones, otros con cruces o dibujos de sahuaros. Desde el ano 2000, los cuerpos de casi 4 mil inmigrantes sin documentos se han encontrado a lo largo de la frontera Mexico- Estados Unidos.\par \par \uc2 La Escuela Preparatoria Catolica San Miguel es una de las tres preparatorias que han adoptado las colchas. La semana pasada, la escuela recibio 208 parches, cada uno de cuatro por cuatro pulgadas, los que estudiantes adornaran, comento Alma Mejia-Garcia, maestra de espanol y coordinadora del programa de inmersion fronteriza de la escuela.\par \par \uc2 Ipsen esta tratando de incitar mas conciencia por medio de los eventos de la comunidad. Ella estara presente en la Feria de la Paz (Peace Fair) y el Festival de Musica en Reid Park el sabado con bolsas y carteras a la venta, tambien materiales para decorar parches.\par \par \uc2 Ipsen de igual manera proveera parches sin decoracion con un sobre con su nombre, domicilio y sello postal incluido para aquellos quienes quieran decorar un parche en su casa.\par \par \uc2 Ipsen, de 49 anos de edad, quien tambien trabaja como escritora independiente dijo que en un mundo ideal, sus esfuerzos no serian necesarios.\par \par \uc2 "Espero que algun dia no tengamos que hacer otra colcha mas", sostuvo. "Pero se que no sucedera".\par \par \uc2 Devlin Houser es estudiante de periodismo en University of Arizona que realiza sus practicas profesionales en el Star. Contactalo al 573-4198 o en starapprentice@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 English version\par \par \uc2 To some, the jeans, backpacks and flannel shirts that illegal immigrants discard as they head north are nothing more than litter. To Jody Ipsen, they are raw materials.\par \par \uc2 "It occurred to me that we could do something with this fabric," Ipsen said.\par \par \uc2 She got the idea to reuse the materials while picking up litter in the desert with Humane Borders in 2007.\par \par \uc2 That year, she formed Los Desconocidos, a nonprofit group dedicated to promoting awareness of immigrant deaths along the border by crafting and selling bags made from cloth materials collected in the desert. The name of the group means "The Unknowns."\par \par \uc2 Ipsen often takes the items she finds to a carwash to power spray them before washing them at a laundromat. She then passes the clean articles to seamstresses, who hand-sew the bags. One bag sports a jeans pocket on the side, accented with what looks to be the pink floral pattern of a woman's blouse.\par \par \uc2 The bags, called Sonora sacks, are made almost entirely of materials found at lay-up sites, where illegal immigrants also leave behind other items such as water bottles, tin cans, toothbrushes and diapers. The bags cost between $10 and $65. Proceeds are used to fund more projects.\par \par \uc2 Ipsen also is orchestrating the production of a series of quilts with her found materials, each one dedicated to one section of the border for each fiscal year. Each patch will have the name of an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  who died, or if the name is unknown, simply "Desconocido."\par \par \uc2 The first quilt - which pays tribute to immigrant deaths in the Border Patrol's Tucson Sector for fiscal year 2004 - was finished in December. Some patches are decorated with hearts, others with crosses or drawings of saguaros. Since 2000, the bodies of nearly 4,000 illegal immigrants have been found along the U.S.-Mexico border.\par \par \uc2 San Miguel Catholic High School is one of three high schools that have adopted quilts. Last week, the school received 208 patches, each four inches by four inches, which students will adorn, said Alma Mejia-Garcia, a Spanish teacher and coordinator for the school's border-immersion program.\par \par \uc2 Ipsen is trying to raise more awareness through community events. She'll be at the Peace Fair and Music Festival at Reid Park on Saturday with bags and purses for sale, and materials to decorate patches. Ipsen also will provide blank patches with a self- addressed stamped envelope for those who want to decorate a patch at home.\par \par \uc2 Ipsen, 49, who also works as a freelance writer, said that in an ideal world, her efforts wouldn't be needed.\par \par \uc2 "I hope someday we won't have to make another quilt," she said. "But we will."\par \par \uc2 Devlin Houser is a University of Arizona journalism student who is apprenticing at the Star. Contact him at 573-4198 or at starapprentice@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100324e6350000o\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc56}{\*\bkmkend toc56}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 OPINIoN POR HUGO TORRES, LA ESTRELLA DE TUCSoN; ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 720 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 February 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Border agents rescue girl, 11, separated from crossers\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol agents rescued an 11-year-old Honduran girl Wednesday who had spent a night alone in the mountains south of Sierra Vista.\par \par \uc2 The girl became separated from a group of illegal immigrants Tuesday evening when agents approached the group near Hunter Canyon, located south of Sierra Vista, said Border Patrol spokeswoman Colleen Agle.\par \par \uc2 The girl's 8-year-old sister, who was among those apprehended, told agents that her sister was missing. The agency launched a search of the area.\par \par \uc2 Agents located the girl alone about 11:30 a.m., Agle said. She was in good condition despite spending the night alone. The smuggler who was leading the group also got away, Agle said.\par \par \uc2 Agents reunited the girl with her younger sister at the agency's Naco station and then transferred them to the Office of Refugee Resettlement in Phoenix, where arrangements will be made to reunite them with their parents or return them to Honduras. The Honduran consulate was also notified.\par \par \uc2 Brady McCombs\par \par \uc2 FBI believes pair robbed Marana bank, 11 others\par \par \uc2 A two-man crew has been holding up rural banks throughout the Southwest over the past five months, including one in Marana, according to the FBI.\par \par \uc2 The two, dubbed the "High Country Bandits" by the FBI, are believed to be responsible for at least 12 heists in Arizona, Colorado and New Mexico between September and earlier this month, according to an agency news release.\par \par \uc2 The Marana robbery happened Dec. 15 at the \uc2 Wells Fargo\uc2  branch on the corner of North Dove Mountain Boulevard and West Tangerine Road, according to the release.\par \par \uc2 The men are described as being in their 30s or 40s, with one between 5-foot-3 and 5-foot-6 and the other around 6 feet. They have been seen making their getaways in an all-terrain vehicle.\par \par \uc2 Anyone with information is encouraged to contact their nearest FBI office or call the Phoenix office at 1-602-279-5511.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Man faces up to 36 years for killing, robbery try\par \par \uc2 A 23-year-old man is facing somewhere between seven and 36 years in prison after pleading guilty Wednesday to manslaughter and attempted armed robbery, said Deputy Pima County Attorney Victoria Otto.\par \par \uc2 Steve Flores will be sentenced April 12 by Pima County Superior Court Judge Christopher Browning.\par \par \uc2 Flores and Raymond Martinez, 18, were attempting to rob the Grand Market in the 6200 block of South Sixth Avenue on Jan. 27, 2009, when an employee shot and killed Martinez, Tucson police said.\par \par \uc2 Flores fled, but later turned himself in. He was originally facing a first-degree murder charge under the felony murder rule, which allows prosecutors to charge people with murder if someone dies during the commission of certain felonies, including robbery.\par \par \uc2 Kim Smith\par \par \uc2 6 suffer smoke inhalation in mobile-home blaze\par \par \uc2 Six people, including five children, were taken to a hospital Thursday after a fire burned a mobile home south of Tucson.\par \par \uc2 An electrical issue in the bathroom was blamed for the blaze, which was reported just after 8 a.m. in the 9900 block of South Oak Canyon Lane, near South Nogales Highway and East Old Vail Connection Road, said Anne-Marie Braswell, a \uc2 Rural/Metro\uc2  Fire Department spokeswoman.\par \par \uc2 Five children and an adult at the home suffered smoke inhalation, Braswell said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Female crosser was victim of homicide, coroner says\par \par \uc2 A suspected \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  found dead alongside a highway near St. David was the victim of a homicide, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 The Cochise County Medical Examiner's Office determined that the woman, a 33-year-old Mexican national, died no more than 48 hours before she was found Feb. 8 in some brush near milepost 308 on Arizona 80, Cochise County Sheriff's Department spokeswoman Carol Capas said.\par \par \uc2 The woman, whose identity is not being released until after the Mexican consulate notifies her next of kin, is believed to have been dumped along the road and then dragged into the brush, Capas said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the City of Tucson, updated every morning with the previous day's data, at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100307e62j0002m\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc57}{\*\bkmkend toc57}\b \uc2 Shallow grave holds body of probable border crosser\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 262 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 February 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 A group of five humanitarians found the remains of a likely illegal border crosser Tuesday afternoon northwest of Nogales near the town of Ruby.\par \par \uc2 At 3 p.m., volunteers discovered the body in a shallow grave covered with rocks and adorned with a handmade cross, a No More Deaths press release says, adding that it was in a narrow canyon about two miles east of Ruby.\par \par \uc2 The volunteers were walking a known migrant trail conducting humanitarian patrols when they found the decomposing body. Ruby is about five miles north of the border, southeast of Arivaca.\par \par \uc2 The group called the Santa Cruz County Sheriff's Office, and deputies recovered the body. Officials estimated the man died six to seven months ago, the press release says.\par \par \uc2 The Pima County Medical Examiner's Office had not yet determined the cause of death, said Dr. Bruce Parks, chief medical examiner.\par \par \uc2 It is the third body believed to be that of an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  found this year in Santa Cruz County, Sheriff Tony Estrada said.\par \par \uc2 The bodies of 70 illegal immigrants have been found since Oct. 1 in Southern Arizona between New Mexico and Yuma County, a 40 percent increase from the 50 bodies found through the same dates in the previous year, the Arizona Daily Star's border-death database shows. The database is compiled using information from the Pima and Cochise County medical examiner's offices.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100303e62c00037\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc58}{\*\bkmkend toc58}\b \uc2 Law & Order\b0\par\par\uc2 KIM SMITH; BRIAN J PEDERSEN & BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 KIM SMITH, BRIAN J. PEDERSEN & BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 728 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 February 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Fired deputy gets 30 days for damage, extreme DUI\par \par \uc2 A former Pima County sheriff's deputy was sentenced to five years' probation and 30 days in jail Tuesday for criminal damage and extreme driving under the influence by Pima County Superior Court Judge Clark Munger.\par \par \uc2 The Tohono O'odham Police Department received a call from a passer-by just before 4 a.m. on Sept. 2, about a crash on Arizona 86 near Kitt Peak.\par \par \uc2 Police found a flipped-over Pima County Sheriff's Department Ford Expedition, a drunken Deputy Daniel Williams and a dead dog belonging to Williams.\par \par \uc2 Williams was indicted on criminal charges after blood tests showed his blood-alcohol level was 0.251, said Deputy Pima County Attorney Heather Lane.\par \par \uc2 The legal limit in Arizona is 0.08.\par \par \uc2 Williams was off duty and on his way to his girlfriend's house, Lane said.\par \par \uc2 Williams, who worked for the Sheriff's Department in the Ajo District, was fired within hours of the crash.\par \par \uc2 Kim Smith\par \par \uc2 Police identify man killed crossing west-side street\par \par \uc2 Tucson police have identified a pedestrian killed last week while crossing a west-side street.\par \par \uc2 John M. Wyatt, 41, died Feb. 2 when he was struck by a motorcycle on West Grant Road near North 14th Avenue, according to a news release issued by the Tucson Police Department.\par \par \uc2 Wyatt had stepped into the street in front of a motorcycle heading east on Grant, the release said.\par \par \uc2 Wyatt was pronounced dead at the scene, while the driver of the motorcycle was hospitalized with serious injuries, the release said.\par \par \uc2 No citations have been issued, police said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Dog brings home human skull, setting off search for body\par \par \uc2 A family dog's discovery has prompted Pima County sheriff's investigators to search an area northwest of Tucson for human remains.\par \par \uc2 The Sheriff's Department received a 911 call around 4:30 a.m. Tuesday by someone saying their dog had brought home a human skull, department spokeswoman Dawn Barkman said.\par \par \uc2 The skull, found near the 13200 block of West Orange Grove Road in Picture Rocks, was determined to have some unnatural defects, Barkman said.\par \par \uc2 The county Medical Examiner's Office was unable to determine a cause of death from the skull, she said.\par \par \uc2 As of 1 p.m. officers with the Sheriff's Department's search-and- rescue and homicide units had found no additional remains in the area where the skull was found, Barkman said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Cochise bicyclists find body, likely that of border crosser\par \par \uc2 A pair of bicyclists discovered the body of a woman in Cochise County who authorities believe was an illegal border crosser.\par \par \uc2 The cyclists spotted the body before noon on Monday north of Arizona 80 at milepost 308, between St. David and Tombstone, said Carol Capas, Cochise County Sheriff's Office spokeswoman.\par \par \uc2 The body was about 100 yards north of the road behind brush. It appeared the woman had been dragged there from the road.\par \par \uc2 No identification was found near the body, but investigators say the woman likely was an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 . The Mexican Consulate was notified, and her body was turned over to the Cochise County Medical Examiner's Office, Capas said.\par \par \uc2 The bodies of five illegal border crossers have been found this year in Cochise County, compared with three at this time last year, medical examiner's records show.\par \par \uc2 Brady McCombs\par \par \uc2 City police have $59.5K grant for seat-belt, car-seat safety\par \par \uc2 The Tucson Police Department has received a $59,500 grant from the Governor's Office of Highway Safety to help curb seat-belt and child-safety-restraint violations.\par \par \uc2 In addition to enhanced "occupant protection" enforcement, the grant will be used to provide education in classes and at public car- seat-check events, according to a department news release.\par \par \uc2 The enforcement, which will be effective through September, will concentrate on seat-belt and car-seat use, but since those violations are considered secondary, state law officers cannot stop a vehicle based solely on those violations, the release said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the city of Tucson, updated every morning with the previous day's data, at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100303e62a0000b\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc59}{\*\bkmkend toc59}\b \uc2 Law & Order Briefs\b0\par\par\uc2 KIM SMITH; BRIAN J PEDERSEN; MEGAN NEIGHBOR; STAFF AND WIRE   \par \uc2 KIM SMITH, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 933 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 February 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Setup of fatal drug deal gets man a 5-year term\par \par \uc2 A Tucson man who set up a drug deal that turned fatal was sentenced Monday in Pima County Superior Court to five years in prison.\par \par \uc2 Ahbram Avalos, 33, told police that he gave Rosendo Ortega, 20, a large amount of cocaine to sell and then set up a drug deal between Ortega and two sisters, Eva Macias, 36, and Alma Trinidad Huizar, 25.\par \par \uc2 Prosecutors said the sisters decided to rob Ortega instead, enlisted some help, and Ortega was shot to death when things went awry.\par \par \uc2 Last month, Avalos pleaded guilty to transportation of a narcotic drug for sale and was facing up to 12 1/2 years in prison.\par \par \uc2 Macias and Huizar pleaded guilty to negligent homicide, and Angelica Leon, 22, pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit robbery. All three women are awaiting sentencing.\par \par \uc2 The case against the shooting suspect, Michael Haro, is pending.\par \par \uc2 Kim Smith\par \par \uc2 Animal cruelty citation is related to 23 dogs\par \par \uc2 A Pima County man has been cited with animal cruelty involving the treatment of 23 dogs, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 Raymond Quintero, 34, was cited on suspicion of failure to provide appropriate food and water for dogs, according to a news release issued by the Animal Cruelty Taskforce of Southern Arizona.\par \par \uc2 Acting on an anonymous tip, investigators with the Pima Animal Care Center and the Pima County Sheriff's Department determined Quintero abandoned the dogs - mostly pit bulls and boxer-mix breeds - at a property south of the Tohono O'odham Nation San Xavier District, west of Sahuarita, two weeks ago without providing them food and water, the release said.\par \par \uc2 Jayne Cundy, public service coordinator with Animal Care, said the dogs sustained a number of injuries and appeared to have never been taken to a veterinarian for treatment.\par \par \uc2 Although all of the dogs were found alive at the home, the Pima Animal Care Center euthanized 19 of the dogs because of health problems and their aggression, Cundy said. The four remaining dogs are being treated at the Animal Care Center. It was not clear if they will be made available for adoption.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Man faces bank-heist, robbery-try counts\par \par \uc2 A Tucson man was arrested Monday on suspicion of bank robbery, police said.\par \par \uc2 Harry Leroy Hildenband, 36, was booked into the Pima County jail. He is facing armed-robbery and attempted-robbery charges, Tucson police said.\par \par \uc2 According to police, Hildenband entered the \uc2 Bank of America\uc2  office at 2091 E. Irvington Road on Jan. 7 and demanded money from a teller. The teller couldn't understand him, and Hildenband left without getting money, a news release said.\par \par \uc2 On Feb. 7, police said, Hildenband entered the Chase Bank branch at 2001 E. Irvington Road, and gave the teller with a note demanding money and implying that he was armed. He left with an undisclosed amount of money, the release said.\par \par \uc2 Megan Neighbor\par \par \uc2 121/2-year term given in home-invasion role\par \par \uc2 The last of five men who pleaded guilty to taking part in a home invasion last May was sentenced to 12 1/2 years in prison Monday.\par \par \uc2 Joaquin Manuel, 25, pleaded guilty to multiple counts of aggravated assault and one count of first-degree burglary in the case and was sentenced in Pima County Superior Court by Judge Jane Eikleberry, said Deputy Pima County Attorney Dan Nicolini.\par \par \uc2 Manuel and three other men kicked in the door of a home near East Valencia Road and South Nogales Highway, believing there was a large amount of marijuana there, police said.\par \par \uc2 When the men found no marijuana, they went to another home on the property and kicked in the door there. They found no marijuana in that home either, and they fled.\par \par \uc2 The men were arrested after their getaway driver crashed into a Domino's Pizza delivery driver while being chased by police.\par \par \uc2 The other men in the case are serving between 1 1/2 and 17 1/2 years in prison.\par \par \uc2 Kim Smith\par \par \uc2 Two border crossers found dead in S. Ariz.\par \par \uc2 The bodies of two illegal border crossers were found last weekend along Arizona's stretch of the U.S.-Mexico border.\par \par \uc2 On Friday, the Santa Cruz County Sheriff's Office received a call about a body near Patagonia in the Harshaw Road area, Sheriff Tony Estrada said. The body was in such a remote and rugged area that deputies were unable to reach the location until Saturday, Estrada said. The body was identified as that of a 41-year-old man from Nogales, Sonora, he said. The cause of death was unknown\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol agents recovered skeletal remains 30 miles northeast of Sasabe on Saturday, said agency spokesman Mario Escalante. It was unclear if the deceased was a man or a woman, he said.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, a soldier hiking in a wilderness area on Fort Huachuca's grounds discovered a woman's body Saturday.\par \par \uc2 Post Public Affairs Officer Angela Moncur said the soldier was hiking in Scheelite Canyon in the Huachuca Mountains when he came upon the body. She wasn't carrying identification. However, investigators found some documents written in Spanish that suggest the woman was an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Staff and wire reports\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the city of Tucson, updated every morning with the previous day's data, at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 The following fields overflowed:\par \par \uc2 BYLINE = KIM SMITH, BRIAN J. PEDERSEN, MEGAN NEIGHBOR AND STAFF AND WIRE, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100227e6290000r\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc60}{\*\bkmkend toc60}\b \uc2 Water jugs at heart of dispute; hostility threatens to boil over\b0\par\par\uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS   \par \uc2 BRADY MCCOMBS, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 1,469 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 February 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 RANCOROUS STANDOFF AT WILDLIFE REFUGE\par \par \uc2 ARIVACA - No More Deaths volunteers Steve Johnston and Peter Ragan walk briskly down a switchback trail with two plastic water jugs in each hand.\par \par \uc2 The men carry several more jugs inside their backpacks, and others hang from carabiners. When they reach a wash at the bottom of the hill, they set the jugs down in a bunch. On this cold and wet January day, Johnson, Ragan and Ayala Rahm leave 79 water jugs at six known \uc2 illegal-immigrant\uc2  trails southeast of Arivaca.\par \par \uc2 These 1-gallon plastic jugs are at the root of an ongoing and sometimes antagonistic standoff between Southern Arizona humanitarian groups and Buenos Aires National Wildlife Refuge officials.\par \par \uc2 Refuge officials have issued littering tickets to 15 volunteers from No More Deaths, Samaritans and Humane Borders over the last two years for putting out jugs on refuge land. Two have been convicted in federal court and 13 are scheduled for trial in April.\par \par \uc2 In a refuge already considered one of the most imperiled in the country because of the damage done by illegal border crossers and Border Patrol agents chasing them, refuge manager Mike Hawkes says he'll allow members of the group to put out water only if they use 5- gallon or larger jugs chained to trees at set locations.\par \par \uc2 "It's an eyesore. It's garbage," said Hawkes, pointing to shattered jugs on the ground. "This is a national wildlife refuge. This is supposed to be a special place. They are putting out tens of thousands of bottles in the environment every year."\par \par \uc2 Humanitarians say the water jugs save lives in the desert, where more than 1,500 illegal crossers have been found dead over the last decade. As their posters say, members of No More Deaths believe humanitarian aid is never a crime.\par \par \uc2 Members are fundamentally against restrictions on their work, and say the littering charges are a smokescreen to keep water from those who need it.\par \par \uc2 "This is a public health emergency," said Margo Cowan, a volunteer and member of No More Deaths. "That would be like, 'You see a house on fire and you go get permission to assist whoever is in the burning house.' We just don't think that's the appropriate way to address the situation."\par \par \uc2 Debates about the merits of leaving water in the desert are nothing new in Arizona, but the level of acrimony in this dispute is.\par \par \uc2 Bad blood\par \par \uc2 The two sides have met three times in six months and exchanged several letters, but they haven't been able to reach an agreement.\par \par \uc2 Cowan, a member of the negotiating committee representing No More Deaths and Samaritans, is optimistic the issue will be resolved in time to avoid the April trial scheduled for the 13 people cited in July. The trial already has been pushed back twice.\par \par \uc2 "We are set on fixing this. It's got to get fixed," Cowan said. "We have no interest in being entangled in a legal context with the United States. We don't want to waste our time. Our only interest is saving lives and reducing suffering."\par \par \uc2 But Hawkes, who became refuge manager in September 2008 after spending six years at the Kauai National Wildlife Refuge Complex in Hawaii, isn't so sure.\par \par \uc2 "We are trying to work with them, but they have been less than cooperative," said Hawkes, who plans to retire at the end of the year. "I think they are intent on maintaining an adversarial relationship because of the PR they get from it."\par \par \uc2 The accusation is one of several scathing opinions Hawkes has about the humanitarian groups.\par \par \uc2 He calls No More Deaths an anti-government organization whose goal is to make sure every illegal border crosser has a safe and comfortable trip. Members want to leave water in the refuge - as opposed to other areas with more deaths - because the refuge is close and convenient from Tucson and Green Valley, he said.\par \par \uc2 Hawkes points out that only two bodies were found in the refuge in fiscal 2009.\par \par \uc2 He said the refuge is doing enough to keep illegal border crossers safe by coordinating with Border Patrol agents and with the placement of Border Patrol rescue beacons and Humane Borders water tanks. He also said there are plenty of water sources within the refuge, including cow tanks.\par \par \uc2 "That will save their life," Hawkes said. "It might make them sick. It might give them kidney failure or something later down the road. But it will save their life for the time being until they get to a road or something and get rescued."\par \par \uc2 Cowan and fellow negotiating team member Gene Lefebvre said the group is trying to avoid demonizing Hawkes, but they disagree with many of his claims.\par \par \uc2 There's not as much water in the refuge as he says, they maintain. Many of the wells he points out no longer work, they say, and the cow tanks are so dirty the water would make a person sick.\par \par \uc2 The bodies of seven border crossers have been found within the refuge since 2007, Hawkes said.\par \par \uc2 But hundreds have been found in the last decade in the Altar Valley, where the refuge is located, the Arizona Daily Star's border death database shows.\par \par \uc2 Last year was particularly deadly in the Border Patrol's Tucson Sector, which covers New Mexico to Yuma County. The bodies of 213 illegal border crossers were discovered in fiscal 2009, the third- deadliest year ever.\par \par \uc2 Cowan and Lefebvre call it disingenuous for Hawkes to cite litter as the reason for his opposition. Group members pick up trash during patrols and recycle jugs they find. The group offered to pick up twice the trash it leaves in exchange for being able to put out water, but Hawkes rejected the idea.\par \par \uc2 "If they really cared about the trash, they would snap at the idea of hundreds, perhaps even thousands of people, every year volunteering through No More Deaths to pick up trash," Cowan said.\par \par \uc2 Speaking on her own and not as a representative of No More Deaths, Cowan said: "Hawkes and his crew want to prevent water from getting into the hands of women and children and men crossing the desert. I think that's a personal view of his, and I don't think it's shared by the secretary. He's the secretary's problem. He's not our problem."\par \par \uc2 Department of Interior Secretary Ken Salazar, who met with No More Deaths representatives last summer, recognizes the urgent need to find a solution that will allow the group to continue its work while complying with federal laws, press secretary Kendra Barkoff said in an e-mail.\par \par \uc2 5-gallon jugs\par \par \uc2 When humanitarians meet later this month with Hawkes and refuge officials, the negotiations will likely turn to the size of the jugs.\par \par \uc2 Members of No More Deaths don't like the 5-gallon idea because they say most border crossers dump their jugs when empty, meaning they wouldn't have jugs to refill when they reach the water station, Cowan said. The group leaves out 1-gallon jugs so people can carry water north.\par \par \uc2 That's exactly Hawkes' concern: The No More Deaths jugs compound the jugs already left by illegal immigrants. He believes the 5- gallon solution would greatly reduce the trash.\par \par \uc2 That's why he rejected a permit application from humanitarians in October that asked to set out 1-gallon jugs.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, No More Deaths members say they'll keep leaving water in the refuge. Hawkes says they'll be ticketed if caught.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Go online to azstarnet.com/news/ local/border for more border and immigration news.\par \par \uc2 Timeline\par \par \uc2 A look at humanitarian groups' standoff with officials at Buenos Aires National Wildlife Refuge.\par \par \uc2 * Summer 2007: No More Deaths and Samaritans begin leaving water in the refuge.\par \par \uc2 * Feb. 22, 2008: Dan Millis is cited for littering.\par \par \uc2 * September 2008: Mike Hawkes becomes refuge manager.\par \par \uc2 * Sept. 22 2008: Millis is convicted of littering but gets a suspended sentence.\par \par \uc2 * Dec. 4, 2008: Walt Staton is cited for littering.\par \par \uc2 * June 3, 2009: Staton is found guilty of knowingly littering in a national wildlife refuge.\par \par \uc2 * July 9, 2009: Upset that Hawkes doesn't agree to a meeting, volunteers from No More Deaths, Samaritans and Humane Borders protest by leaving water in the refuge. Thirteen people are cited for littering.\par \par \uc2 * Aug. 11, 2009: Staton is sentenced to one year of unsupervised probation.\par \par \uc2 * March 2, 2010: The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals is scheduled to hear arguments in Millis' appeal.\par \par \uc2 * April 6, 2010: Trials are scheduled to begin for the 13 people cited in July 2009.\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100223e62700022\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc61}{\*\bkmkend toc61}\b \uc2 Law and Order\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 790 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 January 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Woman is stabbed near east-side eatery\par \par \uc2 A woman suffered serious stabs wounds to her arms and face when she was attacked by a man as she got into her car at an east-side Peter Piper Pizza.\par \par \uc2 The incident occurred at about 2:40 p.m. outside the restaurant, near Kolb Road and East Broadway, said Sgt. Fabian Pacheco, a Tucson Police Department spokesman.\par \par \uc2 The woman was coming out of the restaurant when a man confronted her with a knife and forced his way into the passenger side of her car, Pacheco said.\par \par \uc2 He ordered the woman to drive away and put his foot on her accelerator pedal as they left the parking lot, he said.\par \par \uc2 The woman put her foot on the brake and attempted to put the car in park, but instead switched the vehicle into reverse, he said.\par \par \uc2 She then pressed on the gas pedal, causing the car to go backward and crash into a chain-link fence, he said.\par \par \uc2 The man then stabbed the woman in her forearms and above her left eye, he said. She suffered serious but non-life-threatening injuries.\par \par \uc2 The man fled in a white shirt that was covered in blood. He also was wearing denim jeans.\par \par \uc2 The assailant is about 6 feet tall and weighs between 180 and 200 pounds. He has a bald or shaved head.\par \par \uc2 Anyone with information is asked to call 911 or 88-CRIME.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 Man shot in the head outside bar has died\par \par \uc2 A man who was shot after he tried to break up a fight this week at an east-side bar died Wednesday from his injuries, police said.\par \par \uc2 Matthew Vital, 26, tried to stop a fight early Tuesday between two women at the Hideout Sports Bar, 1110 S. Sherwood Village Drive, when he was shot in the head by another man, said Sgt. Fabian Pacheco, a Tucson Police Department spokesman.\par \par \uc2 The fight broke out in the parking lot after the bar closed, Pacheco said.\par \par \uc2 A second man who was standing nearby was shot in the upper torso, but his wound was not considered life-threatening, he said.\par \par \uc2 Gang detectives were investigating the incident because Vital had known gang ties, he said.\par \par \uc2 No arrests had been made.\par \par \uc2 Anyone with information is asked to call 911 or 88-CRIME.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 Police arrest 4, seek 2 on meth-ring charges\par \par \uc2 Four men were arrested Wednesday on suspicion of running a criminal enterprise involving methamphetamine, police said.\par \par \uc2 Detectives from the Counter Narcotics Alliance obtained warrants and began arresting suspects early Wednesday, said Sgt. Fabian Pacheco, a Tucson Police Department spokesman.\par \par \uc2 Ramon Enrique McCormick, 37, Jose Fernando McCormick, 36, Steve Allen George, 36, and Francisco Martinez, 25 are all facing numerous felony charges, Pacheco said.\par \par \uc2 Those charges range from operating a criminal enterprise and money laundering to possession of dangerous drugs, he said. Jose McCormick is facing nine felony charges.\par \par \uc2 Authorities are still looking for two additional suspects: Jesus Octavio McCormick, 32, and Paul Vidal Soto, 22.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 2 cats are missing after electrical fire\par \par \uc2 A man escaped injury, but his two cats were still unaccounted for after a morning fire on Tucson's south side.\par \par \uc2 The fire was reported at 1:24 a.m. in the 2400 block of South Tucson Boulevard, Tucson Fire Department spokeswoman Tricia Tracy said.\par \par \uc2 When firefighters arrived at 1:31 a.m., they found the home more than half-involved in flames, Tracy said. Nine units and 23 firefighters managed to save the other half of the home, limiting the damage to about $100,000, she said.\par \par \uc2 The fire was blamed on an electrical short caused by a heating blanket that had been turned off but was still plugged in to the wall with an extension cord, Tracy said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol recovers body of illegal entrant\par \par \uc2 U.S. Border Patrol agents recovered the body of an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  on Tuesday night in a canyon near Nogales. They said he appeared to have died from a heart attack.\par \par \uc2 At about 9 p.m. Tuesday, a man flagged down Border Patrol agents and told them that his uncle was in distress, said Omar Candelaria, Border Patrol Tucson Sector spokesman.\par \par \uc2 The nephew led agents to a canyon close to the border, where they found the body of the man, who was estimated to be 25 to 28 years old, Candelaria said. The canyon is between the Mariposa Port of Entry, west of Nogales, and the Dennis DeConcini port, in downtown Nogales.\par \par \uc2 Brady McCombs\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the city of Tucson, updated every morning with the previous day's data, at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100209e61l0002f\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc62}{\*\bkmkend toc62}\b \uc2 Law and Order\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 287 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 January 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Officials now unsure death was a suicide\par \par \uc2 Authorities have backed off calling the Saturday shooting death of a man at a Three Points rifle range a suicide.\par \par \uc2 Autopsy results will help determine the circumstances behind the death of Aaron Carter, 28, who was shot and killed at the Tucson Rifle Club, 18300 W. Ajo Way, said Dawn Barkman, a Pima County Sheriff's Department spokeswoman.\par \par \uc2 Authorities had originally said the death was a suicide, but it is now being labeled as undetermined, Barkman said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 2 agencies receive anti-DUI grants\par \par \uc2 Two local law enforcement agencies have received state grants to aid in their efforts at curbing drunken driving.\par \par \uc2 The Pima County Sheriff's Department and the Nogales Police Department were awarded grants from the Governor's Office of Highway Safety, according to news releases issued by the agencies.\par \par \uc2 Pima County received two grants totaling about $181,000, while Nogales was given just under $69,000.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Authorities still seek slain crosser's kin\par \par \uc2 The Mexican government is still trying to locate the family of an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  who was shot and killed by a Border Patrol agent near Douglas Jan. 4.\par \par \uc2 Officials have identified the victim as Jorge Alfredo Solis Palma, 28, but don't know where he was from in Mexico, said Socorro Cordova, spokeswoman for the Mexican consulates in Arizona.\par \par \uc2 They are looking for family members to coordinate the return of Solis' body.\par \par \uc2 Solis was shot twice by a Border Patrol agent near Douglas after he threw rocks at the agent and a patrol dog, according to a press release from the Cochise County Sheriff's Office.\par \par \uc2 Staff report\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100203e61f00049\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc63}{\*\bkmkend toc63}\b \uc2 Man posing as illegal migrant arrested, jailed in '08 slaying\b0\par\par\uc2 BRIAN J PEDERSEN   \par \uc2 BRIAN J. PEDERSEN, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 291 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 January 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 A 32-year-old man wanted in connection with a 2008 south-side homicide has been arrested after trying to pass himself off as an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , authorities said.\par \par \uc2 Daniel N. Taddey was detained by U.S. Border Patrol agents on Thursday in the Nogales area, a Border Patrol news release said.\par \par \uc2 He is the fifth person arrested in the Nov. 13, 2008, death of Frank T. Gonzales, 35, who was found shot to death in the 700 block of East 35th Street, said Sgt. Diana Lopez, a Tucson Police Department spokeswoman.\par \par \uc2 Taddey initially told Border Patrol agents he was an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  but later acknowledged he is a U.S. citizen. Officials then determined he had a warrant for first-degree murder, the Border Patrol said.\par \par \uc2 He was turned over to the Tucson Police Department, which booked him into the Pima County jail on one count each of suspicion of first-degree murder and suspicion of kidnapping, Lopez said.\par \par \uc2 Two of Taddey's relatives - 33-year-old Carlos Taddey and 25- year-old Jose Taddey - were arrested in 2008 and are awaiting trial on first-degree murder and kidnapping charges, as is 30-year-old Gilbert Gonzalez, who was arrested July 30, court and police records show.\par \par \uc2 A fifth suspect, 35-year-old Ivan Chaparro-Garcia, pleaded guilty to hindering prosecution and was sentenced in October to 3 1/2 years in prison, court records show.\par \par \uc2 Chaparro-Garcia told police he helped get rid of bloody blankets and clothing associated with Gonzales' murder, court documents show.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Brian J. Pedersen at 573-4224 or bjp@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100202e61900040\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc64}{\*\bkmkend toc64}\b \uc2 Law and Order\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 777 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 January 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Inmate kills himself in Pima County jail\par \par \uc2 Alfredo Reatiga, who was booked into the Pima County jail Dec. 7 for suspicion of aggravated assault and attempted first-degree murder, committed suicide Friday, officials said.\par \par \uc2 Correction officers found Reatiga, 25, hanged in his jail cell, said Deputy Dawn M. Barkman, a spokeswoman for the Pima County Sheriff's Department.\par \par \uc2 Officers administered cardiopulmonary resuscitation as soon as Reatiga was found about 1 p.m., before Tucson Fire Department paramedics arrived, Barkman said.\par \par \uc2 Sheriff's homicide detectives are investigating.\par \par \uc2 Carmen Duarte\par \par \uc2 Man takes plea deal to avoid murder charge\par \par \uc2 One of five people facing a first-degree murder charge in the death of an alleged drug dealer agreed to plead guilty to a drug charge Friday in exchange for the dismissal of the murder charge.\par \par \uc2 Ahbram Avalos, 33, will serve between three and 12 1/2 years in prison after pleading guilty in Pima County Superior Court to transportation of a narcotic drug for sale.\par \par \uc2 Rosendo Ortega, 20, was shot to death in a shopping center parking lot in the 500 block of West Ajo Way on July 24.\par \par \uc2 Avalos, 33, told police he supplied Ortega with a large amount of cocaine to sell and then coordinated a drug transaction between Ortega, Eva Macias, 36, and her sister, Alma Huizar, 24, according to court documents.\par \par \uc2 Instead of buying the drugs, however, court documents indicate Marcias decided to rob Ortega of his money and drugs because she owed $33,000 on a truck she owned that had been stolen by another drug dealer employed by Avalos.\par \par \uc2 Macias, Huizar, Michael Haro, 20, and Angelica Leon, 21, met with Ortega at the shopping center and Haro shot him, according to court records.\par \par \uc2 When police found Ortega dead they also found about 97 grams of cocaine in his car, individually packaged for sale.\par \par \uc2 Avalos told police Ortega called him from the meeting place and said he was being robbed at gunpoint.\par \par \uc2 Avalos will be sentenced Feb. 8.\par \par \uc2 The other defendants are awaiting trial.\par \par \uc2 Kim Smith\par \par \uc2 Body discovered east of Douglas\par \par \uc2 The body of a suspected \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  was found Thursday morning by U.S. Border Patrol agents outside Douglas.\par \par \uc2 Miguel Angel Rivera-Acosta was found alongside westbound Arizona 80 east of Douglas, according to a news release issued by the Cochise County Sheriff's Office.\par \par \uc2 Cause of death is unknown pending an autopsy, but no signs of foul play were found, the release said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 6 captured entrants have sex convictions\par \par \uc2 At least six illegal immigrants apprehended this week by U.S. Border Patrol agents in Southern Arizona were found to have past sex- crime convictions, the agency said.\par \par \uc2 Three caught Wednesday and Thursday south and west of Tucson were found to have convictions for sex crimes against children, according to a Border Patrol news release.\par \par \uc2 Roughly 20 percent of illegal immigrants caught by Border Patrol during the 2009 fiscal year had convictions for crimes such as rape, child molestation or murder, according to the release.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 20 Mexican men face US drug charges\par \par \uc2 Twenty Mexican men caught carrying more than 2,700 pounds of marijuana on the Tohono O'odham Nation last month were indicted Wednesday on federal drug-smuggling charges.\par \par \uc2 The men, who range in age from 18 to 44, were arrested Dec. 9 after U.S. Border Patrol agents used both air and ground support to capture them near Pia Oik Village, about 30 miles east of the U.S.- Mexico border at Lukeville, according to documents filed in U.S. District Court in Tucson.\par \par \uc2 The group was found carrying bundles of marijuana totalling about 2,760 pounds, court records show. Each man is scheduled to be arraigned Jan. 21.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Willcox man indicted in child smuggling\par \par \uc2 A 45-year-old Willcox man was indicted Wednesday on federal child- smuggling charges.\par \par \uc2 Jesus Hielo was arrested Dec. 9 at the Douglas Port of Entry when he attempted to drive into the country with an 8-year-old girl and 5- year-old boy he claimed were his stepchildren, according to documents filed in U.S. District Court.\par \par \uc2 Hielo gave customs officials birth certificates for the children that listed their ages as 7 and 2, respectively, but after being interrogated Hielo admitted he was to be paid $2,000 to bring the children into the U.S., court records show.\par \par \uc2 Hielo is scheduled to be arraigned Jan. 21.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the city of Tucson, updated every morning with the previous day's data, at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100202e6190003z\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc65}{\*\bkmkend toc65}\b \uc2 Law and Order\b0\par\par\uc2 ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 602 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 January 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Manager is shot at Miracle Mile club\par \par \uc2 A manager at a north-side strip club was shot in the ankle Wednesday night, police said.\par \par \uc2 The shooting was reported just before 10 p.m. at TD's Show Club West, 749 W. Miracle Mile, said Sgt. Fabian Pacheco, a Tucson Police Department spokesman.\par \par \uc2 Police were still looking for the shooter late Wednesday, Pacheco said.\par \par \uc2 Investigators also were trying to determine the cause of the shooting, he said.\par \par \uc2 Jamar Younger\par \par \uc2 Mexico identifies man slain by border agent\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  shot to death by a U.S. Border Patrol agent Monday was identified by the Mexican government as Jorge Alfredo Solis Palma.\par \par \uc2 The Mexican Consulate in Douglas was working to locate his family in Mexico and send his body back home, a news release said.\par \par \uc2 Although the body was identified, authorities didn't specify where he was from.\par \par \uc2 Solis Palma, 28, was fatally shot after he threw rocks at an agent and a patrol dog, the Cochise County Sheriff's Office said Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 He was one of several people agents had been following near Douglas, authorities said. The dog found Solis Palma hiding under a tree, and a struggle ensued after he refused to come out.\par \par \uc2 Mariana Alvarado\par \par \uc2 Murder count filed in New Year's death\par \par \uc2 Tucson police arrested a 25-year-old man wanted in connection with a New Year's Day homicide.\par \par \uc2 David A. Gorosave has been booked into the Pima County jail on eight counts, including suspicion of first-degree murder, suspicion of attempted first-degree murder, and two counts of drive-by shooting, according to a news release issued by the Tucson Police Department.\par \par \uc2 Manuel DeJesus Nunley, 24, was shot to death around 12:30 a.m. Friday in the 8500 block of East Pantano Crossing, near East Golf Links Road and South Camino Seco.\par \par \uc2 Nunley and his girlfriend were in a minivan headed to a house party when Nunley got into an argument with a man in another vehicle, police said. The man in the other vehicle shot Nunley and his girlfriend, who suffered a non-life-threatening wound in her leg, police said.\par \par \uc2 Nunley was wanted by police in connection with a September home invasion, police said.\par \par \uc2 Brian J. Pedersen\par \par \uc2 Burglar who led chase given 51/2-year term\par \par \uc2 A 36-year-old Tucson burglar who led officers on a 90-minute chase last September was sentenced to 5 1/2 years in prison Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Last September, Tucson police received a report about a burglary in the 3100 block of North Avenida del Clarin. Officers set up a perimeter near East Fort Lowell Road and North Columbus Boulevard, and a police helicopter was called to help.\par \par \uc2 When police spotted the burglar, he was on foot, jumping walls, fences and roofs as he tried to escape.\par \par \uc2 Ninety minutes later, police caught the man, who was later identified as Lewis William Parks, at North Alvernon Way and East Blacklidge Drive.\par \par \uc2 Parks pleaded guilty to second-degree burglary as part of a plea agreement that guaranteed he would serve between 4 1/2 years and 7 1/ 2 years in prison.\par \par \uc2 On Wednesday, Deputy Pima County Attorney Marne Jones asked Judge Charles Sabalos of Pima County Superior Court to send Parks to prison for the maximum sentence, citing Parks' lengthy criminal history.\par \par \uc2 Assistant County Public Defender Michael Mussman asked for the minimum sentence.\par \par \uc2 Kim Smith\par \par \uc2 On StarNet: Find an interactive map of reported crimes in the city of Tucson, updated every morning with the previous day's data, at go.azstarnet.com/crime\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100202e6170001q\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 TUCSON/REGION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc66}{\*\bkmkend toc66}\b \uc2 Border agents had been following group near Douglas before migrant was killed\b0\par\par\uc2 JAMAR YOUNGER   \par \uc2 JAMAR YOUNGER, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 405 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 January 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Rock tosser ignored repeated commands to stop, officials say\par \par \uc2 An \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  shot to death by a U.S. Border Patrol agent Monday was one of several people agents had been following near Douglas, authorities said.\par \par \uc2 The 28-year-old man was shot and killed after he "aggressively" threw rocks at an agent and a patrol dog, according to a Cochise County Sheriff's Department press release.\par \par \uc2 At the time, agents were in an area known as Bay Acres, northeast of Douglas, following the group and tracked three people to a remote area before they lost sight of them.\par \par \uc2 A citizen later told the agents that a man had been walking south from the area, which prompted the agents to use a dog to track him.\par \par \uc2 The dog found the man hiding under a tree, and a struggle ensued after he refused to come out. The man threw rocks before running away.\par \par \uc2 More agents joined the chase, but the man refused to comply with commands and kept throwing rocks.\par \par \uc2 An agent fired two shots after the man tried to assault the agent. The man died while he was being taken by helicopter to a Tucson hospital.\par \par \uc2 The agent was taken to a hospital with injuries suffered during the incident. The dog was treated by a veterinarian after getting hit by a rock.\par \par \uc2 The man who was killed is a Mexican national, but officials weren't sure what part of the country he was from. They did not release his name.\par \par \uc2 Neither did the Border Patrol release the name of the agent who shot the man. The officer was placed on three days' administrative leave, according to the agency.\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol spokesman Omar Candelaria said attacks on agents in the Tucson Sector have nearly tripled compared with the same time last year.\par \par \uc2 Agents have been assaulted 141 times since October, the start of the fiscal year, compared with 53 attacks during the same period last year, he said.\par \par \uc2 The increased use of technology, hiring of more agents and other factors are likely making it tougher for smugglers and causing them to be more aggressive, he said.\par \par \uc2 "The smuggling organizations are getting more frustrated with the success the Border Patrol is having," he said.\par \par \uc2 Contact reporter Jamar Younger at 573-4115 or jyounger@azstarnet.com\par \par \uc2 Document TUCS000020100202e61600008\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 NEWS\par {\*\bkmkstart toc67}{\*\bkmkend toc67}\b \uc2 Border agent kills rock thrower\b0\par\par\uc2 MEGAN NEIGHBOR   \par \uc2 MEGAN NEIGHBOR, ARIZONA DAILY STAR\par \uc2 231 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 January 2010\par \uc2 The Arizona Daily Star\par \uc2 TUCS\par \uc2 FINAL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Arizona Daily Star. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Illegal immigrant\uc2  dies in transport from Douglas area\par \par \uc2 A U.S. Border Patrol agent shot and killed an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  after being "assaulted with rocks" near the border Monday morning, an official with the agency said.\par \par \uc2 Border Patrol spokesman Omar Candelaria said the agent, who was on foot, encountered the rock-throwing man on the Arizona side of the border just east of Douglas in a remote area called "D" Hill.\par \par \uc2 After being struck by rocks, the agent fired at the man. The shooting happened a little after 8 a.m.\par \par \uc2 The man, who was flown from the site, di